<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coke Unveils New Ad Campaign  </HEADLINE>
    By SKIP WOLLENBERG AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Coca-Cola is betting that its "Enjoy" advertising theme
will put some pop in sales of its top-selling flagship soft drink even though
rival Pepsi is already singing about "The Joy of Cola" in its ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Coca-Cola Co., the world's biggest soft drink concern, unveiled its new
slogan along with 10 TV commercials and 19 radio ads for its bottlers on
Wednesday, saying the new approach will help it reconnect with consumers.
</P>
<P>
	   At first glance, the "Coca-Cola. Enjoy" theme may appear to echo the less
specific "Joy of Cola" line that its biggest U.S. rival, Pepsi-Cola Co.,
introduced less than a year ago for its flagship Pepsi brand.
</P>
<P>
	   But Ian Rowden, advertising director for Atlanta-based Coke, said there is
little chance consumers will confuse the messages.
</P>
<P>
	   "They come from totally different perspectives," he said in discussing the
new ads earlier this week. "Ours is all about our ability to connect with
people. It's an invitation to people to enjoy what they do."
</P>
<P>
	   Coke has periodically used "enjoy" on its packaging, but Coke officials said
this is the first time it has been used as the brand's ad theme.
</P>
<P>
	   Television and radio commercials in the new campaign begin appearing Monday
in the United States and are already running in some overseas markets. Coca-Cola
declines to say how much it is spending to run the ads.
</P>
<P>
	   The new theme replaces the "Always Coca-Cola" campaign which has been
appearing since 1993. Coke executives said that campaign has worked well but it
was time for a change.
</P>
<P>
	   Sales of the flagship Coca-Cola brand were up an average 6.7 percent a year
worldwide in the first six years of the "Always" campaign but sales growth
slowed last year, according to Coke spokesman Bob Bertini.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the magnitude of the slowdown has not yet been disclosed but
attributed it to the impact of economic conditions overseas, the recall of
Coca-Cola products in France and Belgium due to a health scare, and to price
competition in the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   In the United States, Coca-Cola Classic accounted for 20.6 percent of
carbonated soft drink sales in the United States in 1998, well ahead of the
second-place Pepsi at 14.2 percent, according to figures from the trade
publication Beverage Digest. The 1999 figures aren't in yet.
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, Coke's share was the same in 1998 as a year earlier and down
from 20.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   The theme change is part of a broader marketing overhaul that has included a
makeover of the imagery used in the Coca-Cola logo and packaging which now shows
the cap popping off and the drink splashing out.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles Frenette, Coca-Cola's chief marketing officer, said the changes are
designed to point up the unique sensory experience of drinking a Coke -- the
bubbles, the fragrance and the chill.
</P>
<P>
	   That is a recurring theme in the 10 new TV ads as well.
</P>
<P>
	   In one ad, a man steps up to a cafe bar and the house parrot perched nearby
mimics the sound of a bottle being opened, poured and gulped. The man grows
thirstier but before he can order, the waitress shows up with a bottle of
Coca-Cola. "Enjoy," the parrot cackles.
</P>
<P>
	   In another ad, three boys in a dusty village in Morocco wait for a delivery
of Coca-Cola and wonder how it will taste.
</P>
<P>
	   "My father says it's just like kissing a girl," one boy says. After a truck
arrives, the oldest boy takes a bottle out of a cooler and drinks.
</P>
<P>
	   "Is it like kissing a girl?" the younger boys ask their 12- or 13-year-old
friend. The older boy replies, "I hope so."
</P>
<P>
	   Dancers appear to be performing inside a bubbly bottle of Coke in another
ad, energetically moving through tap, hip-hop, merengue and modern dance
routines. Teens dive down a waterfall to retrieve Coke bottles buried in the
frothy water below in another ad.
</P>
<P>
	   Coca-Cola also has developed 19 radio ads which feature multiple
interpretations -- mainstream, urban, Tejano, reggae, country and others -- of a
melody written for the new campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Four of the TV ads including the one with the parrot and the one with the
three boys were created by the agency Leo Burnett while the remaining six come
from Edge Creative, which was responsible the much of the "Always" campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The polar bears who first appeared in the "Always" campaign have survived
the change in ad theme -- the parent bears roust two cubs to sit on the snowy
tundra and watch fireworks while sipping Coca-Cola in the new ad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
