<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> H&AMP;R Block Launches Expansion  </HEADLINE>
    By DANA FIELDS AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- H&AMP;R Block Inc. is hoping an aggressive new
advertising campaign will convince its customers that it is more than just a tax
preparation company.
</P>
<P>
	   The $100 million campaign and a new Refund Rewards program that debuted
Wednesday also are designed to help Block spread its profits beyond tax season.
The Kansas City company typically has three money-losing quarters a year.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our core business is as strong as ever, but it's seasonally oriented, and
the rest of the year we have this wonderful distribution system of 9,000 offices
we really don't use efficiently," chief executive Frank Salizzoni said from New
York, where Block executives were deployed Wednesday to call attention to the
new campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Block has been on a three-year buying spree of accounting and investment
firms, including discount brokerage Olde Financial Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Block aired the first of 21 new commercials on Tuesday night's edition of
ABC's popular "Who Wants to Be A Millionaire," then announced Wednesday the
opening of 94 Block Financial Centers around the country. Some of the centers --
more of which will open in the coming year -- formerly housed Olde Financial
offices, others were Block Tax offices.
</P>
<P>
	   The company, with revenue of $1.3 billion last year, hopes to nudge some of
its 16.5 million tax preparation customers toward its other products, including
financial planning and software.
</P>
<P>
	   Customers at the Block Financial Centers will be able to talk not only with
tax preparers but with brokers and financial planners, Salizzoni said.
</P>
<P>
	   The company makes no secret of its target clients. It commissioned a Gallup
poll, released Wednesday, that found 48 percent of households with more than
$20,000 in income don't have financial plans. Two-thirds of that group don't
feel they save or invest enough -- and seven out of 10 have "some" or "great"
concern about paying for retirement.
</P>
<P>
	   "These clients also indicate they look upon H&AMP;R Block as a valued and
trusted final adviser and they would love to be able to get more than just tax
advice from Block," said analyst Michael Millman of Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
	   Offering financial advice in the unintimidating setting of a Block office
"makes Block's tax business much more attractive to clients, and makes
individual clients more profitable for the company," Millman said.
</P>
<P>
	   The fresh blast of publicity for Block's Internet services -- with links to
insurance and banking -- is also likely to pay off, said Michael Hodes, an
analyst with Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides online tax tools, the expanded Web site includes links to E-LOAN's
online mortgage business and to Citibank's new online banking service, Hodes
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "They don't so much expect to be the next etrade-dot-com but to get a
healthy amount of traffic in coming months on the tax site," Hodes said. "They
have their flag out and they're letting people know the door's open."
</P>
<P>
	   Other partnerships, unveiled Wednesday, are also seen as customer draws.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the Refund Rewards programs, taxpayers' refunds are loaded onto
prepaid buying cards that can be used for purchases -- at a discount -- from
General Motors, Sears, Radio Shack and other selected merchants.
</P>
<P>
	   The other major partnership offers discounts on Block tax and financial
services to the 13 million members of the AFL-CIO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0017 </TRAILER>
