<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trail Blazers 95, Cavaliers 75  </HEADLINE>
    By LANDON HALL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Rasheed Wallace scored a season-high 25 points and
Steve Smith added 18 as the Portland Trail Blazers defeated the Cleveland
Cavaliers 95-75 for their ninth victory in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
	   Damon Stoudamire added 17 points, and Scottie Pippen scored all 12 of his
points during a four-minute stretch late in the second quarter when the Blazers
rallied from a five-point deficit to take the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
	   Shawn Kemp had 18 points and Lamond Murray had 17 for the Cavaliers, who had
their three-game winning streak snapped.
</P>
<P>
	   It was a sad and strange night for the Cavs, who began a season-long
seven-game road trip with the news that former teammate Bobby Phills had been
killed in a car accident in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
	   Then, before the game, backup forward Ryan Stack had a dizzy spell, nearly
falling off his chair during player introductions. He was taken by ambulance to
a hospital with what a team spokesman called lightheadedness. Stack was
reportedly feeling better later, but was kept overnight as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
	   Cleveland scored just 10 points and made three field goals in the fourth
quarter as the Blazers turned the game into a rout. The Cavs also had 18
turnovers, nine more than their previous high this season.
</P>
<P>
	   Portland trailed by eight in the second quarter, but used a 16-4 run in the
final 4 1/2 minutes to take a 51-44 halftime lead. Pippen hit two 3-pointers
during the run.
</P>
<P>
	   Stoudamire scored eight points in the third, including a driving layup with
six-tenths of a second left, for a 73-65 lead. Detlef Schrempf's short jumper
made it a 13-point lead less than two minutes into the fourth, and it only got
worse from there for the Cavs.
</P>
<P>
	   Wallace injured his right ankle with 3:57 left in the third when he hung on
the rim after an alley-oop pass from Pippen, then fell backward and stepped on
Kemp's heel. He lay on the court for several seconds and hobbled off the court,
but returned to score four points in the fourth quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
