<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coyotes 3, Penguins 1  </HEADLINE>
    By MEL REISNER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHOENIX (AP) -- Shane Doan broke up goalie Jean-Sebastien Aubin's shutout
bid in the second period, and the Phoenix Coyotes went on to a 3-1 victory over
the Pittsburgh Penguins on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Trevor Letowski added a power-play goal and Keith Tkachuk scored on a
penalty shot in the third period.
</P>
<P>
	   Sean Burke improved to 3-1-1 with the Coyotes, who acquired him in a trade
with Florida in November. He stopped 21 shots and weathered eight Pittsburgh
power plays for the win, but lost his shutout when NHL scoring leader Jaromir
Jagr scored his 33rd goal 8:10 into the third period.
</P>
<P>
	   The goal was the 19th point in the last 10 games for Jagr, who had two goals
in a 4-2 win over the Coyotes on Dec. 11 in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
	   The Coyotes recovered from a seven-game stretch in which they were outshot
by opponents by an average of 14 shots a game. This time, they bettered the
Penguins 27-22, avenging not only the loss but the embarrassment of an 11-shot
game that set a Pittsburgh franchise record for fewest shots by an opponent.
</P>
<P>
	   Letowski scored on a slap shot that went off the skate of Penguins
defenseman as he jostled with Rick Tocchet at the top of the crease 3:04 into
the third period. Tocchet, who originally was credited with the goal, got an
assist -- the 480th of his career, leaving him one point shy of 900.
</P>
<P>
	   Tkachuk made it 3-0 just 2:16 later after Darius Kasparaitis dragged him
down at Aubin's doorstep. Tkachuk, stopped by current Phoenix goalie Bob Essensa
on his first career penalty shot Jan. 24, 1998, against Edmonton, took a
forehand approach to the net, then fired a sharp wrist shot between Aubin's
legs.
</P>
<P>
	   On Monday, New York's Brad Isbister scored on a penalty against Phoenix
during a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
	   Aubin stopped 12 shots in the first period, one more than the Coyotes took
their first game against the Penguins. Aubin made 24 saves in all.
</P>
<P>
	   But even though Pittsburgh had five power plays in the second period to two
for the Coyotes, the pace caught up with the 22-year-old goalie.
</P>
<P>
	   Doan sent Phoenix into a 1-0 lead with 8:35 left in the second. He got the
puck from Mika Alatalo, who fielded the rebound of a slap shot by Yuha Ylonen,
and skated to his left for a 10-foot forehand that beat Aubin on the near side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
