<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Driver's license renewals in New York will require eye exam  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New Yorkers of all ages will be required to pass an
eye exam when renewing their licenses as of April 1.
<P>
	   After vetoing a similar measure in 1997, Gov. George Pataki reinstated the
eye exam requirement. He also changed the schedule for renewing licenses from
every five years to every eight. The change does not effect commercial drivers,
who already had eye exams every five years.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1997, Pataki said the eye testing would have been too expensive for the
Department of Motor Vehicles to conduct and he was not convinced of the traffic
safety benefits.
</P>
<P>
	   Since Pataki's veto, the DMV's medical advisory board has recommended that
eye exams be reinstated, Division of Budget spokesman Kevin Quinn said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, the new measure differs from the 1997 legislation in that it will cost
$400,000 a year to administer, instead of $2 million, because of the eight-year
schedule, according to Quinn.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sound, scientific medical evidence was reviewed that shows that testing for
vision at driver renewal is important for driver safety at all ages," said Dr.
George Stasior, chairman of the DMV medical advisory board.
</P>
<P>
	   Since 1994, motorists renewing their licenses have been permitted to do so
by mail by self-certifying that they have acceptable vision. Vision tests are
required for someone getting a license for the first time.
</P>
<P>
	   The state is working on a plan that would allow drivers to mail in
certificates from health care providers attesting that eye tests were passed, so
that drivers wouldn't be required to go to the DMV, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're looking to make this as easy and as customer friendly for drivers as
possible," Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   Studies have shown that states without vision tests for drivers had higher
accident and death rates, particularly in age groups over 65, said Dr. Robert
Kennedy, president of the New York State Ophthalmological Society.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're happy that the governor has agreed to reinstitute the driver's
license vision testing requirement," Kennedy said. "We're just not sure that
eight years is often enough."
</P>
<P>
	   Stasior said that the DMV medical advisory board is continuing to discuss
ways to help protect public safety, including legislation that would deal with
reporting people who should not be driving.
</P>
<P>
	   The new measure, which does not require legislative approval, will effect
roughly 2 million motorists a year, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   The $5 annual fee for renewals will not change. Drivers will pay $43 for
eight years, and an existing $3 photo document fee. Currently, drivers pay $28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 0041 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Niagara Mohawk helps test experimental street light  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SACKETS HARBOR, N.Y. (AP) - There may be a bright future for a dim light
hanging outside a grocery store in this historical Lake Ontario village.
<P>
	   With a round, bluish head that faces the ground and a rectangular solar
panel that looks like a hat pointing toward the sky, it sits 12 feet high at the
entrance to the Harbor Market's parking lot.
</P>
<P>
	   Since mid-December, Niagara Mohawk scientists have been testing the
one-of-a-kind street light in this community 75 miles north of Syracuse. Hardly
anyone has noticed.
</P>
<P>
	   "The bright lights of the city are alluring for some people. In the country,
though, glaring bright lights can actually limit a person's vision," said Art
Peterson, a Niagara Mohawk research and development specialist.
</P>
<P>
	   "This light illuminates like moonlight. It doesn't wreck your night vision.
That's the whole idea behind it," Peterson said. "It's a neat concept. People
often think brighter is better. It's not true."
</P>
<P>
	   If successful, the light could be used along places like the Erie Canal,
hiking trails, parks and waterfronts where a softer light is preferable, he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not designed to do an intersection," said Anthony Andre, the utility's
regional manager.
</P>
<P>
	   "Where it would be great is in an area where there should be low light
pollution. Someplace where, instead of just blinding light, the light allows you
to see into the reaches of a field," Andre said.
</P>
<P>
	   Most street lights emit a glare that obscures stars at night and temporarily
blinds people. Lights that allow people to see where they are walking without
eliminating all other views are part of a recent trend in light design, Andre
said.
</P>
<P>
	   The light Niagara Mohawk is testing was designed by Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute and Howard M. Brandston, who designed lights for the Statute of
Liberty and Central Park.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to being powered by solar energy, the experimental light
contains light-emitting diodes, or LEDs, which are the latest technology in
low-glare, energy-efficient lighting, said Peterson.
</P>
<P>
	   The experimental light uses only 25 watts compared to a normal street
light's 100 watts.
</P>
<P>
	   "It also offers the promise of a longer lifetime," Peterson said. The LED
light will last in the range of 40,000 hours, up to three times longer than
conventional street lights, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the apparent ecological and aesthetic advantages, the little lamp
with its soft blue hue hasn't won many fans. One drawback is the light does not
illuminate a very large area.
</P>
<P>
	   "You don't even see it and it goes out in the middle of the night," said
Margaret Fein, who owns the Bed of Roses Flower &AMP; Gifts shop next to the market.
"That light, it doesn't light up anything."
</P>
<P>
	   Andre said it is unfair to judge this type of light just yet, because the
prototype was only designed to stay on two hours and while solar-powered, it was
installed in mid-December, when the sun shines for the fewest hours.
</P>
<P>
	   "Until it gets going, we can't answer what the light's potential is," he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 0041 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Said in Talks To Buy Hughes  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL WHITE AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Boeing Co. reportedly is in talks to buy Hughes
Electronics Corp.'s satellite manufacturing operations, a deal that would make
the aircraft builder a dominant player in space-based communications.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing would pay $4 billion for Hughes commercial satellite business,
according to a Dow Jones Newswires report Wednesday that cited unidentified
sources familiar with the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The report said Boeing's board would meet today to discuss the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Spokesmen for Boeing and Hughes declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes is the leading maker of commercial satellites with about 40 percent
of the market. It is owned by General Motors Corp., but its shares trade
separately from regular GM stock.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing wants to position itself broadly in the aerospace market, said Jon
Kutler, president of Quarterdeck Investment Partners, an investment bank
specializing in aerospace acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
	   The move would reduce its dependency on jet airliner sales, and put the
company in position to capitalize on potential growth in the commercial
satellite industry. Boeing already has several satellite launch programs
including SeaLaunch, which uses a Russian-built rocket that blasts off from a
floating launch pad, and the Delta family of land-based rockets.
</P>
<P>
	   The purchase would reflect some uncertainty on Boeing's part as to which
areas of aerospace will become the most lucrative in the next century, Kutler
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "For Boeing, it's hard to sit here and decide which way things are going to
go, and they want to be represented across the board," Kutler said. "They're
trying to have their arms in most of the major areas of the space market in
order to be well-positioned regardless of how the market goes."
</P>
<P>
	   The deal would complete the transformation of Hughes from a major military
aerospace contractor to what would become primarily a commercial
telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes was founded as Hughes Aircraft by wealthy eccentric Howard Hughes in
1932 and branched out into defense electronics after World War II. The company
began to move into commercial ventures, such as DirecTV, after the end of the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes shares have more than doubled during the past year, driven by the
growth of DirecTV. The service, with more than 8 million subscribers, had
revenue of $1.05 billion in the third quarter, up from $408 million in the third
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes, however, has spent heavily developing the subscriber base. The
company lost $29.6 million in the third quarter, mainly because of expenses from
its acquisition of two satellite-TV rivals, as well as higher satellite costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale of its satellite manufacturing business would provide cash Hughes
needs to continue developing DirecTV and other communications businesses, said
Paul Nisbet, an analyst with JSA Research.
</P>
<P>
	   Hughes shed its aircraft operations in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a company that had a lot of money after selling off Hughes Aircraft to
Raytheon, but they've gone through that and now they're substantially in debt,"
said Nisbet. "This would be a source of funds to keep their growth going in
these new fields."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0042 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki budget pushes for control of state Education Department  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki again is asking the state
Legislature for full control of the state Education Department, saying the
record amount of money the schools have been getting aren't improving education
in New York.
<P>
	   Pataki not only wants to take away the department's control over the state
Library, Archives and Museum, he also wants to slash some of the Education
Department's staff; personally choose the department's commissioner, as well as
its controlling board, the Board of Regents, and the Regents' chancellor.
</P>
<P>
	   He even wants to strip the department of $250,000 in charter school money.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki never specifically mentioned his plans during his State of the State
address last week or in his executive budget address on Tuesday to legislators.
Instead, Pataki focused on the record amount of public school aid he wants to
spend in the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
	   "By the way, we haven't seen the results from the schools that we should
have expected when you pour this amount of money into them," Pataki told
reporters after his executive budget address Tuesday. That "is why we don't need
just the additional dollars that we're proposing but we need structural reform.
We need accountability."
</P>
<P>
	   State officials got the first test results from the Board of Regents' push
to increase the educational standards in New York last year.
</P>
<P>
	   More than half of the fourth grade students did not pass the Regents' new
English test, a third failed the fourth-grade math test and a quarter of those
who took the senior English exam needed to graduate have to take it again.
</P>
<P>
	   But Education Commissioner Richard Mills, who was hired by the
Assembly-controlled Board of Regents, didn't like Pataki's education plan.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think this is personal. We have a very good working relationship
with the governor's staff but I certainly don't agree with this proposal," Mills
said Wednesday. "The Board of Regents has mustered the forces at their command
to raise standards. The Regents have been very persistent about this. I don't
see the logic of that change at all."
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers, especially in the Democrat-controlled Assembly, are unlikely to
go along with Pataki's plan. Pataki has suggested that the Legislature give him
greater control of the state's schools every year since the first year of his
term, Assembly Education Chairman Steven Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Legislature has rejected this autocratic approach to education every
year since," Sanders said. "We will certainly reject it again this year."
</P>
<P>
	   While Pataki has suggested abolishing the Board of Regents before, this is
the first time he has suggested taking away the state Museum, Archives and
Library from the Education Department, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Joe Conway, a spokesman for Pataki's Budget Division, said all of Pataki's
suggestions were "common-sense" initiatives. The State University of New York
gets more charter school applications than the Education Department and
streamlining the command structure will provide a greater level of
accountability, Pataki's plan says.
</P>
<P>
	   The 10 percent reduction Pataki wants would consist of 18 employees from the
department's Office of Management Services and Elementary, Middle, Secondary and
Continuing Education divisions, which would be accomplished through attrition,
Conway said. "We would rather spend general fund dollars on the classrooms, not
on the bureaucracy," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The point behind the initiatives is "producing the best possible result for
the students," Conway said. "This plan would allow the Education Department to
focus its attention where it belongs, on the classrooms."
</P>
<P>
	   But Carole Huxley, the deputy education commissioner for cultural education,
worried about the separation between politics and education. Putting political
appointees in charge of information distribution and education might not be a
good idea, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "A buffer between politics and libraries, public broadcasting, archives and
museums is an important thing," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
