<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portnoy's complaint: Legislators don't like names named  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - No matter how the criminal case against tobacco
lobbyist Sharon Portnoy goes, the revelations surrounding her activities already
represent a low point in the state Legislature's recent history.
<P>
	   A deposition she gave on Nov. 10 about her activities on behalf of Philip
Morris was released this week by the state Lobbying Commission and it is a tough
read for anyone who believes that selflessness is the motivation for a career in
public service for many of New York state's legislators.
</P>
<P>
	   In her deposition, Portnoy admits to repeatedly doctoring the spending
reports she was required to make to the Lobbying Commission from 1996-99 by
falsely adding the names of fellow lobbyists who had attended dinners,
receptions and other events with lawmakers. Those other lobbyists were not
actually on hand, Portnoy testified.
</P>
<P>
	   But by adding the other names, Portnoy was able to divide the total amount
spent at those events by more people and thus get the per-person costs under
$75. She considered that crucial because it prevented her from having to list
the names of the dozens of individual legislators she was wining and dining in
reports to the Lobbying Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   Lobbyists only have to name names when they spend more than $75 per event on
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
	   For people cynical of government, Portnoy's activities are doubly troubling.
</P>
<P>
	   First, as she admits repeatedly during her deposition, it was well
understood among lobbyists that state legislators didn't like their names
turning up in lobbyists' reports to the state commission. That was even more
true when the lobbyist paying for dinners, drinks, tickets and so forth was
Philip Morris, a giant in the much-maligned tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was thinking in terms of not embarrassing legislators by naming them on a
lobbying report," she told Lobbying Commission officials. At another point, she
said she felt "compelled" not to "put the legislator in the position of having
their name listed on the lobbying report."
</P>
<P>
	   The lengths Portnoy went to maintain the appearance that legislators were
staying beneath the $75 spending limit suggest that moderation was not on many
lawmakers' minds when they knew Philip Morris was picking up the tab.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, for a March 1997 reception at the fancy Nicole's Bistro
restaurant in Albany, Portnoy admitted adding the names of 12 people who weren't
actually there in order to make the per-person spending numbers work out right.
</P>
<P>
	   For another night out a week later at the same restaurant with legislators,
she doctored the books with the names of 11 people who were not on hand.
</P>
<P>
	   What such instances suggest, according to Blair Horner of the New York
Public Interest Research Group, is that these parties were extremely lavish and
that many legislators almost certainly consumed drinks and food worth far more
than $75.
</P>
<P>
	   Privately, some legislators who attended Portnoy's events insisted that they
were simply not that extravagant and they wondered how they could have cost
thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   Then there were the smaller, quirkier events Portnoy had Philip Morris pay
for, such as the little get-together for Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver. It
featured bagels - $629 worth - and was catered by Mom's Bagels.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked by the executive director of the Lobbying Commission, David Grandeau,
how she could spend that kind of money on bagels, Portnoy said it wasn't just
bagels. There was smoked fish and poached salmon and since Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver, a devout Jew, was the guest of honor the caterers also had to
provide kosher dishes and flatware, Portnoy explained.
</P>
<P>
	   Portnoy's deposition and other documents in the Lobbying Commission's case
against her have been turned over to Albany County District Attorney Sol
Greenberg's office for possible criminal prosecution. She and Philip Morris were
fined late last year by the commission and Portnoy was banned from lobbying in
New York state for three years.
</P>
<P>
	   She had been paid a base salary of $132,500 plus annual bonuses. In 1998,
that bonus was $45,000, she told the lobbying commission.
</P>
<P>
	   She could face a misdemeanor, a $1,000 fine and up to one year in jail if
Greenberg's office wins a conviction against her.
</P>
<P>
	   Portnoy told the commission that she brought her troubles on herself, that
other lobbyists did not know she was claiming they were at certain events and
that she was not asked to falsify records by Philip Morris or legislators.
</P>
<P>
	   Did it ever happen, Grandeau wondered during Portnoy's deposition, that
state legislators actually insisted on paying for their own food and drinks at
one of her events?
</P>
<P>
	   "No, not that I can recall," she replied.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, Portnoy filed an addendum to her deposition to say that
statement wasn't accurate. She said she could recall two state legislators
offering to pay for a portion of their dinners.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in Albany. He can
be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station, Albany, N.Y., 12224, or at
jstashenko@aol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 0042 </TRAILER>
