<DOCNO> APW20000113.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silver pushes new campaign finance limits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Fund-raising events for state office candidates held
within 40 miles of the state Capitol would be banned during annual legislative
sessions under legislation from the state Assembly's Democratic majority.
<P>
	   The wide-ranging campaign finance reform legislation also proposes limits on
the amount of money political party committees could transfer to such state
office candidates.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, party committees could only give $700,000 to candidates for
governor; $50,000 to state Senate candidates; and $25,000 to Assembly candidates
under the Assembly majority's proposal. There are currently no such limits.
</P>
<P>
	   The measure, which stands almost no chance of becoming law in its current
form, also renews the Assembly Democratic majority's past calls for partial
public financing of campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   "As we enter the 21st century, it is incumbent upon elected officials to
face directly the challenge of campaign finance reform and come up with a system
that is equitable and fair to the public," Stephen Kaufman, a Bronx Democrat who
is chairman of the Assembly's Election Law Committee, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Assembly leadership indicated the proposal to ban fund-raising events in
the Albany area during legislative sessions was aimed at the practice of
politicians hitting up lobbyists and their clients for money at a time when they
want to influence legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   In June, Gov. George Pataki unveiled his own sweeping campaign finance
proposal that would have barred fund-raising events from even being held within
25 miles of the state Capitol during the annual legislative session that
normally runs from early January through June or July.
</P>
<P>
	   The Pataki plan would also eliminate the unlimited "soft money" donations
special interests can give to political parties and impose lower campaign
contribution limits for all state office races. The Republican governor did not
call for public campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither the Democratic-led Assembly or the Republican-controlled Senate has
acted on the governor's proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing its campaign finance proposal, the Assembly Democrats called
on the Senate GOP majority to approve the governor's plan and then allow a joint
Assembly-Senate conference committee to work out compromise legislation
acceptable to both chambers.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Rensselaer County Republican, said
Wednesday that his GOP Senate colleagues would be unveiling their own campaign
finance proposal. He gave no timetable for when that plan might be made public.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno did take a jab at the Assembly Democrats, noting that they have
refused to go along with legislation approved by the Senate to bar all gifts
over $25 from lobbyists. The Senate leader noted that the senators have agreed
to abide by that ban voluntarily even without Assembly approval of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno said Wednesday that in that same spirit, the Assembly Democrats should
pass their campaign finance plan and then voluntarily abide by its restrictions,
even without agreement from the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 0043 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
