<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Mulls $1B Investment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The Thai government is considering joining hands
with the private sector to build a $1 billion silicon wafer factory to boost the
local electronics industry, local newspapers reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The government is considering funding about a quarter of the plant's cost,
with the private sector raising the remainder, Industry Minister Suwat
Liptapallop was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
	   The cabinet is set to vote on the proposal later this month, the Bangkok
Post reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Thailand has long planned a silicon wafer factory, which would reduce its
dependency on imports.
</P>
<P>
	   Silicon wafers, which form a part of integrated circuits, or chips, for the
electronics industry, are currently imported from higher-end production centers
such as Malaysia, Singapore, Taiwan and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
	   Thailand wants to move away from the low-end electronics sector -- where it
competes with China -- toward production of integrated circuits.
</P>
<P>
	   A unit of Thailand's Alphatec Electronics, Submicron Technology, planned a
silicon wafer factory, but the project was put on hold after the parent company
entered bankruptcy proceedings in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0044 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
