<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain OK With Pinochet Decision  </HEADLINE>
   By KERNAN TURNER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- If Britain allows Gen. Augusto Pinochet to leave
London a free man, it will be welcome news to the Spanish government, which has
been in a diplomatic hot seat since his arrest nearly 15 months ago.
</P>
<P>
	   An end to the Pinochet saga will be especially satisfying to Prime Minister
Jose Maria Aznar, whose re-election depends on the outcome of the national
parliamentary vote in March.
</P>
<P>
	   Should Britain free Pinochet, Aznar will no longer have to fend off
criticism from the socialist opposition that he has been lukewarm about seeing
the former Chilean dictator stand trial in Spain on charges of human rights
abuses.
</P>
<P>
	   British Home Secretary Jack Straw announced Tuesday that an independent
medical exam found the 84-year-old general unfit to stand trial, and Straw said
he was therefore inclined to cancel extradition proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   That opens the door for Pinochet to return home to Chile within weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   Aznar has maintained neutrality since Pinochet was detained in London in
1998 on an arrest warrant filed by Spanish investigative magistrate Baltasar
Garzon.
</P>
<P>
	   Garzon's indictment accused Pinochet of genocide, terrorism and torture to
intimidate and silence political opponents, including Spanish citizens,
throughout his 1973-90 dictatorship. An official Chilean government report says
3,197 people died or disappeared after Pinochet led a coup to topple elected
Marxist President Salvador Allende.
</P>
<P>
	   Aznar's government never endorsed Pinochet's arrest or extradition. Neither
did it block extradition efforts by Garzon that pushed the case to the brink of
bringing Pinochet to Spain to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Along the way, Aznar's government caught much of the blame from both
Pinochet supporters and the governments of Chile and neighboring Argentina, an
uncomfortable position for a country that has staked much of its economic growth
on commercial ventures in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
	   Garzon has indicted 98 former military officers in Argentina on charges of
genocide, terrorism and torture and issued Interpol detention orders for 48 of
them involved in the 1976-83 dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
	   At least 9,000 Argentines vanished at the hands of the junta's troops during
the country's so-called ``dirty war'' two decades ago. Human rights groups say
the figure is closer to 30,000.
</P>
<P>
	   As the Pinochet case advanced, Argentina and Chile accused Spain of behaving
like it was still a colonial power in South America. Questions were raised over
what gave Spain the right to judge other dictatorships when it did nothing at
home after the death in 1975 of its own despot, Gen. Francisco Franco.
</P>
<P>
	   Spanish historians assert there is a major difference between the Chilean
and Spanish regimes. For one thing, Franco cannot be prosecuted because he is
dead. Pinochet's brutality was one-sided, they note, whereas in Spain, Franco's
opponents also committed atrocities before and during the Civil War that brought
him to power.
</P>
<P>
	   Adopting the slogan, ``Amnesty and Liberty,'' all sides agreed to a general
amnesty after Franco's death in order to help Spain avoid bloodshed and build a
stable democracy.
</P>
<P>
	   ------------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITORS: Kernan Turner is chief of Iberian Services for The Associated
Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
