<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hit HBO Series 'Sopranos' Is Back  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID BAUDER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Dysfunctional at best, murderous at worst, the Sopranos are
hardly anyone's idea of a model family.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet television viewers have embraced Tony, Carmela and their extended
famiglia. And on Sunday night they return -- after a long wait -- for a second
season on HBO.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Sopranos" received so much critical praise after only 13 episodes that
it was considered an upset when the series won just four of the 16 Emmy Awards
it was nominated for. Cable's TV Land network last week gave "The Sopranos" its
"Future Classic" award.
</P>
<P>
	   "Hands down, 'The Sopranos' is the most important television show to come
along in years," said Larry Jones, TV Land general manager. "The show's complex
characters and exciting, continuous plotlines all blend seamlessly thanks to one
of the most superb casts ever assembled on television."
</P>
<P>
	   Life doesn't improve this year for New Jersey mob boss Tony, already
suffering from anxiety attacks and a hit attempt ordered by his mother. His
flaky sister arrives from the West Coast and a new nemesis, Richie Aprile, is
released from jail with a chip on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
	   It's a tribute to the deft work of series creator David Chase that Tony
Soprano became a favorite. The role even made balding, overweight star James
Gandolfini a sex symbol.
</P>
<P>
	   Filming on location in New Jersey with a largely Italian-American cast gives
the plot an ominous authenticity. The mix of mundane family problems with the
more unusual occupational hazards -- like inter-family gunplay -- often makes
"The Sopranos" hilarious.
</P>
<P>
	   Watch in the new season's third episode how the feared mob boss is reduced
to jelly by his teen-age daughter, who suggests her own "punishment" after being
caught partying: a brief ban on using her credit card. Tony and Carmela live in
fear that their daughter will discover how powerless they are to really
discipline her.
</P>
<P>
	   Dominic Chianese, who plays Soprano's uncle and rival, Junior, traces some
of "The Sopranos" success to feelings he remembers from watching King Kong as a
youngster. He feared the monster as he watched it toss subway cars like toys,
yet also felt a little sorry for him.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's got extremely relatable characters, aside from what those characters
do for a living," said Chris Albrecht, HBO president of original programming.
"Their emotions and what drives them feel honest for a wide variety of people."
</P>
<P>
	   As with most successful TV, few people saw it coming. Other networks, most
notably Fox, turned the series down. HBO chief executive Jeff Bewkes, almost
shuddering at the memory, said HBO nearly ordered Chase to change the series'
name.
</P>
<P>
	   In a short time, "The Sopranos" has helped change HBO's image. Once thought
of primarily for its movies and special events, the pay cable outlet is getting
more attention now for original series like "Sex and the City," "Oz" and "The
Chris Rock Show."
</P>
<P>
	   "These shows are successful because they're smart, they're real and they're
well done," Bewkes said. "They're not watered down to make sure everybody gets
it, so they'll still be sitting there when the Pringles commercial comes on."
</P>
<P>
	   An estimated 10 million people watched each episode of "The Sopranos" during
its four weekly airings last year. The series rang up some of its best numbers
on New Year's week, when HBO ran the entire series for an unprecedented third
time, proving people are catching on by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
	   That's a hit by pay cable standards, though it commands less than half the
audience of "ER," which averages 24 million viewers for one airing of an
original episode. About the same number of people watch "The Sopranos" as tune
in to "Martial Law" or "Just Shoot Me."
</P>
<P>
	   HBO, which is in roughly a quarter of American homes, gained 350,000
subscribers last year, according to an outside analyst. No one can say how many
joined because of "The Sopranos."
</P>
<P>
	   As season two begins, cast members are trying to keep plot twists to
themselves, and are pinching themselves to see if all the attention is real. The
new season is again 13 episodes, and will be wrapped up by the spring.
</P>
<P>
	   "You do get a feeling of 'Oh my God, this is too good to be true,"' Chianese
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Chianese's mother is a fan. She's 92.
</P>
<P>
	   "She says, 'You curse a little too much,"' he said. "But deep down, she
knows it's a character. She was born in the Bronx. She's heard those words, I'm
sure."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
