<HEADLINE> GOP Controls Va. Govt. for 1st Time  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- After more than a century as the minority party,
Republicans have seated their first majority in the Virginia House of Delegates
and taken total control of state government for the first time.
</P>
<P>
	   S. Vance Wilkins Jr., who worked for 20 years to bring the GOP to power in
the House, took the oath of office Wednesday as the first Republican speaker
since 1883.
</P>
<P>
	   Prominent Republicans, including Gov. Jim Gilmore and his GOP predecessors
George Allen and Linwood Holton, jammed the House chamber for the start of the
60-day legislative session.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans won House control in November, capturing 52 seats. The Democrats
won 47, with one independent who usually votes with the GOP. Republicans
maintained their 21-19 majority in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
	   It's the first time Republicans have controlled the Virginia governor's
office and both legislative chambers.
</P>
</TEXT>
