<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government: Let Whistles Blow  </HEADLINE>
   By TAMMY WEBBER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) -- Mayor Arlene Mulder says residents in this
fast-growing Chicago suburb are entitled to some peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
	   She fears a federal proposal to require trains to blow their whistles at all
public railroad crossings would shatter that quiet -- and drop property values
in a community where developers are spending millions of dollars to build
condominiums and townhouses near commuter tracks.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The real threat is to quality of life,'' Mulder said. ``We've been working
so hard to rebuild and revitalize downtown, and now they say they're going to
blow whistles?''
</P>
<P>
	   Federal Railroad Administration officials say train whistles are being
silenced at the expense of lives in many communities. They want nearly 250
communities that have banned whistles to let the warnings sound once more unless
other steps are taken to improve crossing safety.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is really about life and death and how we can prevent truly preventable
injuries and deaths,'' FRA Administrator Jolene Molitoris said Wednesday.
``That's our goal.''
</P>
<P>
	   Agency officials said there were 431 deaths and more than 1,300 injuries in
highway-rail crossing accidents in 1998. And they said the collision rate jumps
62 percent when train whistles aren't blown.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue is especially important in Illinois. The state had the
second-highest number of train-related deaths in the nation even before an
Amtrak train collided with a steel-laden semitrailer in Bourbonnais last March,
killing 11 people and injuring more than 100.
</P>
<P>
	   Between 1991 and 1998, there were 288 train-related deaths in Illinois,
second only to Texas. Illinois has the second-highest number of crossings in the
nation -- 15,746 -- meaning more noise for residents if the federal regulation
is adopted.
</P>
<P>
	   Train horns -- two long blasts followed by one short and one long -- are
standard practice at most of the 158,000 public railroad crossings across
America. But there are about 2,200 railroad crossings in 247 communities that
have enacted local bans prohibiting trains from sounding their horns.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal rule would likely supersede local ``quiet zones.'' The FRA will
grant exceptions to communities that take steps to improve crossing safety,
including adding gates or lane dividers to keep motorists from zigzagging around
gates, or installing cameras to catch violators.
</P>
<P>
	   Molitoris said communities can apply for federal and state grants and loans
to help pay for improvements needed to qualify as quiet zones.
</P>
<P>
	   But Ronald Hamelberg, president of Barrington -- a village of some 10,500
people and nine railroad crossings about 35 miles northwest of Chicago -- said
the town's portion of the cost still would be too much.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can't lay this all on our citizens,'' he said. ``We're going to need
some financial help.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mulder said Arlington Heights would have no choice but to find money
somewhere to help the ``thousands and thousands of people trying to sleep at
night.''
</P>
<P>
	   Public hearings on the rules, which also propose a volume limit for train
horns, will be held this spring in Ohio, Massachusetts, Florida, Oregon,
California, the District of Columbia, Indiana and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
	   Officials don't expect to finalize the regulation until 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Leroy Jones, a former engineer and national legislative representative for
the Brotherhood of Locomotive Engineers, said blowing train horns would reduce
deaths and injuries from crossing collisions, which totaled 3,508 in 1998, the
most recent figures available.
</P>
<P>
	   Noisy train horns, however, have been too much to take for some residents in
Elkhart, Ind., east of South Bend.
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Gilot, public works and utilities director, said his city has
petitioned state officials to prevent engineers from blowing horns at 11 of 38
crossings in the community, which is home to a large rail yard.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At some of these crossings there's like 85 trains a day. The long blasts
have gotten some people upset. They understand it in rural areas where they
don't have gates, but don't think they're needed where there's gated
crossings,'' Gilot said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One of the business leaders calculated how many horn blasts we had been
subjected to every day. It was astronomical.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0128 </TRAILER>
