<DOCNO> APW20000113.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Despite setbacks, state stays with teacher education plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York's schools deserve an "A" for standards and
accountability, but class sizes and parental involvement rate a "D-plus",
according to a national education magazine.
<P>
	   For the quality of teachers - which measured both the number of teachers
working in their fields and individual assessments - Education Week gave Empire
State educators a "C-plus."
</P>
<P>
	   Quality Counts 2000, the Maryland-based publication's fourth annual look at
public schooling in kindergarten through 12th grade, found that many states,
including New York, often fail to meet their own goals.
</P>
<P>
	   The magazine, which rated schools in all 50 states in a report published
Wednesday, said New York education officials have stuck by most of the goals the
Board of Regents adopted in mid-1998. But it noted that the state has
backtracked in some areas, including tougher teacher education, certification
and continuing education standards.
</P>
<P>
	   State education officials say they are not turning back, they simply know
more now than when they set the goals and they are doing some fine-tuning.
</P>
<P>
	   "Whenever you bring a policy to life there are all kinds of adjustments and
compromises that are made," state Education Commissioner Richard Mills said.
"Much of that has to do with the fact that the Regents never propose things
without listening to a number of different ideas or voices."
</P>
<P>
	   According to Education Week, there's been a major shift in the state's
thinking on tenure.
</P>
<P>
	   A recent state policy would have required new teachers to get a master's
degree within two years.
</P>
<P>
	   But the latest proposal, which the state Board of Regents is expected to act
on this year, would extend that period to three years. Currently, the state
gives beginning teachers five years to earn a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
	   "The state's decision is an acknowledgment that for many people it is
financially impossible to get a masters' degree as a beginning teacher," Philip
Ellis, manager of educational services with the New York State United Teachers
union, said. "It's particularly tough if those young teachers are working on a
full-time basis because at this time they should really be trying to get
acclimated to the job."
</P>
<P>
	   Mills said the Regents' ultimate goal is to employ teachers who are fluent
in the subjects they are instructing, and who have broad experience and the
ability to teach students with diverse needs.
</P>
<P>
	   Other controversial proposals included those which narrowed the number of
grades that an educator is licensed to teach in New York. Now, the state has two
types of certification for teachers in regular education: pre-kindergarten
through sixth grade and seventh grade through 12th grade.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the latest proposal before the Board of Regents, those would be
replaced by four certificates: birth through second grade; first grade through
sixth grade; fifth grade through ninth grade; and seventh grade through 12th
grade.
</P>
<P>
	   "New teachers need to understand the subjects they teach but they also need
to understand how children grow and develop and the Regents are trying to
combine both perspectives in the standards for teachers," Mills said.
</P>
<P>
	   But according to Ellis, the new breakdown might be self defeating.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have concerns that the narrowing of certification areas could
potentially lead to shortages of teachers in some areas, especially the first
certification (birth to second grade)," Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
	   "If a student was going to become a teacher and was concerned about
long-term employment they might look for certification areas with the widest
grade spans, so people may not want to become kindergarten teachers and we may
potentially end up with a shortage of kindergarten teachers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 0128 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators 2, Mighty Ducks 0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Ron Tugnutt earned his seventh career shutout and
Vaclav Prospal scored the go-ahead goal with 8:31 left as the Ottawa Senators
extended their road-unbeaten streak to five games Wednesday night with a 2-0
victory over the Anaheim Mighty Ducks.
</P>
<P>
	   Tugnutt and Guy Hebert, who shared goalie duties in Anaheim during the
Ducks' inaugural season of 1993-94, were in a scoreless battle until Prospal
beat Hebert with a slap shot from the middle of the left circle for his 10th
goal.
</P>
<P>
	   Marian Hossa, on his 21st birthday, added an empty-net goal with a minute to
play.
</P>
<P>
	   Tugnutt, who earned the first-ever Ducks victory, stopped 32 shots for his
fourth shutout this season. Hebert made 23 saves for Anaheim, winless in its
last seven games (0-5-2).
</P>
<P>
	   Ottawa goalies have recorded five shutouts, one fewer than last season.
</P>
<P>
	   Anaheim's power play, which has gone from first in the league last season to
last this season, went 0-for-3 and is 1-for-33 in eight games.
</P>
<P>
	   About three minutes into the game, Anaheim's Ted Donato found Paul Kariya
all alone about 15 feet in front of the net with a pass from the left boards,
but the Ducks' career-leading goal scorer fanned on the shot.
</P>
<P>
	   Anaheim's Jeff Nielsen was sent off for boarding 25 seconds into the third
and Kariya had a short-handed chance moments later. But Tugnutt got his blocking
pad on a rising slap shot from the top of the left circle to deny him.
</P>
<P>
	   Tugnutt's closest call came with 2 1-2 minutes left in the second when he
stopped Teemu Selanne twice from the edge of the crease.
</P>
<P>
	   Selanne came close again with 12 1-2 minutes left, when his rising slap shot
from between the circles glanced off Tugnutt's mask.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
