<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Borders Closed to Men, 10-60  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNA DOLGOV Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- Men trying to escape the bloodshed of Chechnya
came to the border and were turned back by Russian soldiers for the same brusque
reason.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The problem is that you are not 60 yet,'' said the stern,
Kalashnikov-toting border guard. The men could do nothing but turn and walk
away.
</P>
<P>
	   They were feeling the sting of a new Russian policy to crack down on rebels
who have shown recent signs of resurgence. A top Russian military commander,
Col. Gen. Viktor Kazantsev, on Tuesday ordered that all males between 10 and 60
years old be detained and checked for possible rebel ties.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the military's orders, all roads between Chechnya and the neighboring
Russian region of Ingushetia were closed Wednesday to such males.
</P>
<P>
	   The order also affected those who wanted to get back into Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
	   Vakhid Ashakhanov, 41, said he left Chechnya on Tuesday to drive a friend's
daughter to a hospital in Ingushetia. The girl, 16-year-old Zarema Shishkhanova,
was suffering from an acute form of tuberculosis she developed after living for
several months in a cold basement.
</P>
<P>
	   After the unexpected tightening of border regulations, Ashakhanov was cut
off from his two teen-age sons, who remained in their home village of Gikaly,
just outside Grozny, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They can't leave (Chechnya), and I can't go back,'' Ashakhanov said.
</P>
<P>
	   Shishkhanova's father, Gilany Shishkhanov, showed his daughter's hospital
admission record to the Russian guards -- but with no success.
</P>
<P>
	   At 61, Shishkhanov was old enough to go back to Chechnya, where he had left
his 4- and 6-year-old granddaughters. But having no money to pay for a ride
home, Shishkhanov said he could not leave without his younger friend.
</P>
<P>
	   A straight-backed, dignified-looking man wearing a traditional sheepskin
hat, Shishkhanov was wiping away tears from his wrinkled face.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let God be their judge,'' Shishkhanov said, turning around to walk back to
Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
	   The new policy brought sharp criticism from the watchdog agency Human Rights
Watch.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Chechen males are now effectively trapped in a war zone where they face
grave threats to their lives,'' said Peter Bouckaert, an agency worker in
Ingushetia. ``The Russian authorities are deliberately violating their
international obligations.''
</P>
<P>
	   The orders to screen Chechen men came after rebel fighters launched
counterattacks in the key towns of Shali and Argun, driving back federal troops.
The rebel offensive caught the Russians by surprise, embarrassing senior
commanders who had been predicting imminent victory.
</P>
<P>
	   Kazantsev said Russian forces had been too lax in making sure that all
rebels had been driven out of the towns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0156 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Earmarks Cancer Money  </HEADLINE>
   By KAREN GULLO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's next budget request calls for $27
million to develop ways of testing whether people have been exposed to hundreds
of carcinogens and toxic substances.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration plan being announced today aims to strengthen the
government's ability to study environmental causes of cancer and other diseases
and assist state and local public health officials investigating unusually high
cancer rates or chemical accidents.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention wants to tests
thousands of people with cancer or other diseases for toxic exposures and be
able to identify regions of the country where Americans are exposed to
cancer-causing substances.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There may well be significant environmental factors in the incidence of
disease,'' said Chris Jennings, President Clinton's health policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
	   The funds, to be included in Clinton's 2001 budget request to Congress,
would more than double what the government spent last year to develop ways of
measuring toxic exposure in humans. They would be used for research, test
development and assistance to state and local communities by CDC's Environmental
Health Lab, which does a national survey that tracks lead exposure in children.
</P>
<P>
	   The lab has developed tests that are designed to be used in a research
environment but is working on tests that can withstand the rigors of field work
so that communities can routinely monitor people for exposure to over 100
potentially toxic substances and, in the case of chemical accidents, quickly
determine whether people were exposed to dangerous poisons.
</P>
<P>
	   Right now there are few tests for measuring a wide variety of toxic
chemicals in humans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The lab is developing ways to look for dozens or hundreds of chemicals in
just a teaspoon of blood,'' said Dr. Richard Jackson, director of the CDC's
center for environmental health. ``The CDC wants to take them from the research
lab to the country health officer who is dealing with a cancer cluster or a
toxic spill.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0156 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malay Opposition Leader Charged  </HEADLINE>
   By SEAN YOONG Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- The Malaysian government today charged a
newspaper editor with sedition and warned that more arrests were possible in a
widening crackdown on opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   In a surprise sweep Wednesday, police arrested the editor of the Harakah
paper and a lawyer for ousted Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim on sedition
charges. A vice president of Anwar's National Justice Party was also detained
for provoking racial discord.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If more people commit offenses, there will be more arrests,'' Deputy Prime
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told the national news agency Bernama. ``But it
need not necessarily be all opposition people. Whoever it is, if he commits a
wrong, will have to be punished.''
</P>
<P>
	   Opposition leaders had long feared that Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who
has ruled this Southeast Asian nation for 18 years, would use the police to
silence his critics -- especially those close to Anwar. The former deputy
premier is serving a six-year prison term for corruption and is also on trial
for sodomy.
</P>
<P>
	   But few expected the crackdown now. Political temperatures had cooled after
the November general election, in which the opposition made significant gains
while Mahathir's United Malays National Front coalition retained its two-thirds
majority in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
	   The editor, Zulkifli Sulong -- whos e newspaper is the mouthpiece of the
Pan-Malaysia Islamic Party, or PAS -- appeared in court today to be charged with
sedition for an Aug. 2 article on Anwar's trials. The person responsible for
printing the newspaper was also to be charged with sedition.
</P>
<P>
	   The article quoted a National Justice Party leader alleging there was a
conspiracy planned by Mahathir in which the police, the Attorney General's
office, the courts and local media would be used to destroy Anwar.
</P>
<P>
	   Sessions Court Judge Abdul Karim Abdul Jalil fixed bail at $1,315 and set
Zulkifli's trial for May 22.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am ready to defend myself, and I am ready to face the consequences,''
Zulkifli said after his court hearing. If convicted, he faces three years in
prison and a fine of $1,315, and his newspaper could be shut down.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, Karpal Singh, who is Anwar's lawyer and a longtime critic of
the Mahathir administration, was arrested on charges of sedition for alleging in
court last year that someone had tried to poison his client.
</P>
<P>
	   Marina Yusoff, a leader of the National Justice Party, was arrested and
charged with ``provoking racial discord.'' She too could face a jail term.
</P>
<P>
	   The arrests came as Mahathir left for a two-week vacation in Argentina and
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the first crackdown here since dozens of Anwar supporters were
arrested following Mahathir's dismissal of his popular deputy in September 1998.
Anwar was later arrested. He insists the corruption and sodomy charges against
him have been trumped up to eliminate him from politics.
</P>
<P>
	   Several international human rights and journalism groups expressed outrage
over the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Malaysia has again resorted to strong-arm tactics to silence its critics,
rather than playing by the rules of international law,'' said Robert O. Varenik
of the New York-based Lawyers Committee for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
	   The Paris-based Reporters without Borders wrote to the Malaysian government,
warning that punishing Zulkifli with a jail term would be a ``serious
infringement of press freedom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0157 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital Photojournalism Class Given  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most people think news photographers invade the privacy of
presidents and their families, but they do so only at the direction of the White
House, a photojournalist told students.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We intrude when the White House tells us to intrude,'' Time magazine White
House photographer Diana Walker told students in a program launched this week by
the College of Art and Design at the Corcoran Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
	   During one of the program's first session, Walker showed a series of
intimate shots: President Reagan roaring with laughter at a joke told by Queen
Elizabeth II, President Clinton puffing his cheeks out just before accepting his
party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   The program's opening session was a six-day ``symposium'' for about 30
students that ended Wednesday. It was coordinated by Kevin D. Gilbert, president
of the White House News Photographers' Association.
</P>
<P>
	   During opening session, students visited the White House, the Capitol, the
Pentagon and other Washington sites. Lecturers included Cliff Owen of The
Washington Times and 1998 Pulitzer Prize winner Susan Walsh of The Associated
Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0158 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 13, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court: Flight Can Justify Police Searches
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court on Wednesday gave police broad
authority to stop and question people who run at the sight of an officer. The
5-4 ruling came short of giving police a blanket right to stop anyone who runs
after seeing the police. But it said such flight may indicate a crime is being
committed and therefore can help justify a police stop. The decision was a boost
for police but worried some civil libertarians. "Nervous, evasive behavior is a
pertinent factor in determining reasonable suspicion" to justify a stop, Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist wrote for the court. "Headlong flight -- wherever
it occurs -- is the consummate act of evasion."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russian Media Question Chechen War
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- After a string of military setbacks in Chechnya, the Russian
news media are starting to question the handling of the war as casualties mount
and the promises of swift victory look increasingly empty. Suddenly, newspapers
are challenging the military's claims that the war is going well and are
portraying the war as a replay of the botched 1994-96 campaign in Chechnya.
"Triumphal march in Chechnya -- stepping on a rake" read a headline in the daily
Moskovsky Komsomolets. "Chechnya turns into minefield for Russian politicians,"
said the daily Segodnya. When the war started in September, the media mirrored
the view of many Russians that the campaign was justified by Chechen attacks on
Dagestan.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Twice As Many Americans By 2100
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A century from now there will be twice as many Americans
as today, the Census Bureau predicts. While no one knows what daily life will be
like in 100 years, the new population projections being issued Thursday conjure
images of twice as many cars jostling for position on the highways and twice as
many shoppers crowding the aisles at Wal-Mart. From an estimated 275 million
people today, the bureau projects a U.S. population of 571 million in the year
2100. That might not seem terribly crowded, however, because the nation is so
sprawling.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Government Favors Microsoft Breakup
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government lawyers in the Microsoft antitrust case want
to break the software giant into three parts, arguing that lesser sanctions
would be inadequate, people close to the discussions confirmed Wednesday. If
U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson were to agree to such a dramatic
solution, a mandated breakup of Bill Gates' Seattle-based empire in an
anti-trust case would carry enormous implications for the way consumers buy and
use software for their computers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Turkey Puts Ocalan Hanging On Hold
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's government on Wednesday put on hold the
execution of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan, a move aimed at enhancing the
country's prospects for joining the European Union. The decision, which came
after coalition leaders met for eight hours, came in response to a request from
the European Court of Human Rights to review Ocalan's appeal. The rebel leader
was sentenced to death in June by a Turkish court. Italian Premier Massimo
D'Alema expressed "great satisfaction" with Turkey's decision, saying "the
choice confirms the evolution of Turkish politics toward Europe and its
democratic principles."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Scientists Create 'DNA Computer'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Scientists have created a "DNA computer" from strands of
synthetic DNA they coaxed into solving relatively complex calculations,
according to a report in Thursday's issue of the journal Nature. The short-lived
chemical computer has no immediate practical applications, but it nudges the
fledgling technology of DNA computing further out of world of science fiction
and into the realm of the possible, the University of Wisconsin-Madison
researchers said. "It's kind of a non-automated computer -- an abacus of sorts
-- but it's an approach we're confident can be automated like a conventional
computer," said Lloyd Smith, a professor of chemistry.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average closed at 18,793.12 points on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, up 115.70 points from Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suns Defeat Grizzlies 95-92
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Jason Kidd scored 20 points and recorded
his fifth triple-double in 13 games, as the Phoenix Suns snapped a three-game
losing streak with a 95-92 victory over the Vancouver Grizzlies on Wednesday
night. Despite going 4-for-18 from the field, Kidd went 11-for-13 from the
free-throw line, and added 10 rebounds and 10 assists as the Suns won for only
the second time in seven games. Luc Longley scored 15 points for Phoenix, which
also snapped a five-game road losing streak.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</P>
</TEXT>
