<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sale of Radioactive Metals on Hold  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Energy Department has put on hold plans to sell
thousands of tons of radioactive scrap metal, mostly nickel, for use in
everything from braces to silverware.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Wednesday blocked the sale of 6,000 tons
of nickel, planned for later this year at a defunct uranium enrichment plant in
Oak Ridge, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
	   The department also was reviewing future plans for another 10,000 tons of
radioactive scrap metal -- mostly nickel left over from weapons production at
other facilities -- and likely will not allow it to go unrestricted into
civilian commerce.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists and some members of Congress have been sharply critical of
the recycling program, which had been approved by the Energy Department in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers who have pressed the Clinton administration to abandon the
recycling program applauded Richardson's action. ``Common sense is finally
beginning to take hold,'' said Rep. Ed Markey, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
	   British Nuclear Fuels Inc., which is under DOE contract to clean up the Oak
Ridge facility, planned to sell the nickel to private buyers for $41 million
later this year. The company contended the nickel could be cleaned to the point
that it no longer would pose a health risk.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale had been approved by the state of Tennessee and in 1997 by the
federal Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
	   Richardson said he was modifying the government's contract with British
Nuclear Fuels to block the impending sale until the Nuclear Regulatory
Commission establishes health standards for the material.
</P>
<P>
	   The nickel is contaminated with radiation throughout, as opposed to only on
the surface, which would make it easier to clean. The NRC has for some time
attempted to establish a standard for disposal of such material.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This will give the Nuclear Regulatory Commission time to develop national
standards ... (and) it will allow DOE to examine alternatives to free release,''
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear when the NRC planned to consider a proposed standard for such
scrap metals. The NRC regulates consumer products in which radiation has been
intentionally added, but has said the state had jurisdiction over the planned
nickel recycling at Oak Ridge.
</P>
<P>
	   While materials with surface contamination often can be cleaned, it is
unclear whether radioactivity that permeates a metal can be removed sufficiently
to be used in civilian manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
	   Rep. Ron Klink, D-Pa., said that consumers and steel producers alike were
concerned about the material being used in everything from braces and zippers to
silverware and toys. Steel companies were concerned about having to explain
having a radioactive metal -- no matter how small the dose level -- in such
products.
</P>
<P>
	   A senior DOE official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that while
these materials might eventually be considered safe, the public concerns raised
by the planned Oak Ridge sale prompted Richardson to reevaluate the matter.
</P>
<P>
	   Once the NRC sets national safety standards for the material, some
``restricted use'' sales might be permitted, although not into the general
market, this official said.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists and nuclear watchdog groups, meanwhile, want the recycling
program scrapped altogether.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What we're concerned about is this will be just window dressing,'' said
David Adelman, an attorney at the Natural Resources Defense Council, which sued
to try to stop the recycling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0212 </TRAILER>
