<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By RONALD BLUM AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   While Texas got another left-handed pitcher, signing Darren Oliver to a $19
million, three-year contract, the Milwaukee Brewers decided they needed another
shakeup.
</P>
<P>
	   Milwaukee traded right-hander Cal Eldred and infielder Jose Valentin to the
Chicago White Sox on Wednesday for right-handers Jaime Navarro and John Snyder.
A few hours later, the Brewers agreed to an $11 million, three-year contract
with shortstop Mark Loretta, avoiding salary arbitration.
</P>
<P>
	   Another player in arbitration, Los Angeles outfielder Todd Hollandsworth,
agreed to a $1.45 million, one-year contract.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitcher Rudy Seanez, who became a free agent after the season and then
accepted a salary arbitration offer from Atlanta, agreed to a $1.65 million,
one-year deal with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
	   Another free agent, catcher Jorge Fabregas, agreed to a minor league
contract with the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
	   Oliver, traded to St. Louis by Texas two years ago for shortstop Royce
Clayton and Todd Stottlemyre, joins a rotation that has added left-handers Kenny
Rogers and Justin Thompson.
</P>
<P>
	   Rogers was signed Dec. 29 and Thompson was acquired in the November trade
that sent Juan Gonzalez to Detroit. Texas had only four games started by
left-handers last season.
</P>
<P>
	   "I really don't think I could've imagined getting three left-handers with
their ability in the offseason," Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said. "I
think we're very fortunate."
</P>
<P>
	   The left-handed shift to the Rangers' rotation is an important part of their
attempt to dethrone the Yankees. New York, which has knocked Texas out of the
postseason three of the last four seasons, went just 19-14 against lefty
starters last season and hit 23 points lower against left-handers than righties.
</P>
<P>
	   The 29-year-old Oliver was 9-9 with a 4.26 ERA in 30 starts for St. Louis
last season.
</P>
<P>
	   An Eldred-for-Navarro swap had been rumored since last summer, when Eldred
was knocked out of the Brewers' starting rotation and Navarro fell into disfavor
with White Sox manager Jerry Manuel.
</P>
<P>
	   "Both will probably benefit from a change of scenery," Brewers general
manager Dean Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
	   Since the Brewers' seventh consecutive losing season ended in October,
Taylor has acquired seven pitchers and catcher Henry Blanco. Chicago was anxious
to unload Navarro.
</P>
<P>
	   "He didn't get the job done," Manuel said. "He had a lot of opportunities, a
lot of starts. Anybody that doesn't want to wear the White Sox uniform and be
proud of it, I don't want him around."
</P>
<P>
	   Eldred was 2-8 with a 7.79 ERA in 20 games last year, while Navarro was 8-13
with a 6.09 ERA.
</P>
<P>
	   Loretta, who made $1,495,000 last year, gets annual salaries of $2.5
million, $3.5 million and $5 million. He played every infield position for the
Brewers in 1999 and hit .290 with five homers and 67 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think I'm the senior Brewer on the team," he said. "It's pretty amazing.
Having a mutual commitment from the team for the first time, that just makes me
want to go out and prove they were right about me."
</P>
<P>
	   Hollandsworth, the 1996 NL Rookie of the Year, hit .284 last year with nine
homers and 32 RBIs in 92 games and made $850,000. The 26-year-old outfielder
went on the disabled list twice last year after missing more than 100 games in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Seanez, 31, was 6-1 last season with three saves and a 3.35 ERA in 56 games.
The right-hander did not pitch after Aug. 20 and underwent surgery on Sept. 21
to remove a bone spur from his elbow.
</P>
<P>
	   Fabregas, in the majors since 1994, adds experience to a Royals catching
group that includes Sal Fasano and Brian Johnson.
</P>
<P>
	   Fabregas has a .246 career average with the California Angels, Chicago White
Sox, Arizona Diamondbacks, New York Mets, Florida Marlins and Atlanta Braves. He
hit .206 last year in 82 games with the Marlins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0217 </TRAILER>
