<DOCNO> APW20000113.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Offense Boom Makes Comparisons Hard  </HEADLINE>
    By RONALD BLUM AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Even the newest Hall of Famers know it: 30 homers and 100
RBIs aren't what they used to be.
</P>
<P>
	   Tony Perez's career-high 129 RBIs would have placed him just sixth in the
National League last season.
</P>
<P>
	   Carlton Fisk's best, 107 RBIs, has already been topped four times by Mike
Piazza and once by Ivan Rodriguez, today's top offensive catchers.
</P>
<P>
	   "There might be something in the baseball, the ballparks. I even heard about
El Nino," Perez said Wednesday, a day after he and Fisk were elected to the Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
	   A record 45 players hit 30 or more homers last year. Fisk topped the mark
just once, in 1987, when there were 28 30-homer hitters. Perez topped it twice,
one of 17 players to do it 1969 and among 19 the following year.
</P>
<P>
	   The NL's batting average of .268 last season was its highest since 1939.
</P>
<P>
	   "Balls didn't go that far when we played, Tony," Fisk said, citing the
strength and conditioning programs almost all players are involved in these
days. "The strike zone is different."
</P>
<P>
	   Fans, they both agree, love the offense.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's good for the recognition of the game," Fisk said, "not so good for the
pitchers' earned run averages."
</P>
<P>
	   After traveling to New York for a news conference, both still seemed a
little overwhelmed at their election.
</P>
<P>
	   They kept thinking back to 1975, when Fisk hit his famous 12th-inning home
run at Fenway Park to win Game 6 of the World Series. The following night, Perez
hit a two-run homer as Cincinnati overcame a 3-0 deficit to win Game 7.
</P>
<P>
	   "There was a certain alignment of the stars that evening," Fisk said, "and
there's an alignment of at least two stars this afternoon."
</P>
<P>
	   Because of travel delays from Puerto Rico, Perez didn't arrive in New York
until 4 a.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't want to sleep anyway," he said. "I didn't want to wake up and see
this is just a dream."
</P>
<P>
	   Perez's election was a dream of many Latin fans. He's the first Cuban
elected to the Hall by the Baseball Writers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
	   He joins Latins such as Luis Aparicio, Roberto Clemente, Juan Marichal and
Orlando Cepeda in the Hall, and there's sure to be many more in coming years.
Latins have won three of the last four AL MVPs and one of the last two in the
NL, and the percentage of Puerto Ricans, Dominicans, Venezuelans, Cubans,
Nicaraguans and Mexicans is rising.
</P>
<P>
	   Teams have signed more Latins, and their success has caused teams to
increase their scouting efforts in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
	   Manny Ramirez (Dominican Republic) led the AL with 165 RBIs last season,
followed by Rafael Palmeiro (Cuba) with 148 and Carlos Delgado (Puerto Rico)
with 134. Sammy Sosa (Dominican) was third in the NL at 141, and Vladimir
Guerrero (Dominican) was fifth at 131.
</P>
<P>
	   "They put up tremendous numbers and they have great, great years," Perez
said. "You have to be proud of these kids."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0217 </TRAILER>
