<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Action Urged on IOC Drug Agency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- The new World Anti-Doping Agency is ready to
get down to business, with governments looking for fast action to establish its
credentials as a watchdog curbing the threat of drug use in sports.
</P>
<P>
	At its first meeting today at the International Olympic Committee's Lausanne
headquarters, the new agency faces pressure to improve drug-testing procedures
and to prove its own independence.
</P>
<P>
	Officials from the United States, Australia and Canada stressed the urgency of
stepping up antidoping measures after they met Wednesday with IOC president Juan
Antonio Samaranch and WADA's provisional head Dick Pound, an IOC vice president.
</P>
<P>
	``We're on a very short run to the Sydney Olympics,'' U.S. drug czar Barry
McCaffrey said. ``I would hope that at each step we will have, in a transparent
manner, concrete results.''
</P>
<P>
	He called for ``transparent, accountable and effective new antidoping measures
beginning prior to the Sydney Games.''
</P>
<P>
	Australian Justice Minister Amanda Vanstone said she would ``particularly like
to see a commitment toward certain steps being taken to guarantee that Sydney is
an Olympics where the test result management can be seen as being transparent,
accountable and consistent.''
</P>
<P>
	Today's meeting is a very important day for the IOC, Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
	Although McCaffrey and other ministers backed the IOC's and Pound's role in
getting the WADA going, the White House drugs adviser again said the agency
should move away from the IOC and its home city.
</P>
<P>
	``There is agreement, I think, among all of us that this agency must commit
itself to being outside of Lausanne, to being under new leadership (after) going
through an interim process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	A number of cities have expressed interest in hosting WADA on a permanent
basis, and the IOC plans a bidding process. Details of that process have yet to
be decided.
</P>
<P>
	WADA's tasks include establishing a list of banned substances, coordinating
unannounced out-of-competition drug testing, developing standards for collecting
and analyzing samples, pushing for unified drug sanctions and promoting
research.
</P>
<P>
	The agency, established in November, groups IOC representatives, sports
federations, athletes and governments.
</P>
<P>
	``We'll have to learn from each other,'' Canadian sports minister Denis Coderre
said. ``I think we can.''
</P>
<P>
	Twelve members were initially appointed. The agency will be governed by a board
of at least 10 members and no more than 35.
</P>
<P>
	The United States, Australia and Canada, here as observers, are part of a
consultative group of governments on antidoping measures formed in November in
Sydney. Coderre emphasized that WADA must represent governments worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0219 </TRAILER>
