<HEADLINE> Chechen Leader Doesn't Want US Aid  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chechnya does not want U.S. weapons and hopes for a
negotiated settlement with the Russian government to end the bloodshed in the
breakaway province, a Chechen official says.
</P>
<P>
	   Ilyas Akhmadov, who serves under Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov in
Grozny, said he is not seeking American assistance or mediation of the conflict
but only understanding for the Chechens' desire to stop Russian military
attacks.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration on Wednesday ruled out a U.S. role in mediation
between Russia and the rebels in its province of Chechnya, and suggested
Europeans could take on the job.
</P>
<P>
	   But as Russian forces resumed an offensive in Chechnya on Wednesday, there
was no indication Moscow would heed Chechen appeals or U.S. advice that it seek
a political solution to the threatened secession. Accusing Chechen rebels of
terrorism elsewhere in Russia, the Kremlin repeatedly has said it will not talk
until the rebellion is wiped out.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We don't believe that the result of the use of force is going to be the
melting away of resistance,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said.
``We believe that the Russians are in a cul-de-sac, that they cannot by their
current strategy come to the end of road because there is no end to this kind of
fighting.''
</P>
<P>
	   Akhmadov, speaking at an academic institute Wednesday evening before planned
meetings with members of Congress and others today, also said Russian soldiers
continue to sell weapons to Chechen fighters and claimed no knowledge of any
terrorist activity by Chechens.
</P>
<P>
	   He estimated 10,000 Chechen civilians and about 250 fighters have died in
the conflict, but he declined to estimate Russian casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   ``God forbid, I don't want the United States to bomb Russia or give us
weapons,'' Akhmadov said. His remarks were translated from Russian.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The only aim of our government is to stop the total destruction of our
people, and we are prepared to do anything,'' he said. ``We are prepared to
negotiate.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said Russia tends to lament its mistakes but only stops aggression ``when
it is drowned in its own blood. It's a horrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the State Department is asking Russia for clarification of
reports that Chechen males between ages 18 and 60, would be detained to see
whether they had ties to rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is essential that Russia respect the fundamental human rights of
civilians in and around Chechnya, not endanger the lives of noncombatants, and
ensure freedom of movement for displaced persons,'' spokesman Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
	   Akhmadov said he appreciated the American concern, but added, ``The issue
here is whether the State Department will be satisfied with the explanation of
the Russian government and what its reaction will be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0219 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cos. Plan To Appeal Safety Breaches  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Three companies plan to appeal fines of more than $500,000
for safety violations in the fatal collapse of a giant crane at the Milwaukee
Brewers' partially completed ballpark last summer.
</P>
<P>
	   The crane was lifting a piece of the stadium's retractable roof when it fell
July 14, killing three ironworkers.
</P>
<P>
	   In issuing citations Wednesday, government regulators said Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries of America, Danny's Construction Co. and Neil F. Lampson Inc. allowed
workers to lift a 400-ton roof section that was too heavy for the crane,
especially in the windy conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   Spokesmen for the three companies denied committing safety violations and
said they would seek to have the fines lifted.
</P>
<P>
	   Mitsubishi, the contractor building the roof, was fined $240,500, by the
Occupational Safety and Health Administration. Danny's Construction Co., which
employed the ironworkers, was fined $168,000. Lampson, which leased the 567-foot
crane to Mitsubishi, was fined $131,300.
</P>
<P>
	   "We feel that if these companies had been in compliance with our
regulations, possibly this tragedy would not have occurred," OSHA Area Director
George Yoksas said.
</P>
<P>
	   When the accident happened, the National Weather Service said winds were
gusting at up to 26 mph. The accident caused $100 million in damage and delayed
the opening of Miller Park by a year, to April of 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Investigators relied on a 78-second videotape, taken by OSHA employees who
were on the site looking into an earlier minor accident.
</P>
<P>
	   The dramatic video, released Wednesday, captures the entire collapse,
beginning with someone's routine discussion of the project. Suddenly, a
12-second grinding screech is heard, followed by two loud crashes.
</P>
<P>
	   "What's going on here?" asks one person, as a worker is seen bolting from
near the crane's base. "Watch it!" someone shouts as the blue crane collapses
into the stadium.
</P>
<P>
	   Yoksas declined to say exactly what the agency thought caused the accident.
OSHA has no plans to issue a report on it, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is only the first step," said Robert Donohoo, deputy district attorney
for Milwaukee County. He said there were months of work to be done in the
district attorney's investigation for possible criminal law violations.
</P>
<P>
	   Frank Busalacchi, chairman of the stadium board's construction committee,
said the board did not plan any attempt to have the firms that got citations
taken off the project.
</P>
<P>
	   "The message we're going to send back to our contractors is that they're
going to have to adjust to make sure this work site is safe," Busalacchi said.
</P>
<P>
	   In its citation, OSHA said Mitsubishi loaded a section of the roof beyond
the crane's capacity. The agency also said Mitsubishi failed to keep employees
clear of the 400-ton block and allowed workers to be hoisted in excessively
windy conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   The citation is a willful violation, meaning that the acts were done "with
an intentional disregard for or plain indifference to the requirements."
</P>
<P>
	   Mitsubishi also received a non-willful violation for not properly
considering the crane manufacturer's specifications for how much to lift in
winds of more than 20 mph.
</P>
<P>
	   Mitsubishi's attorney, Franklyn Gimbel, said the company denies the claims
and will be requesting an informal conference with OSHA officials in an attempt
to erase or modify the tickets.
</P>
<P>
	   "To claim willfulness of these violations suggests that there was some
conscious misdeeds, and we just don't believe that's the fact," Gimbel said.
</P>
<P>
	   Danny's Construction was issued a willful citation for failing to keep its
workers clear of the 400-ton block of roof and a non-willful citation for
operating the crane in excessive winds and for using a platforms on the work
site when hoist, ladders or other scaffolding was possible.
</P>
<P>
	   "We deny the allegation, and will be proceeding through the established
channels," company president Willie Mizell said.
</P>
<P>
	   OSHA gave Lampson a willful violation for overloading the crane and a
serious violation for not keeping the area of the crane clear during the morning
lift. The company also received a citation because charts on when to use the
crane did not take into consideration the effects of wind on the load.
</P>
<P>
	   The company plans to appeal the citations, said Bill Lampson, president of
the Kennewick, Wash.-based company.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's absolutely inappropriate," Lampson said. "We leased the crane to
Mitsubishi and we're being cited for violations."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0220 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
