<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins' Armstrong Chases the Ring  </HEADLINE>
    By STEVEN WINE AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Miami Dolphins defensive end Trace Armstrong will line
up Saturday against the Jacksonville Jaguars, chasing Mark Brunell and the dream
of a Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
	   The playoff game will be Armstrong's 11th in 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
	   "You start to develop this feeling of urgency," he says, "because you know
you're not going to be back too many more times."
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong is old by NFL standards, a thirty-something veteran admired by
Dolphins teammates for his dogged pursuit of a Super Bowl title. The story has a
familiar ring because Armstrong, like Dan Marino, is ring-less.
</P>
<P>
	   But that's not the only reason Armstrong, at 34, continues to butt heads
with 325-pound offensive tackles.
</P>
<P>
	   "I still love to play," Armstrong says. "I even like our preseason
scrimmages. The ultimate goal is the Super Bowl, but I just enjoy putting on my
uniform every day."
</P>
<P>
	   This week, he's being lauded for perhaps the best performance of his career.
Armstrong was named NFL defensive player of the week after his three sacks
helped Miami beat Seattle 20-17 in the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   Armstrong watches retirement speculation swirl around Marino and understands
his teammate's reluctance to quit. Armstrong is the same way.
</P>
<P>
	   The former Florida Gators star plans to go back to school for a law degree
eventually, but not yet. He expects to be with the Dolphins again next season.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're going to have to run me off," he says. "You have to realize -- I've
been a football player since I was 7.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's one of the strange things about this game. You're 34, and in regular
society that's still a fairly young man. But they're starting to tell you you're
too old to do what you've done your whole life."
</P>
<P>
	   As president of the NFL Players Association, Armstrong has occasionally
clashed with coach Jimmy Johnson on practice schedules and other issues
involving the union. And Armstrong wasn't happy that his playing time was
reduced when Johnson went to a four-man rotation at defensive end.
</P>
<P>
	   But the change might help Armstrong's longevity. He's no longer a starter
and plays primarily on passing downs, a role he filled beautifully at Seattle.
His three sacks were a career best and a team playoff record.
</P>
<P>
	   "Trace has always been an excellent player for us," Johnson said. "The role
we have him in probably utilizes his talent more than if we had him as an
every-down player. And it keeps him fresher and healthier and is going to extend
his career."
</P>
<P>
	   There are few signs that Armstrong is slowing down. Even with his playing
time limited, he had 7 1/2 sacks this season, increasing his total to 40 in five
years with the Dolphins. He's a trim 270 pounds, if that's possible, and hasn't
missed a game because of injury since 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   "That man ain't old," teammate Daryl Gardener says. "Don't let him fool
you."
</P>
<P>
	   Still, 177 NFL games have taken a toll on Armstrong's body. At this late
date in the season, not even a three-sack performance can make him feel 24
again.
</P>
<P>
	   "I feel like about 54," he said with a laugh. "Lots of fires to put out, but
that's the playoffs. It's a grind. You really come in almost bankrupt
physically. This is a time when you've got to reach and dig and try to find
something to get out there and play with."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0223 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0099 </DOCNO>
