<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colts' Bennett To Miss Playoff Game  </HEADLINE>
    By HANK LOWENKRON AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Linebacker Cornelius Bennett, the team's leading
tackler in his first year with the Indianapolis Colts, will be inactive when
they face the Tennessee Titans in an AFC divisional playoff game on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors checked the condition of the left knee Bennett injured in the team's
regular-season finale this week and decided he needed more time to heal.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's out for this game," coach Jim Mora said. "Hopefully, he'll be healed
enough to play for the AFC championship if we advance."
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett suffered a torn medial collateral ligament and a stretched posterior
cruciate ligament in the knee when he was blocked on his first defensive play of
the game at Buffalo. He said last week that he was hopeful he could play against
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
	   The injury was not related to similar damage to the anterior cruciate
ligament that required surgery after Bennett played in last year's Super Bowl
with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
	   "Any time you lose a player the caliber of Cornelius, it's tough on a
defense. But we have other guys who are expected to come in and play well," said
defensive end Chad Bratzke, who led the Colts with a career-high franchise
record of 12 as Indianapolis went 13-3 in 1999. "We have to rally behind each
other, and other guys are going to have to step up."
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett will be replaced in the starting lineup by Bertrand Berry, a
third-round draft pick out of Notre Dame in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a great opportunity for me. It's one that I've waited on my whole
career," Berry said. "To start in a playoff game, that's what every guy who ever
played football dreamed about, from a little kid up to an adult."
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett said he told Berry "he's just got to step up and be the man."
</P>
<P>
	   "No one expected me to come in and play the way I did this season, except
for myself. I came in and made an impact, and he can do the same thing."
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett, 34, was drafted by Indianapolis in 1987, but went to Buffalo as
part of a three-team trade that brought Eric Dickerson from the Rams to the
Colts. With Buffalo, he played in four straight Super Bowls -- all losses -- and
last year with Atlanta became the only player in NFL history to be on the losing
team in five Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
	   Bennett signed with the Colts as an unrestricted free agent and led the
Colts this season with 114 tackles. Eighty of those were solo efforts.
</P>
<P>
	   Mora also said that defensive tackle Ellis Johnson was expected to be in the
starting lineup against Tennessee on Sunday. Johnson, who like Bennett started
all 16 games on defense, missed the second half of the Buffalo game with a deep
bruise near his left knee. Johnson finished the season with 7 1/2 sacks, the
second highest total on the team, and was in on 76 tackles. He practiced
Wednesday for the first time since the injury.
</P>
<P>
	   "He did everything," Mora said. "He should be ready."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0224 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
