<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vikes Playing Role of Underdog  </HEADLINE>
    By ARNIE STAPLETON AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- The Minnesota Vikings are 9-2 since Jeff George
took over at quarterback. Their six losses were by a total of 22 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Their defense kept opponents out of the end zone in 30 of 46 trips inside
the 20, and they have one of the NFL's most dangerous return tandems in Robert
Tate and Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the Vikings (11-6) find themselves in the unfamiliar role of underdog
as they prepare for their trip to the St. Louis to face the top-seeded Rams
(13-3) at the Trans World Dome on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rams lost to the only team (Tennessee) on their schedule that finished
with a winning record. Their other 11 opponents were a combined 60-116.
</P>
<P>
	   So how can the Vikings be a touchdown underdog?
</P>
<P>
	   "I never look at it as though we're the underdog, but I never look at it as
if we're supposed to win by 14 points, either," Cris Carter said. "Whatever the
spread, it doesn't really matter to me."
</P>
<P>
	   What does matter, Carter insisted, is playoff experience.
</P>
<P>
	   And the Vikings have much more than the Rams even though none of them have a
Super Bowl ring like St. Louis lineman Adam Timmerman, who won a title in Green
Bay in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's far more pressure than you've been under and you do get nervous and
you do have anxiety and you do have concerns," Carter said. "The only teams that
say experience is not vital are the teams that don't have any."
</P>
<P>
	   As much as they hate to admit it, the Vikings are taking their cue from the
1998 Atlanta Falcons, the upstarts who derailed the Super Bowl favorites on the
road in a noisy dome a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   The Vikings are planning to run the ball to keep the Rams' high-octane
offense on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
	   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
	   That's what the Falcons did last year in their stunning upset of the Vikings
in the conference championship at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
	   The Rams cruised through the regular season with a wide-open offense, an
opportunistic defense and solid special teams, exactly what the Vikings did a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   "They could be the Vikings of '98," Moss said. "But some bad things happened
to the Vikings of '98."
</P>
<P>
	   Like slipping up in the playoffs despite being a big favorite.
</P>
<P>
	   The Vikings don't view themselves as inferior in any way to the well-rested
Rams, however.
</P>
<P>
	   "Both teams are fast," Robert Griffith said. "For lack of a better word,
it's going to be a track meet. We just match up really well."
</P>
<P>
	   With Moss, Carter, George and Robert Smith on one side and MVP Kurt Warner,
Isaac Bruce, Marshall Faulk and Az-Zahir Hakim on the other, "you're not ever
going to see any better talent on the football field," Carter said.
</P>
<P>
	   But, as topsy-turvy as the NFL has become, Carter would like to believe
there's still such a thing as paying your dues, especially in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a process that Dallas went through with San Francisco, it's a process
that Green Bay went through with Dallas," he said. "It's a process that we went
through with Green Bay and also that Denver went through. And all those teams,
they had experience. And if you look at last year's Super Bowl, I think that
Denver's experience outweighed Atlanta's."
</P>
<P>
	   But teammate Robert Smith isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
	   "A lot of people are going to use that against St. Louis and I'm sure
they're tired of hearing about it," Smith said. "They're tired of hearing about
how they don't have experience, how they didn't play anybody in the regular
season, all those things. To me, they don't mean a whole lot.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a whole new season. They've got talented players. We've got talented
players."
</P>
<P>
	   Vikings coach Dennis Green noted that the Rams went from 4-12 to 13-3, "and
that's the best experience you can have as a football player."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
