<DOCNO> APW20000113.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titans CB Walker Is on Probation  </HEADLINE>
    By TERESA M. WALKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Tennessee Titans have made a habit of dealing
with problems off the field and not letting them become distractions. Coach Jeff
Fisher thinks nothing will stop them now.
</P>
<P>
	   The fact that starting cornerback Denard Walker is on probation for
assaulting the mother of his son last summer became known on Wednesday as the
Titans (14-3) prepared to visit the Indianapolis Colts (13-3) in the AFC
divisional playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   "Typically, I think these things come up at the worst possible time," Fisher
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not going to become a distraction. The timing's not good. Somewhere,
somehow there was some motivation on someone's behalf to draw attention to
themselves. That's out of our hands. We'll deal with it and go on."
</P>
<P>
	   Walker, the Titans' starting left cornerback the past three seasons, talked
briefly with Fisher at the end of practice. But he declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
	   His agent, John Hamilton, issued a release late Wednesday describing the
incident as a "minor altercation" with a "former friend." The statement said
Walker entered a "conditional plea," and Hamilton said that did not involve
pleading guilty.
</P>
<P>
	   Walker pleaded guilty on Aug. 11 to assault for an incident June 26 at his
apartment, according to Assistant District Attorney Carlton Drumwright.
</P>
<P>
	   According to police reports, Rhonda Lynn Chesser, the mother of Walker's
19-month-old son, said Walker threatened, punched and tried to strangle her.
Police reports said Chesser had bruises on her legs, arms and face with marks on
her neck and told police that Walker also threatened several times that "he
could kill her."
</P>
<P>
	   Two days later, Walker gave a statement to police that he and Chesser argued
and "basically wrestled on the floor, with some punches thrown not to be
harmful." He said he received "marks around my neck, with some minor scratches"
during the fight.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the plea agreement, Walker must stay away from Chesser, attend
weekly domestic abuse classes and stay out of trouble for 11 months, 29 days.
Drumwright said it was the standard agreement for a first-time offender, and the
incident can be expunged after he completes probation.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither Fisher nor the NFL would comment on whether the league had punished
Walker. Any player who pleads guilty to assault faces mandatory counseling and
other discipline that can include fines and suspensions.
</P>
<P>
	   Fisher said the NFL has provided courses, seminars and counseling the past
two years to try and prevent domestic abuse.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a serious issue. Domestic violence is an extremely serious issue in
our society today, and Denard's case, it was dealt with," Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
	   It's the fourth incident off the field that the Titans have dealt with since
training camp.
</P>
<P>
	   End Pratt Lyons broke a vertebra in his neck in a car accident the first
week of training camp and missed the entire season. Tackle Josh Evans missed the
first four games of the season under a substance abuse suspension, and safety
Marcus Robertson needed 150 stitches in his face after a motorcycle crash Dec.
27. He missed the regular-season finale.
</P>
</TEXT>
