<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson's Arms To Live in NFL Infamy  </HEADLINE>
    By JOSEPH WHITE AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- In addition to his $50,000 fine and one-game suspension
for fighting and striking an official, Tre Johnson figures he's the NFL's new
poster boy for bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
	   "To hit an official is wrong," the Washington Redskins guard said Wednesday.
"There's no doubt. It's clearly stated in the rules. We get a book and video at
training camp, and I'm sure that incident will be added to it as a
what-not-to-do example."
</P>
<P>
	   Nonetheless, Johnson said he would appeal his punishment, handed down
Tuesday as part of a record $154,000 in fines issued to 23 Redskins and Lions
players for the fracas that broke out in the second half of Saturday's playoff
game. The one-week suspension, which takes effect the first week of next season,
will cost Johnson about $135,000 in salary.
</P>
<P>
	   "No one intentionally went after any referee," Johnson said. "The referee's
just doing his job. It's a matter of happenstance. It wasn't as malicious, I
guess, as it was made out to be. I stopped. It wasn't like I had to be stopped.
I stopped as soon as I realized the referee was involved. It was an accident.
It's a lot of circumstance surrounding a lot of emotional energy."
</P>
<P>
	   The Redskins can find two pieces of good news from the fight and its
fallout. One is that Johnson won't miss this Saturday's playoff game at Tampa
Bay. The other is a renewed sense of team togetherness and swagger.
</P>
<P>
	   "Looking back at it, it was a positive in a way," fullback Larry Centers
said. "It shows the mentality we have to have in order to stay alive in the
playoffs. It's going to be a fight every week."
</P>
<P>
	   Not literally, one would hope. But the way the players rushed to the defense
of quarterback Brad Johnson galvanized an all-for-one, one-for-all mindset that
has helped the Redskins break a six-year playoff drought. In past seasons, it
would have been hard to imagine players rushing onto the field in a similar way.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we have a definite sense of unity on the team," Tre Johnson said.
"We watch each other's backs. It's a shame everyone has to get fined over
something like that, but it makes its positive statements too."
</P>
<P>
	   The fight started when Detroit defensive end Robert Porcher threw a hard
block at Brad Johnson during an interception return. Brad Johnson, who later
said he was emulating his favorite WWF wrestlers, then threw Porcher to the
ground. A free-for-all ensued, and Tre Johnson was singled out because he kept
flailing his arms and struck the line judge after the other players had settled
down.
</P>
<P>
	   Many players were surprised by the amount and breadth of the fines. Tight
end James Jenkins, for example, was fined $1,500 for "unnecessarily entering a
fight area -- inactive," meaning essentially that he was guilty of being in the
wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
	   "I had nothing to do with the fight," Jenkins said. "I wasn't involved with
it. I don't know what area they're talking about, the fighting area. I was in on
the play, the fight broke out, I turned around, and then I walked away.
Everybody on the field should be fined if they fine me."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
