<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some NYPD cars to be equipped with cameras  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Starting next week, 33 NYPD highway patrol cruisers will
hit the road equipped with small video cameras to record officers - as well as
the actions of people they stop.
<P>
	   The NYPD comes late to this bit of technology. Many other police departments
nationwide have had such devices in their patrol cars for more than 10 years.
Police Commissioner Howard Safir, head of the department since 1996, said
Wednesday he's not certain why it took so long for the NYPD to install cameras.
</P>
<P>
	   "But I'm very committed to technology - this is something we ought to be
doing," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Meyers, director of the New York Civil Rights Coalition, said the
cameras can't hurt. "It will be there as another reminder to the cops - like the
Miranda warning," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   But Meyers added: "There's no telling what can happen outside the range of
the camera."
</P>
<P>
	   Safir says he's certain the cameras will protect citizens and officers. A
field test begins next week.
</P>
<P>
	   "It will give good corroboration to violations and I think it will be very
protective of the officers," he said. "Let's face it. No one likes to get a
summons, and many people who get summonses make allegations against police
officers of being discourteous, of being abusive, of using excessive force. This
will be a video record of what actually took place."
</P>
<P>
	   The small cameras, which cost $4,500 each, are attached to the rear view
window. Officers wear a wireless microphone clipped to a recorder attached to
their belts to capture any words exchanged up to 500 feet from the car.
</P>
<P>
	   The camera is activated when the police car's lights and sirens go on. The
officer turns on the microphone and recorder while getting out of the car. A
button can be used to zoom in on a license plate.
</P>
<P>
	   Officers can also coordinate the videotape with the car's radar device,
which can record the speed of the car right on the tape, Safir added.
</P>
<P>
	   The videotape is in the locked trunk. The only person who has the key is the
officer's supervisor. At the end of every tour, the tape, able to record for six
hours, is retrieved. The NYPD's legal department is researching how long the
tapes should be kept before being destroyed.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, officers seem receptive to the cameras, Safir said. And, if the test
period proves successful, every highway patrol car will be equipped with
cameras. In the future, officials will evaluate whether the cameras should be in
other patrol vehicles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 0245 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Close Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices closed higher Thursday as investors bought
up biotechnology, chemical and other domestic-demand related issues. The dollar
dipped against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 155.87 points, or
0.83 percent, to 18,833.29. On Wednesday, the average closed down 173.50 points,
or 0.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar was trading at 105.64 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange market at
3 p.m. (1 a.m. EST) Thursday, down 0.12 yen from late Wednesday, and below its
late New York level of 105.99 yen overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, Wall Street's overnight gains boosted investor
confidence in Japanese shares. But market players focused more on stocks
centering on domestic demand such biotechnology and chemical companies than
globally-oriented high-tech and telecommunications issues.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is clear now that the market will not rise on the strength of
information technology shares alone, and investors are looking for their next
target," said Kazunori Shimono, manager of the equity trading section at
Tokyo-Mitsubishi Personal Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the day's biggest gainers were Mitsubishi Chemical Corp. and Asahi
Chemical Industry Co.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 40.02, or 0.3 percent,
to close at 11,551.10 on gains by blue-chip industrial stocks such as 3M and
Merck.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-rich Nasdaq Composite index, however, fell 71.30 to 3,849.89.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section rose 1.05 points, or 0.06 percent, to close at 1,657.97. On Wednesday,
the TOPIX closed down 21.90 points, or 1.30 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency trading, U.S. investors sold dollars to take profit from the
greenback's recent gains, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Although near-term dollar-bullish sentiment is unchanged, U.S. and European
investors sold dollars to square their positions in preparation for future
purchases," said Shuji Takano, assistant manager of foreign exchange at ABN AMRO
Bank.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors are eyeing the upcoming meeting of senior financial officials from
the Group of Seven leading industrial nations in Tokyo on Jan. 22 for further
clues on the greenback's moves in the longer term.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 108.72 yen, up from 108.48 yen
late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8050
percent from 1.7950 on Wednesday. Its price was down 0.09 point to 100.79.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0257 </TRAILER>
