<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Closes Chechen Borders  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNA DOLGOV Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SLEPTSOVSKAYA, Russia (AP) -- Men trying to escape the bloodshed of Chechnya
came to the border and were turned back by Russian soldiers for the same brusque
reason.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The problem is that you are not 60 yet,'' said the stern,
Kalashnikov-toting border guard. The men could do nothing but turn and walk
away.
</P>
<P>
	   They were feeling the sting of a new Russian policy to crack down on rebels
who have shown recent signs of resurgence. A top Russian military commander,
Col. Gen. Viktor Kazantsev, on Tuesday ordered that all males between 10 and 60
years old be detained and checked for possible rebel ties.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the military's orders, all roads between Chechnya and the neighboring
Russian region of Ingushetia were closed Wednesday to such males.
</P>
<P>
	   The order also affected those who wanted to get back into Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
	   Vakhid Ashakhanov, 41, said he left Chechnya on Tuesday to drive a friend's
daughter to a hospital in Ingushetia. The girl, 16-year-old Zarema Shishkhanova,
was suffering from an acute form of tuberculosis she developed after living for
several months in a cold basement.
</P>
<P>
	   After the unexpected tightening of border regulations, Ashakhanov was cut
off from his two teen-age sons, who remained in their home village of Gikaly,
just outside Grozny, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They can't leave (Chechnya), and I can't go back,'' Ashakhanov said.
</P>
<P>
	   Shishkhanova's father, Gilany Shishkhanov, showed his daughter's hospital
admission record to the Russian guards -- but with no success.
</P>
<P>
	   At 61, Shishkhanov was old enough to go back to Chechnya, where he had left
his 4- and 6-year-old granddaughters. But having no money to pay for a ride
home, Shishkhanov said he could not leave without his younger friend.
</P>
<P>
	   A straight-backed, dignified-looking man wearing a traditional sheepskin
hat, Shishkhanov was wiping away tears from his wrinkled face.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Let God be their judge,'' Shishkhanov said, turning around to walk back to
Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
	   The new policy brought sharp criticism from the watchdog agency Human Rights
Watch.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Chechen males are now effectively trapped in a war zone where they face
grave threats to their lives,'' said Peter Bouckaert, an agency worker in
Ingushetia. ``The Russian authorities are deliberately violating their
international obligations.''
</P>
<P>
	   The orders to screen Chechen men came after rebel fighters launched
counterattacks in the key towns of Shali and Argun, driving back federal troops.
The rebel offensive caught the Russians by surprise, embarrassing senior
commanders who had been predicting imminent victory.
</P>
<P>
	   Kazantsev said Russian forces had been too lax in making sure that all
rebels had been driven out of the towns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0313 </TRAILER>
