<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 06:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astronaut Makes Rommel Remark  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The commander of the next space shuttle mission
jokingly told a German astronaut ``Rommel would have been proud of you'' after
he drove an armored personnel carrier during training.
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin Kregel made the remark about the Nazi general Wednesday on a vacant
launch pad at Kennedy Space Center where crew members were practicing shuttle
escape maneuvers. Part of their training includes driving a M-113 armored
personnel carrier away from the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
	   Gerhard Thiele, who is part of Kregel's six-member crew on space shuttle
Endeavour, laughed when he heard the remark.
</P>
<P>
	   Endeavour is scheduled to launch Jan. 31 for an Earth-mapping mission.
</P>
<P>
	   Erwin Rommel was known as ``The Desert Fox'' during World War II and led
Germany's Afrika Korps against Allied forces in Libya in 1941.
</P>
<P>
	   He repeatedly outmaneuvered his opponents but was overcome by British forces
at El Alamein, Egypt, in 1942. In 1944, Rommel was implicated in a plot to kill
Adolf Hitler and chose to swallow a fatal dose of poison rather than face trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0646 </TRAILER>
