<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 07:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans Investment Incentives  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is road-testing some ideas he will
highlight during his State of the Union address at the end of this month,
including a plan to sweeten the incentives for businesses to invest in some of
America's hard-luck rural and urban areas.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton travels to New York City today, where he will help launch a
small-business development center at predominantly Hispanic Boricua College in
Brooklyn, and describe his proposal to more than double a tax credit for
investment in what the Clinton administration calls ``new markets.''
</P>
<P>
	   The incentive program, which Clinton first unveiled last year, is supposed
to make investment in poor regions of this country as attractive as investment
in less-developed countries abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the time for these kinds of initiatives because for the first time
in many, many years we have an economy where jobs are looking for people,''
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said today on CNN. ``That means we need to
make sure that that supply (of capital) is there and there in every part of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
	   While many Republicans on Capitol Hill support the economic empowerment
agenda behind the new markets proposal, Clinton was unable to push the entire
package through Congress and is trying again this year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What the president's trying to do is inspire corporate America and
investors to take a second look in their own backyard,'' White House economic
adviser Gene Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed 25 percent tax credit would leverage $15 billion a year in
investment over five years, but cost the government just a third of that,
Sperling said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``So this tax credit would now leverage $15 billion of equity investment in
lower income parts of America, both urban and rural,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
	   For much of the rest of the day, Clinton was participating in a separate
economic development project shepherded by the Rev. Jesse Jackson. Jackson's
Wall Street Project is a 3-year-old effort to involve the titans of New York
City finance in minority business ventures.
</P>
<P>
	   The program, and a similar venture in Chicago, ``are set to partner major
venture capital partnerships in the country with minority vendors and minority
business, giving them better access to capital and strategies for economic
growth in the long term,'' said Barbara Proctor, media relations director for
Jackson's sponsoring Rainbow/PUSH Coalition.
</P>
<P>
	   During a midday speech to the project's annual conference, Clinton is
expected to focus on the economic successes of his seven-year administration,
and his efforts to include everyone in America's current economic boom.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We ought to dedicate ourselves to bringing opportunity to the people and
places who have been left behind,'' Clinton said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton was attending a gala evening party honoring the project on the floor
of the New York Stock Exchange. The exchange is a co-sponsor of the Wall Street
Project, exchange spokesman Ray Pellecchia said.
</P>
<P>
	   This is the third year the exchange has opened its trading floor for the
party, although an ice storm canceled Clinton's scheduled visit last year,
Pellecchia said.
</P>
<P>
	   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton opened the Wall Street Project conference
on Wednesday. The three-day program also features address by four Clinton
administration Cabinet secretaries, top officials such as Sperling and Wall
Street leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 0758 </TRAILER>
