<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 29.47; Nasdaq Up 37.94  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher in early trading today as
technology shares bounced back from a two-day slump and the broader market
gained strength from a report of relatively modest inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 29.47 at 11,580.57.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 4.58 at 1,436.83, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 37.94 at
3,887.96.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose after the Labor Department said that while prices at the
wholesale level shot up 3 percent in 1999, the biggest increase in nine years,
most of the increase came from the volatile energy sector. Excluding energy,
wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent last year, a more modest showing than in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   For December, the Producer Price Index, which measures inflation pressures
before they reach the consumer, was up 0.3 percent, right on target with many
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   The reports boosted investors' confidence that inflation is not escalating
quickly enough to merit sharp interest-rate increases by the Federal Reserve.
The Fed raised interest rates three times in 1999 in an effort to keep inflation
at bay, and in recent sessions, stocks have been pressured by fears that another
series of rate hikes are ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Higher interest rates can hurt stocks by cutting into corporate profits as
it becomes more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   Beyond the interest rate debate, Apple Computer rose 7 3/16 to 94 3/4 after
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on the stock to "outperform" from
"neutral." An analyst said Apple shares should reach 120 in a year.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Trust soared 31 1/8 to 110 after agreeing to be acquired by Charles
Schwab for $2.7 billion, or about $129 per share.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-8 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 126.20 million shares, behind Wednesday's
early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.39 to 494.43.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.8 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 2.1 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
up 0.05 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 1.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
