<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 10:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Centralize all police functions  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A proposed restructuring of the city's troubled
police department would centralize command, replenish top jobs lost to
retirement and attrition and put brass on night and weekend shifts.
<P>
	   City Manager Saundra Kee Borges on Wednesday released a national
consultant's report and her recommendations to Mayor Mike Peters and the City
Council. The report, prepared by Carroll Buracker &AMP; Associates, was ordered in
October.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the proposal, the department would be headed by a chief, two assistant
chiefs and five deputies who would oversee five bureaus: field services,
investigative services, special operations, professional standards and
operations support.
</P>
<P>
	   Currently, due in part to retirements and attrition, the department has only
one assistant chief and no deputy chiefs. Acting Chief Deborah Barrows said she
would like to see a return to captains supervising each shift.
</P>
<P>
	   Barrows, a 25-year veteran of the troubled force, took the helm when Joseph
F. Croughwell Jr. went on medical leave in June.
</P>
<P>
	   "We can't go on with an acting chief for another six months as we try to
make changes," Peters said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, Peters said publicly that he believed it was time for
Croughwell to retire. Croughwell, who is scheduled for open-heart surgery in a
few days, said at the time that he planned to return to his job once his doctors
gave him approval.
</P>
<P>
	   The study also recommended reassessing the police service area model, which
keeps officers in neighborhood stations from responding to calls in other parts
of the city. Kee Borges said she supports the idea of retaining the service
areas as mini-stations while moving all police functions to the Jennings Road
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
	   Recommendations include assigning a deputy chief to work evenings Tuesday
through Saturday and assigning specialized personnel to work Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
	   The report also recommended increasing the number of "community policing"
officers from 13 to 21, while reducing the total size of the department from 482
sworn officers to 424.
</P>
<P>
	   Implementing the proposed changes would require federal grant money as well
as money from the city's general fund, Kee Borges said. But, she said, cutting
back on overtime by establishing a limit for each police division could help
recoup some of the general fund costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The state's largest municipal police force, the Hartford department has been
criticized for repeated incidents of alleged corruption and mismanagement. A
separate consultant's report in October called the $36 million-a-year department
"dysfunctional," saying it has too many officers doing too little work and
making too much in overtime pay.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 20 Hartford police officers have been arrested in on- and off-duty
incidents in the last six years. That includes five officers who were indicted
by a federal grand jury in the spring for allegedly assaulting prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
	   The fatal shooting of 14-year-old mugging suspect Aquan Salmon, who was
black, by a white officer also has strained the department's public image. A
prosecutor's report on the shooting is due in a few weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1027 </TRAILER>
