<HEADLINE> Lion King Tops British Nominations  </HEADLINE>
    By MATT WOLF Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- "The Lion King," director Julie Taymor's stage adaptation of
the animated Disney film, garnered eight nominations Thursday for the Laurence
Olivier Awards, London's equivalent to Broadway's Tony Awards.
</P>
<P>
	   Matching that number was an English show as small as "The Lion King" is huge
-- "Spend, Spend, Spend," a musical biography of Englishwoman Viv Nicholson, who
hit it big in the 1960s by winning football pools and then lost it all.
</P>
<P>
	   The two shows are competing for best musical, director, musical actress,
choreography, sets and lighting.
</P>
<P>
	   The winners will be announced Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
	   Rounding out the nominees for best musical are "Mamma Mia!," the
ABBA-inspired songfest that has been the season's surprise smash, and "Honk! The
Ugly Duckling," a new version of the popular children's tale by the British
songwriting team of George Stiles and Anthony Drewe.
</P>
<P>
	   American dramatists snared three of the slots for best new play -- Martin
Sherman for "Rose," Richard Nelson for "Goodnight Children Everywhere" and
Richard Greenberg for "Three Days of Rain." Scottish writer Liz Lochhead's
"Perfect Days" and veteran English playwright Alan Bennett's "The Lady In the
Van" -- the odds-on favorite -- completed the category.
</P>
<P>
	   Dame Maggie Smith, the inimitable lead of Bennett's funny and moving play,
is up for best actress against Janie Dee for "Comic Potential," Alison Steadman
for "The Memory of Water" and Jennifer Ehle for "The Real Thing."
</P>
<P>
	   Stephen Dillane, Ehle's co-star in the Tom Stoppard revival -- which
transfers to Broadway at the end of March -- leads a strong list of best actor
hopefuls: Henry Goodman in "The Merchant of Venice," Roger Allam in
"Summerfolk," Michael Sheen in "Look Back In Anger" and Antony Sher in "The
Winter's Tale."
</P>
<P>
	   Sheen is currently winning plaudits in New York in his Broadway stage debut,
as Mozart in "Amadeus."
</P>
<P>
	   Allam, in turn, received an additional Olivier citation for supporting actor
in the revival of the little-known Victorian comedy-drama "Money."
</P>
<P>
	   Surprising omissions included Olympia Dukakis, the lone performer in the
demanding "Rose," as well as Vanessa Redgrave and her brother Corin, who
appeared together on stage for the first time in a revival of Noel Coward's
"Song At Twilight."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
