<DOCNO> APW20000113.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Weighs $25B Debt Buyback  </HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN GALVIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Responding to the new era of budget surpluses, the
Clinton administration today announced rules that will allow the government to
buy back up to $30 billion of the national debt this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, in announcing the new procedures, said
the goal was to save taxpayers' money on interest payments while making sure the
huge Treasury securities market does not lose any of its appeal for investors.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal government has already posted back-to-back budget surpluses for
the first time since Dwight Eisenhower was president. Current projections show
the $3.6 trillion total debt held by the public could be eliminated over the
next 15 years if surpluses currently projected materialize.
</P>
<P>
	   But economists have cautioned that such surpluses will be contingent on a
host of factors that can't be known at the present time. These include how well
the economy performs and how well the White House and Congress can resist the
temptation to use a portion of the projected surpluses to boost spending or cut
taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan Summers announced today will have the debt buybacks conducted in a
``reverse auction'' process in which holders of government securities who want
to sell their bonds back to the government will be given the chance to bid on
what price they would accept.
</P>
<P>
	   Summers said this process will ensure that the government will not pay more
than the going market price for the securities.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement of final rules for the procedure followed an August release
of preliminary rules, which were modified after Treasury reviewed public
comments.
</P>
<P>
	   The debt buybacks would be the first since 1972. The government is in a
position to make the purchases because of the huge projected budget surpluses
over the next decade. The surpluses have been the subject of intense debate
between the administration and Congress involving such politically charged
issues as protecting Social Security and providing tax relief.
</P>
<P>
	   The total national debt is $5.76 trillion. Of that amount about $3.6
trillion is held by the public in the form of Treasury securities. This is the
portion that would be bought back. The rest of the debt, some $2 trillion, is
held by the government's large trust funds, most significantly the Social
Security trust fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1201 </TRAILER>
