<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koch Industries Fined for Pollution  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency today slapped Koch
Industries with $35 million in fines and penalties as part of a settlement over
alleged contamination of lakes and streams in six states from Missouri to Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   Based in Wichita, Kan., the company operates more than 35,000 miles of
pipeline in the United States and Canada, and has refineries in Texas and
Minnesota through its Koch Petroleum Group subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
	   The settlement, announced by the EPA and Justice Department, stems from
allegations that the company had more than 300 oil spills from its pipelines and
other oil operations, resulting in 3 million gallons of crude oil pouring into
lakes and streams in violation of the Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
	   The spills polluted waterways in Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Alabama, Louisiana
and Missouri, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Today's landmark fine against Koch Industries for egregious violations of
the Clean Water Act sends a strong message that those who try to profit by
polluting our environment pay a price,'' said EPA Administrator Carol Browner.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch Pipeline Co. said in a statement that pipeline leaks had been reduced
by 90 percent since 1990 and when leaks occur the company is committed ``to
clean them up quickly and completely.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe that the settlement is fair and reasonable and will avoid even
more years of litigation,'' Pat McCann, Koch Pipeline senior vice president,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The $30 million in fines and a commitment to make $5 million in
environmental restitution represents the largest civil penalty ever levied
against a single company in connection with violation of an environmental law,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The much larger fines against Exxon for the 1989 tanker disaster in Alaska
involved criminal penalties.
</P>
<P>
	   The oil spills cited by the EPA in its case against Koch stretched across
the company's pipeline system. It included a case in which 221,000 gallons of
oil spilled near Payne, Okla., contaminating Keystone Lake, a popular recreation
area 25 miles away.
</P>
<P>
	   In another case, the public water supply system near Wichita, Kan., was
polluted by a spill from one of the company's pipelines, officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   The spills that dumped 3 million gallons of oil into waterways occurred over
a seven-year period from 1990 to 1997, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
	   On its Internet Web page, Koch Industries touts its environmental record,
saying it has spent $980 million for environmental protection at refineries and
other facilities since 1990. It claims to have reduced pipeline leaks by more
than 90 percent over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
	   The company, which employs 13,000 people worldwide in businesses ranging
from oil refining and chemical production to cattle ranching, has had its share
of turmoil over the years, much of it stemming from a 20-year feud among the
three Koch brothers who once shared in operating the company.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month a federal jury in Oklahoma found Koch Industries had cheated the
government on oil purchases, a ruling that could end up costing the company as
much as $214 million in penalties and claims, depending on appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit that led to that ruling accused the company of filing 31,000
false claims on oil from federal and Indian-held leases. The jury found that the
company had inflated the amount of oil it was taking by adjusting measurements
in its favor. In the 1980s, a Senate subcommittee investigated the company's
oil-measuring policies.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch argued in its defense that the yearly oil overages were less than 1
percent and were designed to make up for oil shrinkage and sediment in tanks.
Ironically, the charges stemmed from a whistle-blower lawsuit filed by Bill
Koch, against his family's company.
</P>
<P>
	   Bill Koch claimed in an unsuccessful court action last year that his
brothers cheated him of $1 billion when he sold his stake in Koch Industries in
1983. He lost the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Investment Incentives  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investment in America's hard-luck urban and rural areas
makes bottom-line economic sense, since it represents an easy way to expand the
economy without increasing inflation, President Clinton declared today.
</P>
<P>
	   Road-testing some ideas he will highlight during his State of the Union
address at the end of this month, Clinton made a dollars-and-cents pitch for his
proposal to more than double a tax credit for investment in what the Clinton
administration calls ``new markets.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``How do you keep it going?'' Clinton said of America's current economic
boom. ``You have to find new markets, create new businesses in places where they
didn't exist before.''
</P>
<P>
	   The president spoke at Boricua College in Brooklyn, a predominantly Hispanic
community college, where he helped launch a small-business development center
that will deliver business counseling, training and other help for minority
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
	   Every American should be supporting this,'' Clinton said, not only because
it is ``morally right'' to help those left out of expanding economic prosperity,
but because ``it is in our self-interest as a nation, if we want to keep this
astonishing economic revival going.''
</P>
<P>
	   A tax incentive program, which Clinton first unveiled last year, is supposed
to make investment in poor regions of this country as attractive as investment
in less-developed countries abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the time for these kinds of initiatives because for the first time
in many, many years we have an economy where jobs are looking for people,''
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said today on CNN. ``That means we need to
make sure that that supply (of capital) is there and there in every part of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
	   While many Republicans on Capitol Hill support the economic empowerment
agenda behind the new markets proposal, Clinton was unable to push the entire
package through Congress and is trying again this year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What the president's trying to do is inspire corporate America and
investors to take a second look in their own backyard,'' White House economic
adviser Gene Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed 25 percent tax credit would leverage $15 billion a year in
investment over five years, but cost the government just a third of that,
Sperling said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``So this tax credit would now leverage $15 billion of equity investment in
lower income parts of America, both urban and rural,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike most commuters, President Clinton breezed into New York today as
police cleared the highways for his motorcade and tollbooth operators waved him
by without charge.
</P>
<P>
	   A light morning snow forced the president to abandon plans to helicopter
from his new home in Chappaqua to Manhattan for speaking appearances. About an
hour late, his 14-car motorcade took to the highway. Police blocked all traffic
except for the president's cars, causing large backups.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House said Clinton's departure had been delayed by a telephone
call with Syrian President Hafez Assad about the status of the Syrian-Israeli
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
	   The two leaders talked at length, White House deputy press secretary Jake
Siewert said, about ``the status, and how we can make progress when the next
round commences.''
</P>
<P>
	   The talks, which began in Sheperdstown, W.Va., and recessed on Monday, are
to resume Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
	   For much of the rest of the day, Clinton was participating in a separate
economic development project shepherded by the Rev. Jesse Jackson. Jackson's
Wall Street Project is a 3-year-old effort to involve the titans of New York
City finance in minority business ventures.
</P>
<P>
	   The program, and a similar venture in Chicago, ``are set to partner major
venture capital partnerships in the country with minority vendors and minority
business, giving them better access to capital and strategies for economic
growth in the long term,'' said Barbara Proctor, media relations director for
Jackson's sponsoring Rainbow/PUSH Coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1238 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0165 </DOCNO>
