<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warner-Lambert reverses course, begins talks to merge with Pfizer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Warner-Lambert Co. today said it would hold merger talks
with Pfizer Inc, reversing its November decision to be acquired by American Home
Products.
<P>
	   Either combination would create the world's largest drugmaker.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors had pressured Warner-Lambert executives to re-evaluate its
decision to unite with Madison, N.J.-based American Home Products, especially in
light of the rising value of Pfizer's offer. Pfizer made a bid for
Warner-Lambert on Nov. 4, just hours after American Home and Warner-Lambert
announced plans to combine.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer's offer is now worth about $77 billion. American Home's bid is valued
at about $57 billion. The difference between the offers has widened in recent
weeks due to Pfizer's rising stock price and American Home's falling stock
price.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of Warner-Lambert rose 68 3/4 cents to $82.50 in afternoon trading on
the New York Stock Exchange, where Pfizer rose 75 cents to $35.87 1/2 and
American Home rose $2.25 to $44.43 3/4.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert, the fastest growing major drugmaker, is the world's
15th-largest prescription drug company. The Morris Plains N.J.-based company
makes the blockbuster cholesterol-lowering drug Lipitor, which it co-markets
with Pfizer and which is expected to have $3.3 billion in sales this year and
upwards of $6 billion in 2002.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement this morning, Warner-Lambert's board said that "in light of
changing circumstances" it had concluded Pfizer's offer "is better financially
for Warner-Lambert shareholders than the proposed merger with American Home
Products."
</P>
<P>
	   Lodewijk J.R. de Vink, chairman, president and chief executive officer of
Warner-Lambert, said talks would be held with Pfizer. Warner-Lambert said it
could not guarantee that an agreement could be reached with Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
	   It is unclear how much Warner-Lambert would have to pay American Home if
Warner-Lambert walks away from its deal. The American Home-Warner-Lambert deal
called for either company to pay the other $2 billion if it wanted to walk away
from the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
	   If American Home Products is rejected, it would be its third failed merger
attempt in less than two years. In 1998, negotiations broke down with Monsanto
Co. and SmithKline Beecham PLC.
</P>
<P>
	   The battle for Warner-Lambert has escalated into some nasty exchanges
between the companies' top officials and several lawsuits have been filed.
Warner-Lambert has even sought to terminate Pfizer's rights to co-market and
share profits from Lipitor.
</P>
<P>
	   None of the cases has yet to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer, which was preparing a hostile takeover of Warner-Lambert, said today
it was pleased with Warner-Lambert's move.
</P>
<P>
	   "We look forward to an expeditious completion of the transaction combining
the two fastest-growing companies in our industry and creating the best
pharmaceutical company in the world," Pfizer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   American Home officials did not immediately respond for comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert has hired Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. and Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. to act
as its financial advisers in dealing with Pfizer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1250 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APA panel moves to expand wilderness; full-agency vote next  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. (AP) - Little Tupper Lake and the surrounding forest
should be declared wilderness, a committee of the Adirondack Park Agency has
recommended.
<P>
	   The Adirondack Park Agency's State Land Committee voted unanimously
Wednesday to recommend that Little Tupper Lake and 14,700 acres of surrounding
land known as the William C. Whitney tract be designated as wilderness, the most
restrictive land use designation. Under the wilderness designation, the land
would essentially remain untouched, and motorized vehicles would be prohibited.
The land is open to the public and canoes will be allowed on Little Tupper Lake.
</P>
<P>
	   The Adirondack Park Agency was expected to vote on the recommendation
Friday. Gov. George Pataki will then be called upon to give final approval.
</P>
<P>
	   The centerpiece of the tract is Little Tupper Lake, a shallow, pristine lake
with 20 miles of shoreline, surrounded by small mountains and forests of beech,
maple, birch and scattered pine trees.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think this is a unique piece of property for a wilderness classification
in that you can literally drive right up to it," said committee member William
Kissel, adding that the area is readily accessible to the disabled.
</P>
<P>
	   Little Tupper Lake provides one of the best canoeing lakes in the United
States, according to Greg Caito, the Department of Economic Development's
representative to the APA.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the only place in the United States where you can drop a canoe in
on the shore and paddle into the middle of the wilderness in seven minutes,"
said Caito.
</P>
<P>
	   The APA regulates development and preservation of the 6 million-acre state
park, which is a mixture of public and privately owned land.
</P>
<P>
	   The land was purchased by the state from Whitney Industries on May 29, 1998,
for $17.1 million and has been managed by the state Department of Environmental
Conservation as a wilderness area, pending the final decision.
</P>
<P>
	   The purchase renewed a debate over land use in the Adirondacks with
environmental groups calling for the wilderness designation as local officials
argue the limitations will deprive their communities of a badly needed economic
boost. The latter group argues for a "wild forest" classification that would
open the lands to motorized vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   Local businessmen say the mountains that attract throngs of vacationers from
around the country every summer don't provide many year-round jobs. Unemployment
has been traditionally high in the area, and businessmen blame much of it on the
myriad state environmental regulations governing development.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmentalists argued that the land should be protected for future
generations.
</P>
<P>
	   The APA received more than 1,200 letters from the public since August, said
James C. Frenette, chairman of the APA land committee.
</P>
<P>
	   In related action, the committee recommended a state administrative
designation for the 80-acre DEC property, where its Little Tupper Lake
headquarters building is situated. The property provides the only public access
to the lake. After a lengthy discussion, the committee recommended that 4,000
acres of land adjacent to the Whitney tract be designated wilderness. The area
includes Lake Lila and is south and west of the Whitney tract, sharing a
one-mile border.
</P>
<P>
	   The panel hesitated to recommend a wilderness designation for the entire
Lake Lila tract, which totals 7,215 acres, until the status of a historic - but
abandoned - two-story house connected to the railroad is determined.
</P>
<P>
	   In other action, the committee recommended:
</P>
<P>
	   - A 23,000-acre parcel known as the Watson's East/Lassiter tract be
classified part wilderness and part wild forest. A wild-forest designation
allows for uses such as temporary hunting camps and, in certain cases,
snowmobiles and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
	   - The reclassification of the 2,000-acre Alice Brook tract from wilderness
to wild forest.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the wilderness designation, the land must remain essentially
untouched, and motorized vehicles are prohibited. The land is open to the
public, and canoes will be allowed on Little Tupper Lake.
</P>
<P>
	   Environmental groups complained about the committee's recommended "wild
forest" classifications of parts of the Watson's East tract and the Alice Brook
tract. They urged the Adirondack Park Agency to reject the "wild forest"
classifications.
</P>
<P>
	   "Are we protecting public lands and wildlife habitat from development just
so they can be torn to shreds by motorized traffic?" asked Timothy Burke,
executive director of the Adirondack Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1253 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hartford officer charged with stealing license plates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A Hartford police officer accused of stealing
license plates and using his badge to escape arrest has been suspended from the
city force.
<P>
	   Officer Greg Thompson, of West Hartford, was charged Wednesday with four
counts of misdemeanor larceny, criminal trespass, breach of peace and
interfering with police.
</P>
<P>
	   The larceny charges carry an automatic suspension without pay until the case
is disposed of in court. If convicted, Thompson would be fired. He has been a
police officer for two years.
</P>
<P>
	   Thompson is the third Hartford officer in a month to face charges. One
officer was forced to resign amid allegations he fraudulently obtained a
driver's license, and the other was fired over charges that he beat two
prisoners in the city lockup.
</P>
<P>
	   Thompson turned himself in at the same time Hartford officials were holding
a news conference to recommend a proposed restructuring of the troubled police
department. The report, which recommends centralizing command, replenishing top
jobs lost to retirement and attrition and putting brass on night and weekend
shifts, follows another consultant's report that described the department as
"dysfunctional."
</P>
<P>
	   The state's largest municipal police force, the Hartford department has been
criticized for repeated incidents of alleged corruption and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
	   More than 20 Hartford police officers have been arrested in on- and off-duty
incidents in the last six years. That includes five officers who were indicted
by a federal grand jury in the spring for allegedly assaulting prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
	   In the latest case, police say Thompson used license plates stolen from two
cars that had been involved in crashes in Hartford, an emissions sticker taken
from a car belonging to one of his neighbors and a registration sticker reported
stolen from a fourth vehicle.
</P>
<P>
	   According to court documents, Thompson put the stolen plates and stickers on
his 1995 Mitsubishi and drove it. He was stopped several times in West Hartford
for driving an unregistered car, but was not arrested. In one instance, he
flashed his badge and sped away, leaving the officer with the impression he was
working undercover, West Hartford police officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   On the other occasions, officers gave him a break after Thompson identified
himself as a Hartford police officer, according to arrest documents.
</P>
<P>
	   Thompson declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1300 </TRAILER>
