<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State dismisses harassment complaint against Hartford mayor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The state Commission on Human Rights and
Opportunities dismissed a sexual harassment complaint against Hartford Mayor
Michael Peters, saying a former city employee's allegations were too vague and
may have come too late.
<P>
	   Andrea Buglione-Corbett, a former council aide, claimed she had been the
target of "constant sexual harassment" while employed as an aide from September
1996 through January 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Buglione-Corbett, 36, said Peters passed around pornographic magazines in
his office and made inappropriate jokes and comments in her presence. She also
accused Peters of placing his hand on her thigh during a June 1998 office
get-together.
</P>
<P>
	   The commission, whose proceedings are confidential, closed the case on Dec.
30 after finding that the allegations were "overly vague, nonspecific and - for
the most part - untimely."
</P>
<P>
	   Peters could not be reached for comment. A message was left at his office
Thursday, but a member of his staff said he was out of the city.
</P>
<P>
	   Buglione-Corbett's lawyer, Lee Kennedy Tiernan, said the decision merely
clears the way for her client to include a charge of sexual harassment in a
civil lawsuit she has filed against Peters, former Councilman Steven D. Park and
the city of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
	   State law generally requires that any complaints of sexual harassment go
first to the commission, said Philip A. Murphy Jr., the CHRO's general counsel.
Only after the commission investigates or dismisses a case can the charge be
considered in a civil lawsuit, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the lawsuit, Buglione-Corbett claims she was unfairly fired in January
1998. Park accused her of incompetence and told her to leave her job, but she
was asked to return a month later when he failed to drum up enough City Council
votes to fire her.
</P>
<P>
	   She did not return, citing a stressful work environment, and was dropped
from the payroll May 3.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit also accuses Park of asking Buglione-Corbett to baby-sit his
children and to perform personal business on city time. Park denies the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   It remains unclear whether Buglione-Corbett will pursue the sexual
harassment allegation in her civil suit. Her lawyers have consistently
emphasized other parts of her complaint.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're the ones making a big deal about it," Tiernan said. "The really
relevant issue is that they tried to remove my client from her job for no
reason."
</P>
<P>
	   Hartford Corporation Counsel Kevin G. Dubay said the city expects a similar
victory in the civil case.
</P>
<P>
	   "I believe her civil action has every bit as much merit as her CHRO
complaint," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
