<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwab, which owns the nation's largest discount and online brokerage, is
buying U.S. Trust for $2.7 billion in stock, or about $129 per share. U.S. Trust
provides investment management services primarily for wealthy individuals.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said it expects fiscal third-quarter earnings between 58 cents a
share and 64 cents a share, below analysts' forecasts of 73 cents a share.
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and Merrill Lynch lowered their ratings on the stock.
</P>
<P>
	   The parent company of United Airlines said it expects to earn between $7 and
$9 per share in the coming year. Analysts had estimated UAL would earn $9.82 a
share. The company cited rising fuel and labor costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The boutique investment bank said it expects to report net income of 18
cents to 21 cents a share for the fourth quarter. Analysts had anticipated a
loss of 2 cents per share. Friedman Billings Ramsey officials cited strength in
its venture capital business.
</P>
<P>
	   The company could be forced to break into three parts to dilute its
competitive advantage, according to sources close to the government's antitrust
trial. A breakup would dismantle the software empire built by Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
	   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on the stock to "outperform"
from "neutral." An analyst with the firm said Apple shares should reach 120
within a year.
</P>
<P>
	   Applied Materials Inc. agreed to acquire Etec for $1.77 billion in stock.
Etec makes equipment for making photomasks, a device used to lay down patterns
on a chip. Applied Materials expects the deal to help it meet manufacturing
requirements of its customers.
</P>
<P>
	   The company signed a three-year electronic-commerce purchasing agreement
with Merck &AMP; Co. Merck's scientists will use SciQuest.com to locate and purchase
research products. SciQuest also joined a supplier network run by Oracle Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
