<HEADLINE> IBP Sued on Environmental Charges  </HEADLINE>
   By JESSICA FARGEN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The federal government has sued the meatpacker IBP Inc.,
accusing it of polluting the air and water surrounding its Dakota City plant.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit, filed Wednesday in U.S. District Court on behalf of the
Environmental Protection Agency, seeks fines up to $241 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The complaint alleges the plant violated federal clean air and water laws
and hazardous waste management regulations at its slaughter and tannery
operations.
</P>
<P>
	   IBP's six uncovered waste lagoons at the site emitted largely uncontrolled
amounts of hydrogen sulfide into the air, and the company discharged ammonia
into the Missouri River in quantities toxic to aquatic life, the Justice
Department said in the complaint.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department is asking the court to order IBP to cover or close
its waste lagoons, capture emissions from uncontrolled sources, install
additional treatment for its discharges to the Missouri River, and take other
steps to protect the environment.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This case presents a pattern of activity for which the common thread is
IBP's avoidance of environmental regulation,'' U.S. District Attorney Tom
Monaghan said.
</P>
<P>
	   IBP officials rebutted the charges, said the suit will benefit no one and
will delay further its planned $13 million in improvements.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have been trying to do the right thing, but aren't being given the
green light,'' said Gary Mickelson, spokesman for IBP at its headquarters in
Dakota Dunes, S.D.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dakota City plant employs about 4,000 people. IBP is the world's largest
producer of fresh beef, pork and related products.
</P>
<P>
	   IBP planned to break ground this spring on environmental improvements
including construction of three covered wastewater lagoons and installation of
equipment to clean air released from the tannery, Mickelson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Also in the project is money to expand tannery production by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Brian McManus, state Department of Environmental Quality spokesman, said the
department supports IBP's lagoon project, but needs more information to issue
permits for the tannery expansion. IBP has consistently presented the two
projects together, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They can move forward with lagoon improvements right away,'' McManus said.
``It's been their choice to link the two.''
</P>
<P>
	   Mickelson said the two projects are intertwined and can't be proposed
separately.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department wants the court to order IBP to cover or close its
waste lagoons, capture emissions from uncontrolled sources, install additional
treatment for its discharges to the Missouri River, and take other steps to
protect the environment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1329 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The First Couple Commutes  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- On their first day as real New York commuters on Thursday,
President Clinton left home in the suburbs and headed off to work with help from
a phalanx of police, while his wife enjoyed the morning paper's favorable review
of her Letterman debut.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clintons are feeling their way in the uncharted territory of a commuter
White House, with the president making drop-by visits to the family's new home
in the tony New York suburb of Chappaqua. Hillary Rodham Clinton is living there
pretty much full-time now, using the handsome, $1.7 million house as home base
for her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The First Commuters left home in the morning for what are now two very
different jobs. The president, who is road-testing some themes for his final
State of the Union address later this month, had a barrage of economic incentive
ideas to discuss during stops in Brooklyn and Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   There were also a party on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange, a
swank, $5,000-a-couple Democratic fund-raising reception and a few opportunities
for the modern helpmate husband to boost his wife's nascent political career.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I always like to come to New York and give my wife a plug,'' Clinton joked
during a morning appearance at a Brooklyn community college.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton campaigned nearby on Long Island and basked in good press after
Wednesday's star turn on the Manhattan-based Late Show with David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
	   Of course the Clintons are not exactly straphangers. Clinton was supposed to
whisk from Westchester County to Brooklyn by helicopter, but bad weather forced
him to drive in a 14-car, heavily protected motorcade. Police blocked all
traffic as the president passed, causing large backups, and the toll booth
operators waved him by without charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton travels lighter, but still with the Secret Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
