<DOCNO> APW20000113.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last temporary sales tax exemption begins Saturday  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) - Rudnick's main street storefront has been front
row for dancing in the streets at the end of World War II, for industrial
America's heyday when 40,000 people worked downtown and for New York's
post-industrial decline.
<P>
	   But it hasn't seen anything like knocking $2.10 cents in sales tax off a $30
shirt.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's amazing how many people come down that week," said Linda Tolokonsky,
owner of the time-frozen clothing shop which has been in her family since 1909.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a chaotic week," she said. "It's very, very busy."
</P>
<P>
	   Beginning Saturday, the state once again will eliminate sales tax on
clothing and shoes for a week. The taxes return on Jan. 22.
</P>
<P>
	   Retailers are poised for a rush of business that rivals Christmas and
back-to-school sales during what have traditionally been lull periods.
</P>
<P>
	   Twenty cities and 58 of 62 counties will also drop their local sales taxes
for the state's seventh tax-free week, resulting in a 7 percent to 8 percent tax
break to move winter inventories and prompt the cashing in of holiday gift
certificates.
</P>
<P>
	   The tax-free weeks on the sale of clothing and shoes up to $500 per item are
aimed at jump-starting retail sales and keeping New Yorkers home to shop instead
of at malls strategically placed just over the state lines in Massachusetts, New
Jersey and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have seen many of our customers go to Lee, Mass.," Tolokonsky said. "Now
they stay in the state of New York to spend."
</P>
<P>
	   Lee, about seven miles from the New York line, is home to a new complex of
factory outlet stores.
</P>
<P>
	   Tolokonsky's son works across the border at a popular shoe and boot outlet
in Vermont and she said, "Our tax-free weeks have a devastating effect on them."
</P>
<P>
	   The tax-free week is estimated by proponents as saving consumers $25 million
or more.
</P>
<P>
	   Marc Carey of the state Department of Taxation and Finance emphasized that
the sales tax break applies only to clothing and footwear - what he called
necessities - rather than luxury items.
</P>
<P>
	   State Sen. Thomas Libous, R-Binghamton, represents one of the border areas
where business operators have long sought an end to the sales tax. After 12
years in office, the idea that he said wasn't thought possible by most during
his initial campaign has flourished in Broome County along the Pennsylvania
border.
</P>
<P>
	   "In 1988, the Southern Tier was losing business to Pennsylvania because of
our sales tax," Libous said. "So the sales tax became a hot issue. The merchants
are really excited about it."
</P>
<P>
	   The state will permanently drop its 4 percent tax beginning March 1 for
clothing and shoes costing less than $110. Business operators said that makes
this last temporary tax-free week the last shot at a break on items that cost up
to $500.
</P>
<P>
	   Most counties and cities, however, won't follow the state's lead and
permanently give up the local sales taxes on March 1. Most argue that they
simply can't afford to do without the millions in revenue their portion of the
sales tax provides them with.
</P>
<P>
	   They include rural Schoharie County, which depends on sales tax revenue to
avoid higher property taxes and Orange County, which relies on growing sales tax
revenue thanks to huge malls like the Galleria Mall in Wallkill and the Woodbury
Common factory outlet mall in Monroe.
</P>
<P>
	   But lopping off the sales tax is more than a matter of dollars and cents.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a symbolic value," said Matthew Maguire of the state Business
Council. "Historically, New York state taxation was above and beyond other
states. Now you're telling the world we're trying to do something about that.
And that has a value."
</P>
<P>
	   Ashley Lounsbury of the Retail Council of New York State said previous
tax-free weeks have been "incredibly successful."
</P>
<P>
	   Counties not participating in the tax-free week are Nassau, Putnam and
Columbia. Westchester County will not charge a local sales tax except the cities
of Mount Vernon, New Rochelle, White Plains and Yonkers. The city of Rome in
Oneida County will charge a local sales tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1339 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
