<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koch Industries Fined for Pollution  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency today slapped Koch
Industries with $35 million in fines and penalties as part of a settlement over
alleged contamination of lakes and streams in six states from Missouri to Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   Based in Wichita, Kan., the company operates more than 35,000 miles of
pipeline in the United States and Canada, and has refineries in Texas and
Minnesota through its Koch Petroleum Group subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
	   The settlement, announced by the EPA and Justice Department, stems from
allegations that the company had more than 300 oil spills from its pipelines and
other oil operations, resulting in 3 million gallons of crude oil pouring into
lakes and streams in violation of the Clean Water Act.
</P>
<P>
	   The spills polluted waterways in Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Alabama, Louisiana
and Missouri, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Today's landmark fine against Koch Industries for egregious violations of
the Clean Water Act sends a strong message that those who try to profit by
polluting our environment pay a price,'' said EPA Administrator Carol Browner.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch Pipeline Co. said in a statement that pipeline leaks had been reduced
by 90 percent since 1990 and when leaks occur the company is committed ``to
clean them up quickly and completely.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe that the settlement is fair and reasonable and will avoid even
more years of litigation,'' Pat McCann, Koch Pipeline senior vice president,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The $30 million in fines and a commitment to make $5 million in
environmental restitution are the largest civil penalty ever levied against a
single company under the Clean Water Act, Browner said. Previously the largest
was a $12.6 million fine against Smithfield Foods Inc., for dumping hog wastes
into Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
	   Much larger settlements, including those involving the 1989 Exxon tanker
disaster in Alaska and last year's $150 million settlement with General Electric
Co., over toxic chemical pollution of a river in Massachusetts, included cleanup
costs.
</P>
<P>
	   While not facing specific cleanup costs, Koch under the settlement must
assess the condition of 2,500 miles of pipeline and repair any defects, and
begin an improved leak-detection program. Most of the spills were caused by
pipeline corrosion and the government alleged the corrosion could have been
prevented with property maintenance and operation.
</P>
<P>
	   The oil spills cited by the EPA in its case against Loch stretched across
the company's pipeline system but were concentrated in Oklahoma, Texas and
Kansas. It included a case in which 221,000 gallons of oil spilled near Payne
County, Okla., contaminating Keystone Lake, a popular recreation area 25 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
	   In another case, the public water supply system near Wichita, Kan., was
polluted by a spill from one of the company's pipelines, officials said. And in
a third, 100,000 gallons of spilled oil caused a 12-mile slick on Nueces and
Corpus Christ bays in Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   The spills that dumped 3 million gallons of oil into waterways occurred over
a seven-year period from 1990 to 1997, according to the EPA.
</P>
<P>
	   On its Internet Web page, Koch Industries touts its environmental record,
saying it has spent $980 million for environmental protection at refineries and
other facilities since 1990. It claims to have reduced pipeline leaks by more
than 90 percent over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
	   The company, which employs 13,000 people worldwide in businesses ranging
from oil refining and chemical production to cattle ranching, has had its share
of turmoil over the years, much of it stemming from a 20-year feud among the
three Koch brothers who once shared in operating the company.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month a federal jury in Oklahoma found Koch Industries had cheated the
government on oil purchases, a ruling that could end up costing the company as
much as $214 million in penalties and claims, depending on appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit that led to that ruling accused the company of filing 31,000
false claims on oil from federal and Indian-held leases. The jury found that the
company had inflated the amount of oil it was taking by adjusting measurements
in its favor. In the 1980s, a Senate subcommittee investigated the company's
oil-measuring policies.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch argued in its defense that the yearly oil overages were less than 1
percent and were designed to make up for oil shrinkage and sediment in tanks.
Ironically, the charges stemmed from a whistle-blower lawsuit filed by Bill
Koch, against his family's company.
</P>
<P>
	   Bill Koch claimed in an unsuccessful court action last year that his
brothers cheated him of $1 billion when he sold his stake in Koch Industries in
1983. He lost the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1404 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State treasurer will present Legislature with reform proposals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The Connecticut General Assembly will be asked to
consider at least 11 proposals from the treasurer's office to reform the way
state employee pension funds are invested in wake of last year's scandal
involving former Treasurer Paul Silvester.
<P>
	   Denise L. Nappier, Silvester's successor, said her ideas include requiring
mandatory disclosure of finders fees paid to third-party agents by investment
firms and their subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
	   Silvester has pleaded guilty to money laundering and racketeering charges.
He has admitted accepting kickbacks from intermediaries who received finders
fees from private firms for helping set up investment deals with the state.
</P>
<P>
	   "In my view, these proposals are not merely a response to a scandal,"
Nappier said this week said after clearing her plans with the state Investment
Advisory Council. "They represent an attempt to turn a scandal into an
opportunity by using the public focus on pension fund management to make
meaningful, constructive changes."
</P>
<P>
	   Nappier said her reforms would impose professional standards on investment
firms' marketing agents and, thereby, exclude well-connected political
intermediaries from influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
	   Among her other ideas:
</P>
<P>
	   -Prohibiting treasurers from directing the payment of fees, as Silvester has
been accused of.
</P>
<P>
	   -Extending the current prohibition on campaign contributions by those doing
business with the treasurer's office. Now, such vendors cannot contribute to
campaigns for treasurer, but Nappier wants the ban extended to all statewide
candidates. Although Silvester, a Republican appointed by Gov. John G. Rowland,
could not raise money for his own campaign from financial firms he did business
with, he helped raise more than $100,000 for the governor.
</P>
<P>
	   -Requiring a special election, not a gubernatorial appointment, when a
treasurer quits, as Silvester's predecessor did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   House Republican leader Robert M. Ward of North Branford called Nappier's
proposals "a weak reform package that does little more than maintain the status
quo."
</P>
<P>
	   He said they leave a "huge loophole which fails to end the unsavory practice
of finder's fees paid to people simply by arranging meetings with the
treasurer."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1416 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 48.63; Nasdaq Up 33.11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher today as technology shares
recovered from a two-day slump and the broader market gained strength from a
report of relatively modest inflation. Investors remained fairly cautious in the
hours ahead of a speech by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
48.63 at 11,599.73.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were also slightly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 10.68 at 1,442.93, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 33.11
at 3,883.13.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose after the Labor Department said that while prices at the
wholesale level shot up 3 percent in 1999, the biggest increase in nine years,
most of the increase came from the volatile energy sector. Excluding energy,
wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent last year, a more modest showing than in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   For December, the Producer Price Index, which measures inflation pressures
before they reach the consumer, was up 0.3 percent, right on target with many
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   The reports boosted investors' confidence that inflation is not escalating
quickly enough to merit sharp interest-rate increases by the Federal Reserve.
Higher interest rates can hurt stocks by cutting into corporate profits as it
becomes more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed raised interest rates three times in 1999 in an effort to keep
inflation at bay, and in recent sessions, stocks have been pressured by fears
that another series of rate hikes are ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Today's report eased some of those fears, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Fed is not behind the curve on inflation," said David Orr, chief
economist at First Union Securities Inc. While most analysts remain convinced
that the Fed will raise rates by 25 basis points, or a quarter percentage point,
at its next meeting on Feb. 1 and 2, today's report suggested the Fed won't
increase rates beyond that amount, Orr said.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was fairly volatile as investors waited for more evidence on the
Fed's likely course. Tonight, Greenspan was discussing technology and the
economy in a speech before the Economic Club of New York. Greenspan has
occasionally used his public speeches as an occasion to telegraph the Fed's
sentiment about the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   And Friday, the government will report on price pressures at the retail
level when it releases its Consumer Price Index. Analysts expect the index to
have risen 0.3 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Beyond the interest rate debate, Apple Computer rose 9 3/16 to 96 3/8 after
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on the stock to "outperform" from
"neutral." An analyst said Apple shares should reach 120 in a year.
</P>
<P>
	   Computer maker Dell rose 1 1/16 to 42 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Trust soared 45 1/2 to 124 3/8 after agreeing to be acquired by Charles
Schwab for $2.7 billion, or about $129 per share.
</P>
<P>
	   The pharmaceutical sector drew investors as Warner-Lambert said it would
hold merger talks with hostile suitor Pfizer, abandoning its November decision
to be acquired by American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading, Warner-Lambert was up 5 3/16 to 92, Pfizer was up 1
5/16 to 36 7/16 and American Home Products was up 1 to 43 3/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-8 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 673.90 million shares, ahead of Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.58 to 496.62.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
