<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-awaited first snowfall of the season blankets New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A strangely snowless landscape was finally swathed
in white on Thursday as the long-overdue first snowstorm of winter swept across
upstate New York, bringing bitter cold and wind in its wake.
<P>
	   Dozens of schools were closed or delayed and morning commuters faced a
white-knuckle drive on highways slickened by fast-falling snow. By noon, there
was as much as 10 inches of snow on the ground in parts of eastern New York.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've had a bunch of minor accidents and vehicles off the road needing a
tow," said Sheriff John Bates in Schoharie County, about 25 miles west of
Albany. "It's the usual stuff you get with the first snow. The only difference
is, it usually happens long before January."
</P>
<P>
	   Before tapering off to flurries, the storm was expected to dump six to 10
inches of snow on a region that so far has had an unusually snowless winter.
Albany has had the least snowy winter in 50 years, with only 1.6 inches before
Thursday's storm.
</P>
<P>
	   In Seneca and Tompkins counties in central New York, authorities declared
snow emergencies and told drivers to stay off the roads. In Baldwinsville, north
of Syracuse, a car spun off a snow-packed road and crashed into a house, but
police said nobody was injured.
</P>
<P>
	   Wind gusts of up to 35 mph compounded driving difficulties and produced
bone-penetrating windchills as low as minus 25 degrees.
</P>
<P>
	   "I knew we were going to pay for all that nice warm weather we had," said
Karl Madsen of the Syracuse suburb of Liverpool as he trudged to lunch, battling
the blowing snow that kept him from looking up.
</P>
<P>
	   Syracuse, reputed to be America's snowiest big city, was 30 inches below its
normal snowfall before Thursday's storm moved in.
</P>
<P>
	   "My fear is it's going to catch up all at once," said Madsen.
</P>
<P>
	   Slick conditions slowed traffic to below 30 mph on the Adirondack Northway
and other major arterials around Albany. AAA Hudson Valley had received 85
reports of cars off the road or other trouble by 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is the first significant accumulation of the year, so people tend to
forget how to drive under these conditions," said George Zeller, manager of
member services for AAA Hudson Valley.
</P>
<P>
	   In Rochester, Alan Whitcomb, a self-employed businessman, stomped his feet
in a 16-degree chill while waiting for a bus Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've gotten spoiled here for the last couple of weeks," he said, tucking
his chin into his coat as snow whipped down Main Street. "This is just getting
back to normal. If you want to live in Rochester, you really can't complain."
</P>
<P>
	   The National Weather Service said eight to 10 inches of snow fell in Wyoming
and Livingston counties in western New York, south of Rochester and southeast of
Buffalo. Police reported numerous minor accidents, including two jack-knifed
tractor-trailers on the Thruway near Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
	   Bitterly cold weather was expected Thursday night and Friday, with
temperatures plummeting into the single digits or below zero, according to the
National Weather Service. Blustery winds were expected to drive the windchill
temperature as low as 40 below zero in some places.
</P>
<P>
	   The heaviest snow fell in a band across the central section of eastern New
York, including Albany and westward through the Mohawk Valley.
</P>
<P>
	   While the snow bedeviled commuters, it delighted some people.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is the first time my little girl has seen snow," said Christine
Carpenter of the Albany suburb of Altamont, who bundled up her 20-month-old
daughter and 4-year-old son to play in fresh powder. "She's not quite sure what
to make of it."
</P>
<P>
	   "This is good weather for us," said Sean Golden, manager of Robinson Ace
Hardware. The store in the Albany suburb of Guilderland has for months kept a
full complement of snow shovels, blowers, brushes and rock salt. But Golden has
seen few buyers.
</P>
<P>
	   Golden said he was preparing for customers to make a run on winter supplies
on their way home from work Thursday. "Because we haven't had any snow, not too
many people think ahead," he said. "Then when it snows, people start stocking
up."
</P>
<P>
	   In Lake Placid, in the heart of the Adirondacks, there was three to five
inches of snow on the ground on Thursday. Greg Fisher, marketing manager at the
Whiteface Mountain ski center, said he wasn't worried about the season's scant
snowfall. Whiteface has a 16 to 34-inch base, and conditions were excellent for
mechanical snowmaking with temperatures dropping to zero and below.
</P>
<P>
	   "Every winter is different," Fisher said. "Winter's a long season that
doesn't end sometimes until June. We're just getting started."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
