<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schwab To Acquire U.S. Trust Corp.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Charles Schwab Corp., which owns the nation's largest
discount and online brokerage, is buying an investment firm that caters to the
rich for $2.7 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwab said today it has signed a definitive agreement to acquire U.S. Trust
Corp. in a bid to create a business serving investors "at every stage of their
financial growth." On the news, shares of U.S. Trust shot up 61 percent by this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
	   The combined company would have annual revenue of $4.5 billion and earnings
of $663 million and about $800 billion in assets under management.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've long held a goal of building an organization that can serve investors
completely -- from those taking their first steps towards becoming lifelong
investors, to those looking to manage their accumulated wealth for themselves
and their families," said Charles R. Schwab, the chairman, co-chief executive
and founder of the company that bears his name. "U.S. Trust represents for us a
piece of the puzzle that had been missing in our offering to affluent
investors."
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Trust was founded in 1853 and is based in New York, with 1,900
employees and offices in nine states and Washington, D.C. The company provides
investment management and consulting services, financial and estate planning and
private banking and has $86 billion in assets under management.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwab, through its main business, Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. Inc., is the
nation's fourth-largest financial services company with 340 branch offices. It
has 6.4 million customers with active accounts representing a total of $725
billion in assets. There are 5,600 independent advisers who manage some of the
Schwab accounts.
</P>
<P>
	   "Schwab will be able to offer affluent clients access to U.S. Trust's wealth
management expertise, while Schwab's vast technological resources will enable
U.S. Trust to combine our traditional high-touch approach with high-tech to
better serve our clients," said H. Marshall Schwarz, chairman and CEO of U.S.
Trust.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies said there are more than 6 million U.S. households each with a
net worth of over $1 million and that the numbers of Americans with large
investment portfolios is expected to grow at a double-digit pace in the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
	   "The baby boomers are emerging as a dominant wealth segment in the United
States," said Schwab president and co-CEO David Pottruck.
</P>
<P>
	   Both companies will retain their separate brand identities.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the agreement, U.S. Trust shareholders will receive 3.427 shares of
Schwab stock for each share of U.S. Trust stock, or $129 in stock for each U.S.
Trust share, based on Wednesday's closing stock price.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of U.S. Trust surged $48 to $126.87 1/2 in midafternoon trading on
the New York Stock Exchange, where Schwab was up 87 1/2 cents at $38.50.
</P>
<P>
	   The transaction is subject to approval by the Federal Reserve Board and
other regulators and to a vote by U.S. Trust shareholders. The companies said
they expect to complete the deal by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
