<HEADLINE> Zions, First Security To Layoff 700  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Zions Bancorporation and First Security Corp. plans
to lay off more than 700 workers as a result of the companies' merger.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies want to reduce their combined 17,000-employee work force by
about 10 percent and hoped to do it primarily through attrition.
</P>
<P>
	   A companywide hiring freeze in effect since they announced their plans to
merge in June helped reduce employment by about 900 people, said Clark Hinckley,
Zions' human resources manager. He confirmed the number of planned layoffs
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Those who will lose their jobs are receiving letters telling them when they
will be terminated. The workers are in the banks' accounting, information
technology, auditing, payroll, human resources, budgeting and other
administrative departments.
</P>
<P>
	   The consolidation of Utah's largest financial institutions will create the
nation's 20th-largest bank with about $40 billion in assets. The combined
company will do business under the First Security name.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal received final regulatory approval from the U.S. Federal Reserve
Board on Dec. 13, shortly after the U.S. Justice Department gave its blessing on
the condition the companies sell 64 branches in Utah and Idaho.
</P>
</TEXT>
