<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, Jan. 13, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   Wholesale Prices Up 3 Percent in '99
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level had their
biggest increase in nine years last year, rising 3 percent. But the
Labor Department said today that the rise was largely due to an
18.4 percent rebound in energy costs. Without the energy and food
sectors, wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent, well below the
1998 rise of 2.5 percent. Last month, the Producer Price Index was
up 0.3 percent, matching many analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   Retail Sales Rise 1.2 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retail sales rose 1.2 percent in December,
according to figures released today by the Commerce Department.
That was stronger than the 0.9 percent increase many analysts were
anticipating, and up from 1.1 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
	   Jobless Claims Unchanged
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for
unemployment benefits was unchanged at 309,000 last week. The
four-week moving average rose to 294,000, the highest level since
Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
	   Dow Up 72.91; Nasdaq Up 55.89
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher today as technology
shares recovered from a two-day slump and the broader market gained
strength from a report of relatively modest inflation. Investors
remained fairly cautious in the hours ahead of a speech by Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. Just before 3 p.m. EST, the Dow
Jones industrial average was up 72.91 at 11,624.01. Broader stock
indicators were also higher, with the Nasdaq composite index up
55.89 at 3,905.91.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 3 p.m. EST:
Dow Industrials:        11624.01  + 72.91
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1805  Declines 1151  Unchgd  508
NYSE Volume:         741,441,650
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online 62 7/8   + 2 7/8  
S&AMP;P 500:         1447.36 + 15.11
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          867.27  +  9.29
Nasdaq Composite Index        3905.91  + 55.89
Gold(final) -    $285.50    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
</P>
<P>
	   Electronic Tax Credit Proposed
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rewards may be waiting for U.S. taxpayers who
file their federal income taxes online or over the telephone using
the IRS' Telefile. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said today
that Clinton will include in his fiscal 2001 budget request to
Congress next month a $10 refundable tax credit for taxpayers
filing online and a $5 credit for those using Telefile. Summers
said the credit ``will provide an incentive for filing online and
reward individual taxpayers'' while simultaneously helping the IRS
become more efficient.
</P>
<P>
	   United Air Warns of Lower Earnings
</P>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Shares of United Airlines' parent company fell
today after UAL, the world's largest airline, warned that its
earnings this year will be well below expectations because of
higher fuel and labor costs. UAL Corp. stock was down 10 7/16 at 64
5/16. UAL, issuing its revised outlook before chairman and chief
executive James Goodwin met with analysts in New York, forecast
earnings for the year at between $7 and $9 a share. Analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had pegged earnings for
the year at $9.76 a share.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert To Hold Pfizer Talks
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Warner-Lambert Co. today reversed course and
said it would hold merger talks with Pfizer Inc. The decision came
two months after Warner-Lambert agreed to be acquired by American
Home Products. Either combination would create the world's largest
drugmaker. Investors had pressured Warner-Lambert executives to
re-evaluate its decision to unite with American Home Product,
especially in light of the rising value of Pfizer's offer. Pfizer's
offer is now worth about $77 billion. American Home's bid is valued
at about $57 billion. The difference between the offers has widened
in recent weeks as Pfizer's stocks rise and American Home's fall.
Pfizer stock was trading at 36 5/16 Up 1 3/16 this afternoon;
Warner-Lambert was up 4 1/2 at 91 5/8; American Home Products was up
13/16 at 43.
</P>
<P>
	   Roche Sales Rise 12 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) -- Pumped up by strong sales of its new
diet drug, Swiss pharmaceutical firm Roche Holding AG's 1999 sales
jumped 12 percent, the company said today. Sales for the company's
flagship drug division gained 15 percent to $10.6 billion. Overall,
the company's 1999 sales were $17.7 billion. The company did not
release profit results for 1999. Roche said sales of its Xenical
obesity drug, which was launched in the United States in May,
totaled nearly $640 million. Roche's beleaguered vitamins and fine
chemicals division picked up 1 percent to $2.3 billion. Roche is
still reeling from a $500 million fine from the U.S. Justice
Department for its involvement in a worldwide price-fixing
conspiracy over vitamins.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwab To Acquire U.S. Trust Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Charles Schwab Corp., which owns the nation's
largest discount and online brokerage, is buying an investment firm
that caters to the rich for $2.7 billion in stock. Schwab said
today it has signed a definitive agreement to acquire U.S. Trust
Corp. in a bid to create a business serving investors ``at every
stage of their financial growth.'' The combined company would have
annual revenue of $4.5 billion and earnings of $663 million and
about $800 billion in assets under management. Schwab stock was up
</P>
<P>
 1/2 at 38 1/8; U.S. Trust was up 48 5/8 at 127 1/2.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch Industries Fined for Pollution
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Environmental Protection Agency today
slapped Koch Industries with $35 million in fines and penalties as
part of a settlement over alleged contamination of lakes and
streams in six states from Missouri to Texas. Based in Wichita,
Kan., the company operates more than 35,000 miles of pipeline in
the United States and Canada, and has refineries in Texas and
Minnesota through its Koch Petroleum Group subsidiary. The
settlement, announced by the EPA and Justice Department, stems from
allegations that the company had more than 300 oil spills from its
pipelines and other oil operations, resulting in 3 million gallons
of crude oil pouring into lakes and streams in Texas, Oklahoma,
Kansas, Alabana, Louisiana and Missouri. Koch Pipeline Co. said in
a statement that pipeline leaks had been reduced by 90 percent
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
	   Fannie Mae Reports Record Profits
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fannie Mae said today that its profits rose to
a record $3.9 billion last year from $3.4 billion in 1998, boosted
by continued growth in its mortgage business and a reduction of
credit-related losses. The nation's largest mortgage-market company
said it earned $3.72 a share on a diluted basis in 1999, up 15.2
percent from $3.23 a year earlier. Chairman and CEO Franklin Raines
called 1999's financial results ``extraordinary'' and called the
outlook ``extremely bright' despite the possibility of further
interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
	   Brunswick Closing N. America Plants
</P>
<P>
	   LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Brunswick Corp. said today it will
close its North American bicycle plants, lay off 80 percent of its
bicycle-division work force and move the unit's manufacturing
business to Asia to cope with rising imports and falling prices.
About 750 people at Brunswick's two Mexican plants and 325
employees at its Olney plant will be affected by the closings, said
Kathryn Chieger, spokeswoman for the Lake Forest-based company.	   ``We would
plan to be out of manufacturing by the end of June,''
Chieger said. Olney will remain the company's distribution and
warehousing center for the Roadmaster brand, she said.
</P>
