<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The First Couple Commutes in Style  </HEADLINE>
   By ANNE GEARAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- On their first day as real New York commuters on Thursday,
President Clinton left home in the suburbs and headed off to work with help from
a phalanx of police, while his wife enjoyed the morning paper's favorable review
of her Letterman debut.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clintons are feeling their way in the uncharted territory of a commuter
White House, with the president making drop-by visits to the family's new home
in the tony New York suburb of Chappaqua. Hillary Rodham Clinton is living there
pretty much full-time now, using the handsome, $1.7 million house as home base
for her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   They left that home in the morning for what are now two very different jobs.
The president, road-testing some themes for his State of the Union address later
this month, had a barrage of economic incentive ideas to discuss during stops in
Brooklyn and Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   There were also a party on the floor of the New York Stock Exchange, a
swank, $5,000-a-couple Democratic fund-raising reception and a few opportunities
for the modern helpmate husband to boost his wife's nascent political career.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I always like to come to New York and give my wife a plug,'' Clinton joked
during a morning appearance at a Brooklyn community college.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, Clinton got a laugh after performing butler duty at a luncheon speech
-- helping one speaker to the podium and picking up another's dropped
eyeglasses.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm just practicing for my role as a Senate spouse,'' Clinton deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton campaigned nearby on Long Island and basked in good press after
Wednesday's star turn on the Manhattan-based Late Show with David Letterman.
</P>
<P>
	   Her husband marveled admiringly that her performance dealt him a double dose
of humility -- not only did it underscore the fact that he will soon leave his
post as president, ``but now I have to give up my role as the funny one in the
family, too.''
</P>
<P>
	   Although they commuted to their Thursday appointments, the Clintons are not
exactly straphangers. Clinton was supposed to whisk from Westchester County to
Brooklyn by helicopter, but bad weather forced him to drive in a 14-car, heavily
protected motorcade. Police blocked all traffic as the president passed, causing
large backups, and the toll booth operators waved him by without charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton travels lighter, but still with the Secret Service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
