<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Grows for Manufacturers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Inflation pressures are beginning to mount for U.S.
manufacturers, according to a recent Dun &AMP; Bradstreet survey that found
executives a bit more upbeat about business prospects in the first quarter of
this year than they were in late 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   A companion survey for the construction industry, also conducted in
December, reported executives anticipate a gradual slowdown following what
appeared to be a record-setting performance by builders last year.
</P>
<P>
	   The survey of 1,000 manufacturing executives reported prices remained low
and stable at the end of 1999 but suggested manufacturing prices may start to
climb in the new year, Dun &AMP; Bradstreet said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Over one in five manufacturers expect to see their costs go up in the next
three months. About that same proportion plan to increase their selling prices
over that same period," said David T. Kresge, chief economist for Dun &AMP;
Bradstreet, a private business-information service.
</P>
<P>
	   The survey of 200 U.S. construction executives also reported expectations of
rising prices. In addition, the survey said growth of construction orders slowed
for a second straight month in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Construction companies also reported employment levels decreasing more
rapidly than usual for this time of year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
