<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 48.63; Nasdaq Up 33.11  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher today as technology shares
recovered from a two-day slump and the broader market gained strength from a
report of relatively modest inflation. Investors remained fairly cautious in the
hours ahead of a speech by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
48.63 at 11,599.73.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were also slightly higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 10.68 at 1,442.93, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 33.11
at 3,883.13.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose after the Labor Department said that while prices at the
wholesale level shot up 3 percent in 1999, the biggest increase in nine years,
most of the increase came from the volatile energy sector. Excluding energy,
wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent last year, a more modest showing than in
1998.
</P>
<P>
	   For December, the Producer Price Index, which measures inflation pressures
before they reach the consumer, was up 0.3 percent, right on target with many
analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   The reports boosted investors' confidence that inflation is not escalating
quickly enough to merit sharp interest-rate increases by the Federal Reserve.
Higher interest rates can hurt stocks by cutting into corporate profits as it
becomes more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed raised interest rates three times in 1999 in an effort to keep
inflation at bay, and in recent sessions, stocks have been pressured by fears
that another series of rate hikes are ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Today's report eased some of those fears, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Fed is not behind the curve on inflation," said David Orr, chief
economist at First Union Securities Inc. While most analysts remain convinced
that the Fed will raise rates by 25 basis points, or a quarter percentage point,
at its next meeting on Feb. 1 and 2, today's report suggested the Fed won't
increase rates beyond that amount, Orr said.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was fairly volatile as investors waited for more evidence on the
Fed's likely course. Tonight, Greenspan was discussing technology and the
economy in a speech before the Economic Club of New York. Greenspan has
occasionally used his public speeches as an occasion to telegraph the Fed's
sentiment about the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   And Friday, the government will report on price pressures at the retail
level when it releases its Consumer Price Index. Analysts expect the index to
have risen 0.3 percent in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Beyond the interest rate debate, Apple Computer rose 9 3/16 to 96 3/8 after
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on the stock to "outperform" from
"neutral." An analyst said Apple shares should reach 120 in a year.
</P>
<P>
	   Computer maker Dell rose 1 1/16 to 42 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Trust soared 45 1/2 to 124 3/8 after agreeing to be acquired by Charles
Schwab for $2.7 billion, or about $129 per share.
</P>
<P>
	   The pharmaceutical sector drew investors as Warner-Lambert said it would
hold merger talks with hostile suitor Pfizer, abandoning its November decision
to be acquired by American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading, Warner-Lambert was up 5 3/16 to 92, Pfizer was up 1
5/16 to 36 7/16 and American Home Products was up 1 to 43 3/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-8 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 673.90 million shares, ahead of Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 6.58 to 496.62.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1527 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
