<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consultants' bill: $108,000 to help SUNY 'find' King  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - It apparently cost about $27,000 per block to find
the State University of New York's new chancellor.
<P>
	   That's what a Los Angeles consulting firm wants - $108,667 in all - for
helping SUNY run a national search to find its new chancellor, documents
obtained by The Associated Press show.
</P>
<P>
	   That search ended with last month's hiring of former Pataki state Budget
Director Robert King, who worked four blocks away from SUNY's central
administration building the entire time.
</P>
<P>
	   Such a payment to management firm Korn/Ferry International makes no sense,
especially when SUNY already is having money problems, Assembly Majority Leader
Michael Bragman of Onondaga County said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We all know that Bob King has always had the inside track for this job and
such a huge payment to an outside consultant is outrageous," Bragman said. "As
far as I know ... I think there was only one other candidate besides Bob King. I
question if a national search was necessary to identify a candidate from within
our state government who works just a few blocks away."
</P>
<P>
	   The SUNY system is controlled by Gov. George Pataki through his appointments
to the SUNY Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
	   A trustees' search committee unanimously recommended King - a former
prosecutor, colleague of Pataki's in the Legislature and bureaucrat in Pataki's
administration - to be chancellor over Stanley Koplick, chancellor of the
Massachusetts state university system.
</P>
<P>
	   Koplick died Jan. 3, two days after King officially started as SUNY
chancellor.
</P>
<P>
	   King's hiring in December culminated a long search which began in January
1999 when former SUNY Chancellor John Ryan said he wanted to retire. Korn/Ferry
was hired in July.
</P>
<P>
	   SUNY spokesman Jon Sorensen said King was not preordained to be chancellor
because of his relationship with the Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
	   "He went through the process like everyone else," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Sorensen also said Korn/Ferry deserves its money because it did a true
national search.
</P>
<P>
	   "They put together quite a long roster of people, many of whom were
interviewed and explored," he said. "They presented a list of traditional and
nontraditional candidates and it's wrong to accuse these people of not working
hard because they did. They earned their money with a lot of time and the result
of this search turned out well."
</P>
<P>
	   Sorensen said six candidates were interviewed for the chancellor's job.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said the complaints by Bragman, a Democrat,
about the Korn/Ferry search is "just partisan politics."
</P>
<P>
	   Korn/Ferry hasn't been paid yet because state Comptroller H. Carl McCall has
yet to approve the firm's contract with SUNY.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have the contract, it's under review and we have questions we have asked
the state university," McCall spokesman Dennis Tompkins said. "We have some
procedural and some substantive questions."
</P>
<P>
	   Tompkins would not say what questions the comptroller, who is also a
Democrat, has about the contract. SUNY cannot pay Korn/Ferry until the
comptroller approves the contract.
</P>
<P>
	   Sorensen said one of the questions that SUNY is refusing to answer is who
the other four finalists for chancellor were. "We insured our finalists privacy
because they have jobs in higher education that could be jeopardized," he said.
"We find (the questions) highly irregular and inappropriate. We made commitments
to these finalists."
</P>
<P>
	   A call to Korn/Ferry's offices in New York City was not immediately returned
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers like Bragman said they know what questions they would like to ask
to SUNY.
</P>
<P>
	   The university system's teaching hospitals have to transfer $116 million of
its state government funds to the SUNY system every year because of a
legislative mandate. However, it is unlikely the hospitals will be able to come
up with the money this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The teaching hospitals in Stony Brook, Syracuse and Brooklyn were only able
to transfer $39 million last year and had to borrow the rest.
</P>
<P>
	   Assembly Democrats have complained about the university system hiring
high-priced consultants while it has this money problem. For example, SUNY is
paying nationally-recognized health care consulting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers
$1.1 million to investigate SUNY's teaching hospital finances and recommend ways
to make the hospitals fiscally viable again.
</P>
<P>
	   However, that report is not due until February, a month after Pataki has
submitted his state budget to the Legislature. Therefore, Pataki and King did
not offer any suggestions on how to end the hospitals' fiscal crisis during the
executive budget message, Bragman said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It just appears to me that it's a continuing pattern of fiscal
irresponsibility," Bragman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1600 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman announces $6.3 million revitalization project for Camden  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman on Thursday announced a $6.3
million plan to restore 65 abandoned homes in an East Camden neighborhood
frequented by drug dealers and prostitutes.
<P>
	   The project is an extension of the plan launched last year to beautify
Admiral Wilson Boulevard, a tawdry gateway into New Jersey dotted with seedy
motels, a strip club and liquor stores.
</P>
<P>
	   The homes are located just off the infamous boulevard and the neighborhood
has been infected with crime from the 2-mile strip. Vacant lots are filled with
debris, the sidewalks are crumbling and the streets need repair.
</P>
<P>
	   "Believe me when I tell you it's very bad," said resident Emma Graham, 65,
who lives on Baird Boulevard. "Any help we're going to get will be appreciated."
</P>
<P>
	   Graham, who stood next to Whitman on a dilapidated sidewalk strewn with
broken glass, appealed to the governor for help ridding the neighborhood of
prostitutes who stroll the street and drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
	   "The boulevard is entrenched with prostitutes. We put up with it," said
Graham, a retired business owner who has lived here since 1970. "Sometimes it's
overbearing."
</P>
<P>
	   Graham said she had to chase away a prostitute who was sitting on her stoop
with a rubber band around her arm shooting up drugs. The hardest part, she said,
is trying to field questions from her granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
	   "My granddaughter asked me 'what are those ladies doing,"' she recalled.
"What are you going to tell a 5-year-old?"
</P>
<P>
	   State Transportation Commissioner James Weinstein said the revitalization
project announced Thursday is an attempt to "help make Camden a better place to
live, work and raise a family."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman said the project should help stabilize the neighborhood and clean up
crime. The state is also providing $200,000 for new lighting, which should deter
criminals, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The state has been criticized by some for the Admiral Wilson Boulevard
project, which is expected to cost up to $90 million. Businesses - legitimate
and shady - will be replaced with a scenic view for motorists.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman's goal is to spruce the area up in time for this summer's Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia. Many delegates have already booked rooms in
New Jersey hotels and will likely travel along the boulevard.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor said the state is not ignoring neighborhoods in the
9-square-mile city of 87,000. The state pumps millions of dollars annually into
Camden, the poorest city in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   "As we move ahead with our Gateway Project to fix up the boulevard, we're
building on our commitment to fix up the neighborhoods of Camden," Whitman said.
"The boulevard may be one of the city's major arteries, but the neighborhoods
are its heart and soul."
</P>
<P>
	   The neighborhood is just a few blocks from The Alley, a notorious drug area
allegedly run by the largest cocaine cartel in Camden's history. Two accused
drug lords are on trial in federal court.
</P>
<P>
	   The project calls for about 65 homes to be repaired over a three-year
period, according to state Department of Community Affairs Commissioner Jane
Kenny. The first group of homes should be completed by this summer, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The abandoned properties, scattered throughout the neighborhood in the
city's Marlton section, will be rebuilt by St. Joseph's Carpenter's Society, a
nonprofit church affiliated group that has redeveloped more than 200 Camden
houses.
</P>
<P>
	   The renovated houses will cost between $45,000 and $55,000 and will be sold
to low- and moderate-income families who will be offered low-interest mortgages,
officials said. Whitman said the goal is to keep residents in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not a yuppie-fying of a neighborhood," Whitman said. "We are making
it affordable to people."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1601 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
