<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NU, utility regulators discuss sale of nuclear plants  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) - Northeast Utilities and state regulators
Thursday hashed out the details of how to sell NU's nuclear power plants as
foreseen in the electric deregulation law.
<P>
	   Leaders of NU and consumer advocates agreed that the state should try to get
the highest possible price for the plants, but differed on the best way to do
it.
</P>
<P>
	   The Department of Public Utility Control is scheduled to set the ground
rules for the sale of the plants on Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale of plants is meant to divorce Connecticut from a regulated power
system to a system where the price for power is subject to the free market and
competition. The deregulation law is intended to lower electricity prices and
bring better service.
</P>
<P>
	   The law requires the plants to be auctioned by the end of 2003, if NU wants
to collect "stranded costs," or future payments from customers to cover debts
the utility incurred under decades of regulation. The higher price the plants
get, the lower the stranded costs will be.
</P>
<P>
	   NU wants to sell the plants sooner, maybe as soon as this summer, since at
least four companies are interested in the plants and interest rates are low.
</P>
<P>
	   NU thinks it can get the highest price if the three Millstone plants in
Waterford are auctioned off as a group, including Millstone Unit 1, which is
being decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
	   The company hopes to start the auction in March and have a winning bidder by
August, pending regulatory approvals, said Bruce Kenyon, the head of NU's
nuclear operations.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seabrook Station plant in New Hampshire should be considered separately
and sold at a later time, when New Hampshire leaders approve a settlement
agreement with the company, said Michael Morris, the president, chairman and
chief executive of NU.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruce Johnson from the Office of Consumer Counsel questioned whether it
would be better to wait to include Seabrook in the auction, since that plant
combined with Millstone Unit 3 account for about 20 percent of the electric
power capacity in New England.
</P>
<P>
	   NU also had said when it bought the Seabrook plant that it could save $61
million in operation and maintenance costs by operating the two big plants
together, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
	   NU's leaders responded that the savings have not been nearly as great as
anticipated and that Connecticut should not wait on the sale of the Millstone
plants until New Hampshire leaders to decide what to do.
</P>
<P>
	   "Delaying the auction six months, we believe, would disserve customers in
Connecticut," Morris said.
</P>
<P>
	   Likewise, Kenyon said that companies interested in buying the Millstone
plants would want to buy all three plants at once, even though Millstone Unit 1
is no longer generating power and must go through the lengthy decommissioning
process.
</P>
<P>
	   "A buyer would prefer to control the entire site," Kenyon said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenyon said one company interested in buying the Millstone plants is AmerGen
Energy Co., a consortium of a British company and PECO Energy Co. of
Philadelphia, which recently bought the operating reactor at Three Mile Island
and plans to buy Vermont Yankee.
</P>
<P>
	   Other interested companies are: Entergy Corp. of New Orleans, which operates
four nuclear power plants and is decommissioning Millstone 1; PECO and Virginia
Power, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Connecticut Coalition Against Millstone, which was allowed to
participate in some of Thursday's hearing, argued that the DPUC should require
bidders for the NU plants to demonstrate that they can operate the plants
safely. The group's lawyer, Nancy Burton, also said an escrow account should be
set up for decommissioning funds to ensure the money is not misused.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawyers for NU said these issues will be addressed when the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission reviews plans to transfer the plants' operating licenses
once a bid is awarded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1620 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rescuers Reach S. Africa Miners  </HEADLINE>
   By DANIEL J. WAKIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Rescuers, clawing with shovels and their
bare hands, broke through a wall of rock Thursday night to reach nine miners
entombed for four days below more than a mile of earth and rock.
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors were examining the first of the rescued miners in an underground
area before bringing him to the surface, mine officials said. All were expected
to reach the surface Thursday night and would be taken to a hospital, mine
spokeswoman Merle Gouws said.
</P>
<P>
	   A short crawl away from where the miners had awaited rescue, four comrades
lay dead from Monday's rock fall at the African Rainbow Minerals gold mine in
Orkney, about 110 miles southwest of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
	   Hopes were fading that two severely injured miners were still alive.
Rescuers were moving toward them, Ms. Gouws said.
</P>
<P>
	   The rescue effort, progressing inch by agonizing inch, captured national
attention in a country built on mining, where hundreds die every year deep in
the earth's recesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Gold accounts for one-fifth of South Africa's export earnings. Pulling it
from the nation's shafts remains grueling and deadly work for the mainly black
employees despite safety improvements since the end of white minority rule in
1994. South African gold mines are particularly dangerous because they are among
the deepest in the world, and more subject to earth tremors like the one that
caused Monday's rock fall.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 200 rescuers, many from other mining companies, joined the effort in
Orkney, working in eight-hour shifts. They have dug through 300 tons of dirt and
rock, clearing a path through a 60-foot upward-sloping tunnel, said Peter
Steenkamp, the mine manager. At times, the passage was only 18 inches high,
forcing the rescuers to wriggle forward on elbows and knees.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier Thursday, rescuers were able to speak to the main group of trapped
miners, Steenkamp said.
</P>
<P>
	   The rescuers used hand drills to bust up debris, winches to pull out
boulders and shovels and their hands to scoop away dirt and gravel, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rescuers were able to establish contact through the air pipe Tuesday
evening, after the miners spent 30 hours in isolation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The first thing they wanted was water,'' mine spokeswoman Charmane Russell
said. ``They have since been in relatively good spirits, working with the
rescuers and quite calm, which is important.''
</P>
<P>
	   Through the tube, they were being sent water, a nutritional drink and
fluorescent tubes that throw off light when broken, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Two workers were lying about 100 feet away from the main group. They had
been too severely hurt to move when the others made their way toward the main
shaft after the rock fall, Steenkamp said.
</P>
<P>
	   The two severely injured miners have been without food or water since
Monday, as it was too difficult for the other workers to get back to them. ``The
chances are not good'' that they would survive, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The accident victims were a cross-section of the South African mining
industry's workers, who number 430,000, more than half in gold mines. Eight were
from Lesotho, two from Mozambique, one from Swaziland and four from South
Africa. The migrant miners often support large extended families on average
salaries of $430 a month.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1999, 312 workers died in mining accidents, according to the minerals and
energy ministry. The fatality rate has declined since 1993, from 1.08 per 1,000
minors in 1993 to 0.86 five years later. Serious accidents -- meaning four or
more dead -- have dropped from 14 in 1992 to one last year, the industry says.
</P>
<P>
	   The Orkney mine, which dates from the 1950s, was the scene of one of the
nation's worst mining accidents. In 1995, a mine train fell into an elevator
shaft on a carriage full of men, killing 104.
</P>
<P>
	   The mine was then owned by Anglo-American. The mining giant sold it in
January 1998 to black investors. Five miners have died there since, Ms. Russell
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1628 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closes at New High 11,582.43  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose today after a report of relatively modest
inflation boosted the bond market and calmed jittery stock investors. Financial
shares led the Dow Jones industrials to a new closing record.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow rose 31.33 to close at 11,582.43, just past its previous record of
11,572.20.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators also closed higher. The Nasdaq composite index
broke out of a two-day slump to finish up 107.24 at 3,957.26.
</P>
<P>
	   Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 17.46 to 1,449.71.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, with 1,861 up, 1,219 down and 427 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   NYSE volume totaled 1.02 billion shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 968.78 million in
the previous session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 11.15 to 501.19.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose after the Labor Department said inflation remained under control
in 1999. The department's Producer Price Index, which measures inflation
pressures before they reach the consumer, shot up 3 percent in 1999, the biggest
increase in nine years.
</P>
<P>
	   But most of the increase came from the volatile energy sector. Excluding
energy, wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent last year. For December, the
index rose 0.3 percent, right on target with many analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   The reports boosted investors' confidence that inflation is not escalating
quickly enough to merit sharp interest-rate increases by the Federal Reserve.
Higher interest rates can hurt stocks by cutting into corporate profits as it
becomes more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed raised interest rates three times in 1999 in an effort to keep
inflation under control, and in recent sessions, stocks have been pressured by
fears that another series of rate hikes are ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Today's report eased some of those fears, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Fed is not behind the curve on inflation," said David Orr, chief
economist at First Union Securities Inc. While most analysts remain convinced
that the Fed will raise rates by 25 basis points, or a quarter percentage point,
at its next meeting on Feb. 1 and 2, today's report suggested the Fed won't
increase rates beyond that amount, Orr said.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond dipped to 6.65 percent from 6.71
percent late Wednesday, benefiting bank and brokerage stocks that often suffer
when rates are rising. J.P. Morgan and Citigroup rose.
</P>
<P>
	   Merger activity also enlivened the sector. U.S. Trust, an investment firm
that caters to wealthy clients, soared after agreeing to be acquired by online
and discount broker Charles Schwab for $2.7 billion, or about $129 per share.
</P>
<P>
	   "That deal has prompted many investors to look at this sector in a new light
and consider other possible combinations," said Ned Riley, chief investment
strategist at State Street Global Advisors in Boston.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest development in the consolidating drug industry also sparked
buying. Warner-Lambert said today it would hold merger talks with hostile suitor
Pfizer, abandoning its November decision to be acquired by American Home
Products.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of all three companies rose.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks reversed two days of steep losses. Apple Computer rose
after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on the stock to "outperform"
from "neutral." Analyst Gillian Munson applauded the company's strong product
pipeline and said Apple shares should reach 120 in a year.
</P>
<P>
	   "Despite some weakness so far this year, there is still a strong conviction
that the money to be made in this market is in technology stocks," Riley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was fairly volatile as investors waited for more evidence on the
Fed's likely course. Tonight, Greenspan was to discuss technology and the
economy in a speech before the Economic Club of New York. Greenspan has
occasionally used his public speeches as an occasion to telegraph the Fed's
sentiment about the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   And Friday, the government will report on price pressures at the retail
level when it releases its Consumer Price Index. Analysts expect the index to
have risen 0.3 percent in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
