<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Bureaus To Settle Charges  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's three major credit bureaus have agreed to
pay $2.5 million total to settle charges that consumers calling their toll-free
lines could not reach personnel to discuss credit reports, regulators said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Trade Commission alleged that the national consumer reporting
agencies -- Equifax Credit Information Services Inc., Experian Inc. and Trans
Union LLC -- blocked millions of calls from consumers during business hours.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumers who wanted to talk about the contents of their credit report or
possible errors were met with busy signals or a message indicating that they
should call back because all representatives were occupied, the commission said.
Others were kept on hold for long amounts of time, the FTC said.
</P>
<P>
	   Regulators charged that these practices constituted violations of the Fair
Credit Reporting Act. That law was amended in 1997 to require the major credit
bureaus to give consumers who receive copies of their credit report toll-free
telephone numbers to reach employees during business hours.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The reality is that consumers never got the access to the consumer
reporting agencies that the law guarantees,'' said Jodie Bernstein, director of
the FTC's bureau of consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the FTC's complaint, more than a million callers trying to
reach Trans Union and Experian received a busy signal or a call back message.
The complaint against Equifax contains similar charges impacting hundreds of
thousands of customers.
</P>
<P>
	   A number of consumers were kept on hold for what the commission called
``unreasonable'' amounts of time, waiting to speak to personnel. The FTC also
charged that Equifax and Trans Union blocked incoming telephone calls from
certain area codes because they assumed those consumers should only be handled
by their affiliates.
</P>
<P>
	   The FTC said the bureaus have to permit such calls to go through.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the terms of the consent agreement, the three companies must answer
consumers' calls within three minutes and thirty seconds on average. In
addition, 90 percent of consumers who call the bureaus must be connected to
personnel without getting a busy signal.
</P>
<P>
	   Experian, which receives about 1 million phone calls to its consumer
assistance center each month, pledged that representatives would be available to
consumers who have a copy of a credit report from the bureau. Automated systems
would be used when appropriate, said the Ohio corporation which operates out of
Orange, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   Experian and Trans Union will pay $1 million, while Equifax has agreed to
pay $500,000.
</P>
<P>
	   The Atlanta-based Equifax asserted that the commission's allegations only
referred to a very small percentage of its customers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We handle 99.9 percent with a high degree of accuracy,'' said Alan Boyer,
the company's vice president of communications. Boyer said his credit bureau has
already instituted the standards required by the settlement.
</P>
<P>
	   Trans Union, based in Chicago, has made additional investments by installing
new phone systems and expanding its staffing to enhance its service, said the
company's consumer relations vice president Dave Wolff. He said the company
would work to exceed the standards set by the FTC.
</P>
<P>
	   The bureaus also have agreed to conduct internal audits to ensure they are
complying with guidelines.
</P>
<P>
	   The proposed settlements were filed Thursday in U.S. District Courts in
Illinois, Georgia and Texas by the Justice Department, on behalf of the FTC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1630 </TRAILER>
