<DOCNO> APW20000113.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Miffed at Venezuelan Refusal  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. officials expressed dismay Thursday at Venezuelan
President Hugo Chavez's refusal to accept two shiploads of U.S. troops and
equipment to help recovery from devastating floods.
</P>
<P>
	   One ship en route was slowed down and another held back at a North Carolina
port while officials sought clarification of remarks by Chavez, who said he does
not want U.S. soldiers in his country.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Well, we were surprised by the reported comments,'' said Pentagon
spokesman Ken Bacon, indicating that U.S. officials had not heard directly from
Chavez's government on the matter. The Pentagon had started deployment of 450
U.S. Marine and Navy engineers to help rebuild a coastal road damaged by Dec. 15
flooding that killed thousands of Venezuelans.
</P>
<P>
	   They were expected to work in Venezuela for two months or more.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Clearly, if they don't want the help, we won't provide it,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
	   At the State Department, spokesman James P. Rubin said, ``We're asking the
government of Venezuela for clarification.'' He cited a Dec. 24 letter in which
Venezuela's defense minister ``specifically requested the assistance of U.S.
military engineers to open up a humanitarian corridor for flood-ravaged coastal
communities.''
</P>
<P>
	   Rubin said the deployment was authorized after close coordination with
Venezuelan authorities and as part of a $25 million U.S. aid package.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez's government earlier welcomed U.S. help, including about 120 soldiers
operating water purification facilities, Blackhawk helicopters, C-130 cargo
planes and a C-5 Galaxy cargo plane. Their continued deployment remained in
doubt.
</P>
<P>
	   The USS Tortuga and the USS Nashville were to transport bulldozers, tractors
and engineering equipment along with the troops to operate and maintain them.
The Tortuga was being slowed down in its trip and the Nashville was held at
Moorhead City, N.C., until the Venezuelan position is clarified, Pentagon
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, Chavez told reporters that while Venezuela still needs more
money, equipment and other materials, additional relief workers are unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to clarify before Venezuela and the world that North American
troops are not going to come to Venezuela,'' Chavez said. ``If they want to send
machines or other types of equipment we are open to that, and we are very
thankful for the intention to help.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bacon said U.S. equipment cannot be supplied without people to run it,
maintain it and bring it back home after the work is done.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez, a former army paratrooper elected a year ago, has been accused by
opponents of using the floods and killer mudslides to consolidate his power,
eliminating Congress, replacing the Supreme Court and hand-picking top judicial
officials. Chavez's backers say he is merely taking steps mandated in his
election victory to crush a corrupt oligarchy and help the nation's poor.
</P>
<P>
	   Chavez has bolstered relations with communist Cuba and has been critical of
U.S. global influence. He earlier refused to allow U.S. planes to fly over
Venezuela in anti-narcotics operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
