<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golan Residents Await Peace  </HEADLINE>
   By RON KAMPEAS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MAJDAL SHAMS, Golan Heights (AP) -- Nayef Guzardin remembers his earliest
lesson in land mine detection.
</P>
<P>
	   He was 8, and his teacher told the class to bring in any lethal device they
could find -- in their backyards, in the apple orchards surrounding the village,
in the sheep meadows where their fathers worked.
</P>
<P>
	   His classmates collected an arsenal: anti-tank mines, anti-personnel mines,
hand grenades, bullets.
</P>
<P>
	   The teacher then delivered the lesson. He beat each child with a stick until
he promised never to touch military hardware again.
</P>
<P>
	   All except Guzardin. He knew better.
</P>
<P>
	   Two years earlier, Guzardin had picked up a curious device lying next to his
balcony. It blew off his forearm and scattered shrapnel throughout his body.
</P>
<P>
	   The International Campaign to Ban Landmines estimates there are 76
minefields planted across the Golan Heights, most by Israel and some by the
Syrian army.
</P>
<P>
	   Residents hope that after three decades of casualties -- 16 deaths and 200
injuries -- the mines will be cleared once there is peace between the hostile
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
	   The 18,000 Druse Arabs who live in four villages along the mountainous
demarcation line -- where most of the minefields lie -- have despaired of an
Israeli government they say cares more for its soldiers than the civilians who
live in the Golan.
</P>
<P>
	   The Druse -- members of a sect that broke with Islam in the 12th century --
say the army refuses to remove the mines and the Education Ministry has done
nothing to warn residents of their danger.
</P>
<P>
	   The army says minefields -- some planted as recently as two years ago -- are
the result of a hostile border. In all cases, the army insists, the fields are
clearly marked.
</P>
<P>
	   But the barbed-wire fence surrounding a two-acre minefield on the frontier
is broken in many places, and only two ``Danger, Mines'' signs have survived the
elements and brushfires set by troops seeking to prevent cross-border
incursions.
</P>
<P>
	   The fence borders on an orchard where village children help pick apples each
autumn. In November, four teen-agers working the orchard were wounded when an
anti-personnel mine exploded while they examined it at home. One lost a leg.
</P>
<P>
	   It was an all too familiar story to Saleh Baarar, who lost his right leg,
right hand and right eye in 1982, when he was 14.
</P>
<P>
	   He was playing in a sheep meadow his family owned, when his cousin handed
him what looked like a green jar -- a hand grenade.
</P>
<P>
	   ``How was I to know what warfare looked like?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
	   Teaching children how to detect land mines and other lethal devices is
virtually unknown in Israel. Education Ministry spokesman David Gorali listed a
few informal courses -- none aimed at the Druse children in the Golan.
London-based Save the Children, which operates courses in other land
mine-intensive areas, has no Golan program.
</P>
<P>
	   The Druse do not blame discrimination for the laissez-faire attitude. They
note that Jewish settlers and tourists -- including Jerry White, now director of
the Washington, D.C.-based Landmine Survivors Network -- have also fallen
victims to mines.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is just pure thick headedness,'' said Salman Saharadeen, a Druse
activist who campaigns for the Golan's return to Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   Such ignorance can be lethal in this terraced village near the
Israeli-Syrian demarcation line, where land mines loosened by winter snows
tumble into backyards.
</P>
<P>
	   That was what took the life of Amir Abu Jabel, a 4-year-old killed in his
front yard as he picked flowers in 1989.
</P>
<P>
	   The risk to civilians is outweighed by the risk to troops, the army says.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In certain cases, the security danger to soldiers in working in an area
that is mined or highly suspected of being mined is higher than the danger that
citizens will be harmed from them,'' the army spokesman's office said.
</P>
<P>
	   That enrages local Druse, who note that the army lends its de-mining skills
to countries such as Cambodia and Africa, while ignoring the Golan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Am I a resident or just paying taxes?'' asks Baarar, who rebuilt his life
and now owns two businesses inside Israel. ``Clean up your house and then go
elsewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1650 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
