<HEADLINE> Retirees' HMOs Said Overpaid  </HEADLINE>
   By ALICE ANN LOVE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- HMOs that enroll senior citizens get billions of dollars
too much from Medicare because their fees are based on overblown cost estimates,
government investigators say.
</P>
<P>
	   In a report released Thursday, Health and Human Services Department
Inspector General June Gibbs Brown said investigators found ``compelling
information that managed care companies are financially benefitting from the
present process used to calculate the Medicare monthly capitation payments.''
</P>
<P>
	   About 6 million of Medicare's 39 million elderly and disabled beneficiaries
are enrolled in HMOs -- private health plans that accept a flat monthly fee from
the government to provide all needed care.
</P>
<P>
	   Current HMO fees are based on a formula set by Congress in 1997, which
predicted retirees' medical costs in that year to be 4.2 percent higher than
they actually turned out to be, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   Because HMO payment increases in subsequent years have been added to the
1997 base rate, the 4.2 percent overpayments persist from year to year. The
report said if that continues, it would mean $11 billion in overpayments over
the next five years and $34 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Medicare administrator Nancy-Ann DeParle said in a letter responding to the
report that President Clinton has proposed legislation to change the way HMO
fees are calculated, eliminating the problem.
</P>
<P>
	   That legislation, however, has not been approved by Congress. Lawmakers
voted last fall to give HMOs a raise after many pulled out of the Medicare
business in 1999 complaining that they are not paid enough.
</P>
<P>
	   Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the American Association of Health Plans,
noted that even taking into account the new report's conclusions -- which the
group disagrees with -- HMOs get paid less per Medicare patient than the average
amount the government spends for those not enrolled in an HMO.
</P>
<P>
	   HHS investigators, however, have concluded that the health plans are
overpaid in other ways as well. In a report last year, Brown noted that
Medicare's 11 percent overall rate of overpayments due to fraud and errors is
also built into the formula for HMO fees, for example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1655 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wash. Post Buys Back Shares  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Post Co. announced plans Thursday to buy
back 500,000 shares of its Class B common stock. Company directors have set no
ceiling price or time limit for the repurchase offer.
</P>
<P>
	   With 7,700,496 shares outstanding, the buyback offer is valued at nearly
$294 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The offer was announced on the same day that Post board members voted to
increase the annual dividend rate by 20 cents to $5.40 per share. The first
quarter payment of $1.35 will be made on Feb. 4 to all Jan. 28 shareholders of
record.
</P>
</TEXT>
