<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Finalize New Crash Dummy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal safety agency said Thursday it has finalized
specifications for a new crash dummy representing a 6-year-old child that will
be used in testing to help protect young children from being killed or injured
by car air bags.
</P>
<P>
	   Until now, the government has required automakers to pass crash tests for
air bags using only adult male dummies. But the 146 people killed by inflating
air bags have been mostly young, unbelted children and small women, the very
people automakers have not been required to design for in meeting government
regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has proposed new federal
air bag tests using a ``family'' of test dummies aimed at preventing children
and small adults from being harmed by the next generation of advanced air bags.
</P>
<P>
	   The government proposal to regulate air bags in future cars is scheduled to
become final by March 1, a deadline imposed by Congress. By then, agency
officials said they would have the specifications for all the dummies, including
a slender female and a 3-year-old child and an infant.
</P>
<P>
	   But for now, the 6-year-old so-called Hybrid III dummy is the first to be
certified for compliance tests since the male dummy was adopted in 1986.
</P>
<P>
	   ``These specifications for a child crash dummy will improve highway safety
by helping to clear the way for the introduction of advanced air bags,'' said
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater.
</P>
<P>
	   Hybrid III test dummies representing 6-year-olds have been used in research
for several years. But government officials say the new 6-year-old dummy has a
highly instrumented neck that better simulates human neck responses. That is
important, officials say, because neck injuries are one of the main causes of
child fatalities due to air bags.
</P>
<P>
	   However, some industry groups have expressed concern the air bag might get
caught during testing in a cavity between the dummy's chin and neck that doesn't
exist in humans, leading to false readings of potentially serious neck injuries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1659 </TRAILER>
