<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Talks Resume in Colombia  </HEADLINE>
   By CESAR GARCIA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN VICENTE DEL CAGUAN, Colombia (AP) -- Peace talks resumed outside this
town in southern Colombia on Thursday after guerrilla clashes punctuated the end
of a temporary holiday truce.
</P>
<P>
	   The negotiations were held before a planned visit Friday by U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright to discuss a new $1.3 billion aid proposal for
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright's visit, the first by a chief U.S. diplomat to Colombia since 1990,
underscored Washington's growing concern about the linked threats of drug
trafficking and a powerful leftist insurgency.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton this week proposed the anti-narcotics aid package, with
most of the money earmarked for military helicopters and new army battalions
that would push into southern jungles where the guerrilla presence has limited
anti-drug operations.
</P>
<P>
	   Rebels draw money from the drug trade and protect the flow of drugs out of
the world's top cocaine-exporting nation. U.S. officials are trying to
strengthen Colombia's police and military without getting drawn into the
country's 35-year civil conflict.
</P>
<P>
	   The guerrillas -- and some U.S. lawmakers -- are calling the two-year plan a
counterinsurgency policy in disguise. They warn that it could undermine the
peace process without denting the flow of drugs to the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   However, as government and rebel delegates convened for peace talks, their
tone was positive.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm optimistic because this process is now into its substantive phase,
which means negotiations and discussions of the issues,'' said Fabio Valencia,
one of the five government delegates to the talks with the 15,000-member
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC.
</P>
<P>
	   Talks with the country's largest rebel group have plodded along since they
began in San Vicente del Caguan's main plaza one year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   With no cease-fire in effect, the FARC has carried out several bloody
offensives seen as attempts to bolster its negotiating position. Rival
right-wing paramilitary groups also have continued to kill civilians they accuse
of being rebel sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
	   A 20-day rebel truce, called to give Colombians a Christmas and New Year
reprieve, expired on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, guerrillas attacked police barracks in three neighboring
villages in southern Narino State, killing three officers and one civilian,
authorities said. There were also unconfirmed reports of heavy rebel casualties.
</P>
<P>
	   In a village near San Vicente del Caguan on Thursday, rebel and government
negotiators discussed a plan to hold town meetings to encourage public input
into the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
	   They also were expected to discuss what topic to debate first on a
negotiating agenda that would include sweeping reforms to combat poverty,
political corruption and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
	   The negotiations are taking place in a poor region controlled by the FARC
since last November, when President Andres Pastrana evacuated his troops as a
gesture toward peace.
</P>
<P>
	   Included in the Clinton aid proposal, which now goes to Congress, is $145
million to bring economic development and legal alternatives to poor peasants
who subsist by growing coca and opium plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1700 </TRAILER>
