<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dayton Hudson Changing Name  </HEADLINE>
    By KARREN MILLS AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Dayton Hudson Corp. is aiming for a bull's-eye with the
decision to change its name to Target Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Target is the biggest division and the fastest-growing arm of
Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson, accounting for more than 75 percent of the
company's revenues and profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Target has been the company's top moneymaker since 1977.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a move to demonstrate to the world that they finally acknowledge
that Target is the crown jewel of the Dayton Hudson empire," said Kurt Barnard,
president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report, a retail consulting firm in Upper
Montclair, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no question that it is the one (part) that will ultimately
determine what the rest of the company does,"
</P>
<P>
	   Dayton Hudson, which announced the decision Thursday, said the name change
will take effect Jan. 30 when the company begins its new fiscal year. The
company will trade on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol TGT.
</P>
<P>
	   The company has been prominently advertising Target -- the No. 3 U.S.
discount chain behind Wal-Mart and Kmart -- trying to make the red bull's-eye
logo as recognizable as symbols such as the Nike swoosh.
</P>
<P>
	   While the corporate name will now focus on Target, the change won't affect
any of the company's other store brands and the company said it remains
committed to its Mervyn's chain as well as its Dayton's, Marshall Field's and
Hudson's department stores.
</P>
<P>
	   But Barnard said that the name change may signal that the company is
thinking of restructuring its business.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is a strong possibility," Barnard said, "that sooner or later, and
probably more sooner rather than later, they will divest themselves of Mervyn's,
which has really been lagging badly, and also their department stores."
</P>
<P>
	   Bob Ulrich, Dayton Hudson chairman and chief executive officer, said the
company's main goal continues to be delivering annual earnings per share growth
of 15 percent or more over time.
</P>
<P>
	   This year, Target plans to add about 70 new Target Stores, including 15
larger SuperTargets, which are grocery and discount stores combined.
</P>
<P>
	   The company's stock has been publicly traded since 1967, when the Dayton
Company went public. In 1969, Dayton's merged with J.L. Hudson Co. to form
Dayton Hudson Corp.
</P>
<P>
	   Strong sales at Target stores fueled a 32 percent third-quarter earnings
increase for the period ending Oct. 30. For the first nine months of 1999,
Dayton Hudson earnings rose 27 percent, to $650 million, or $1.39 a share, from
$512 million, or $1.08 a share, a year earlier. Sales rose 10 percent to $22.98
billion, from $20.81 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Dayton Hudson operates 1,245 stores in 44 states, including 914 Target
stores, 267 Mervyn's stores and 64 department stores.
</P>
<P>
	   Dayton Hudson shares rose $1.56 1/4 to $69 as of 4 p.m. on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1701 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0245 </DOCNO>
