<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Approves Shorter Work Week  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France's constitutional watchdog gave its approval Thursday to
a shortened work week, clearing the final hurdle for the controversial law.
</P>
<P>
	   Shortening the work week from 39 hours to 35 has been a key project of the
Socialists since they came to power in June 1997. They hope it will help reduce
France's 11 percent jobless rate by forcing companies to hire more people.
</P>
<P>
	   Conservative lawmakers asked the Constitutional Council to toss out the law
passed last month, saying it creates unequal work conditions.
</P>
<P>
	   The council rejected their arguments but said four minor provisions did not
conform to the constitution, including a 10 percent tax on overtime of employees
on the 35-hour plan.
</P>
<P>
	   The law begins Feb. 1. Companies with more than 20 employees must implement
it by the end of 2000. Smaller companies have an extra year.
</P>
<P>
	   Trucking bosses blockaded France's borders for two days this week to protest
the plan, worried it would affect their competitiveness in Europe. The blockades
ended after officials agreed to let truckers work longer hours if they are paid
overtime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
