<DOCNO> APW20000113.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backs Investment Incentives  </HEADLINE>
   By TERENCE HUNT AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- With a booming stock market and robust economy, President
Clinton said Thursday that Americans ``have a moral obligation'' to bring
prosperity to the nation's neediest urban and rural areas. On the Republican
side, House Speaker Dennis Hastert said it was important that ``no community be
left behind.''
</P>
<P>
	   Two weeks before his State of the Union address, Clinton opened an
election-year drive to win congressional approval of $5 billion worth of tax
incentives over 10 years to encourage investment in depressed areas under a
program he calls ``New Markets.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Economic opportunity should not be the political province of any
particular party,'' Clinton said. ``Economic opportunity should be the
birthright of every American.''
</P>
<P>
	   After a night in his new, $1.7 million home in Chappaqua, the president
followed the path of countless commuters into New York. In Clinton's case,
police cleared the highways for his 14-car motorcade and toll booth operators
waved him by without charge. Long lines of motorists wound up stalled behind
police barricades.
</P>
<P>
	   The president spoke at Boricua College, a largely Hispanic school in an
ethnic neighborhood in Brooklyn. A custodian was shot to death at the college
Monday, and Clinton and other members of the audience observed a moment of
silence.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, the president went to midtown Manhattan for an economic development
program led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson. Jackson's Wall Street Project is intended
to persuade New York's financial leaders to invest capital in minority
businesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton won accolades from Citigroup's chairman, Sanford Weill, for the
stock market's performance. ``I want to thank you for my net worth,'' Weill
declared, saying Citigroup's stock had climbed from $5 a share when Clinton took
office to $55 now.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, deeply in debt with legal bills, replied, ``I'm glad one of us made
money out of this administration.''
</P>
<P>
	   Later, Clinton was speaking at the New York Stock Exchange at a reception
for the Wall Street Project and then attending a $250,000 fund-raising event on
the Upper East Side for the Democratic National Committee. Clinton was to return
to Chappaqua for the night before heading to Washington on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Programs for economic revival of urban and rural areas are drawing rare
bipartisan agreement between Clinton and House Republicans. Hastert, in a
statement from his office, said, ``I look forward to working with the president
on creating a bipartisan package that will address the needs of these
communities.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Removing tax and regulatory barriers that prevent private sector
investment in these areas is a hallmark of compassionate conservatism,'' Hastert
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said his initiatives were aimed at giving American companies the
same incentives to invest in U.S. communities as they have for investing in
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If we can't do this now, we will never do this,'' the president said. ``We
will never get around to doing this if we don't do it now. So, point number one,
we have a moral obligation to use our prosperity at this moment, especially, to
lift up the areas'' that have been left behind.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said he would resubmit his New Markets initiative to Congress,
seeking more than twice the funding he requested last year. He said the tax
credits would leverage $15 billion in investments.
</P>
<P>
	   The president said he also would propose expanding the New Markets agenda
with programs geared toward helping small and first-time entrepreneurs and
private investment companies, modeled after the Overseas Private Investment
Corp. that offers loan guarantees and risk insurance for foreign ventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
