<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal attends college dedication in his honor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Cardinal John O'Connor on Thursday attended the
dedication of a South Bronx campus of the College of New Rochelle that is being
named in his honor.
<P>
	   But while his spirits were up and his voice was strong, O'Connor sat
throughout the ceremony, walked with a cane and asked someone else to blow out
the candles on a cake in honor of his 80th birthday, which is Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   After the dedication of the newly renovated building in the Morrisania
section of the Bronx, O'Connor told reporters: "I came from a relatively poor
family of a bunch of kids in Philadelphia. I never dreamed that anything of this
sort would happen, that I would be given the honor of having my name attached to
any college or any university. I'm deeply grateful."
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier, Bishop Patrick Sheridan read a letter O'Connor wrote in which the
cardinal noted that he had "repeatedly refused to accept offers to name this or
that institution or building after me."
</P>
<P>
	   But he added: "There is no way I could resist such a kind offer. Education
has been one of my key concerns since coming to New York."
</P>
<P>
	   The cardinal had a brain tumor removed in August and has curtailed his
public schedule in recent months. Because cardinals lose their power to vote for
a new pope when they turn 80, it is likely that the Vatican will replace him in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
	   But College of New Rochelle President Stephen Sweeney asserted that the
dedication of the building in his name was not "connected with his health
challenges or his age, which the cardinal reminds us will surely be acknowledged
by the pope sooner rather than later. Rather ours is a genuine esteem and
admiration for the cardinal."
</P>
<P>
	   He said O'Connor provides "the example of a man of faith whose devotion to
the sacredness of life at all stages, to the poor, to racial harmony, to
religious tolerance and ecumenism and to justice is legendary."
</P>
<P>
	   The College of New Rochelle was founded in 1904 by the Ursuline Order of
nuns and was the first Catholic college for women in New York State. The campus
named for the cardinal is in a newly renovated building in Morrisania.
</P>
<P>
	   As the cardinal left, he was asked his thoughts on turning 80.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm getting old," he said with a laugh. As for his birthday wish, he said:
"To live among you New Yorkers for the next 100 years."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
