<HEADLINE> Gulf War Illness Czar Recommended  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen on Thursday said he is
recommending that Bernard Rostker, the point man on the Pentagon's long-running
investigation into Gulf War illnesses, be promoted to undersecretary of defense
for personnel.
</P>
<P>
	   Rostker would replace Rudy de Leon, whom Cohen has recommended for promotion
to deputy secretary of defense. The current deputy secretary, John Hamre,
announced Monday he is leaving the Pentagon on March 31 to become president of
the Center for Strategic and International Studies, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen said he recommended to President Clinton that Rostker take de Leon's
slot. Rostker has been undersecretary of the Army -- the No. 2 civilian post in
the Army -- since October 1998. Since November 1996 he has been a special
assistant to Hamre for Gulf War illnesses. He will continue with that
assignment.
</P>
