<DOCNO> APW20000113.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hang him, then smile for the camera  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Once upon a time in America, mobs dragged people out of
jails or off the streets and hanged them from the nearest tree - in some
particularly shocking cases, burned them alive. Then, often as not, members of
the mob lined up to be photographed with the deceased.
<P>
	   Dozens of these pictures- some of them turned into postcards - go on public
display Friday at a Manhattan gallery. "It's clear to me that this is a piece of
history that demands an audience," said Andrew Roth, co-owner of the Roth
Horowitz Gallery, which is presenting the sobering exhibit.
</P>
<P>
	   Visitors may browse before photos of corpses of young black men hanging from
branches, telephone poles and, in one case, a bridge. There is a shot of a man
being incinerated, and another of "the half-burned head of James" on a pole.
</P>
<P>
	   The gruesome material was gathered over the past decade by James Allen, a
Georgia-based dealer in antiques and memorabilia, and are now part of the
Allen-Littlefield Collection at Emory University in Atlanta. The New York
exhibit is timed to the release of a book, "Without Sanctuary: Lynching
Photography in America."
</P>
<P>
	   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People reported
3,436 people lynched between 1889 and 1922, and one photo in the collection is
dated 1960.
</P>
<P>
	   During the peak years, most victims were black men accused of offenses
ranging from murder and rape to not stepping off the sidewalk to let a white
person pass. But it was not a strictly Southern practice, and whether in
Gadsden, Alabama, Duluth, Minn., or the "Hanging Tree" in Helena, Mont., someone
with a camera always seemed to be present.
</P>
<P>
	   Picture after picture shows local citizens gathered around the dangling
bodies - some undoubtedly perpetrators of the crime, others simply bystanders
agape with curiosity.
</P>
<P>
	   The amateurish snapshots reveal a sameness about the southern racist mobs
and western posses carrying out vigilante justice - rawboned, angular-faced men
wearing hats. In some, small children watch the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the photos were turned into souvenir postcards, some colorized and
inscribed with such notations as "Down in Old Kentucky," or "Negro who shot J.H.
Rogers at Ten Mile, Miss., 5-21-19."
</P>
<P>
	   At least one series of photos, from a double lynching in Okeman, Okla., in
1911, was copyrighted by the photographer. Another picture, taken after dark in
1900, is stamped, "Flash light by Dabbs."
</P>
<P>
	   The postcards with one-cent stamps could be sent legally through the mail
until about 1908, when they were banned. "I bought this in Hopkinsville for 15
cents. It's not on sale openly (the law forbids it)," an anonymous correspondent
wrote on the back of one postcard.
</P>
<P>
	   Roth said the postcards are not only curious but "insightful into the nature
of the medium and how it was disseminated in the public domain."
</P>
<P>
	   Pictures aside, perhaps the exhibit's most chilling entry is a 1921 pamphlet
issued by the National Association of Colored People. It reproduced the Jan. 26
and 27 front pages of the Memphis (Tenn.) Press that provided an account of a
white mob seizing a black youth from a jail in Georgia and transporting him to
Arkansas, where he was burned at the stake.
</P>
<P>
	   The paper duly reported how the kidnappers stopped off in Memphis and were
seen "laughing and talking" in the lobby of the Hotel Peabody, and how police
formed up to guard the roads, but did nothing to interfere - more than a decade
before the FBI won the power to take charge of interstate crime.
</P>
<P>
	   "Questions," Roth said when asked what people should take away from the
exhibit. "Questions about our culture, our history, our times. People aren't
being lynched today, that we know about, but there certainly are references ...
that we hear on the news, morning noon and night, that connect back to this
history."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1720 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Port Area Evacuated  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Authorities ordered about 70 families to leave a
port area Thursday after detecting a dangerous mix of toxic chemicals spilled
when killer mudslides damaged cargo containers.
</P>
<P>
	   The containers were smashed and tossed around at the La Guaira port in the
Caribbean coastal state of Vargas, the worst-hit area in the Dec. 15 floods.
Some of the containers apparently had been used for years to illegally store
toxic wastes.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and Coast Guard officials who traveled
to Venezuela identified chemicals leaking from some containers and said they
pose a threat to public health, Venezuelan Environmental Minister Jesus Perez
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities said the chemicals could contaminate the ground and sea, emit
dangerous gases and cause an explosion. They said they would evacuate families
who live near the port and restrict access to the area.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is a cocktail of products that could cause serious damage,'' Perez
said. He said technicians assisted by U.N. environmental experts would be
assigned to clean up the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
	   In the days following the mudslides, thousands of hungry flood survivors
swarmed through the port to take food, bicycles and other items out of the
broken containers. Health officials have issued public warnings that any
survivors suffering from skin rashes, respiratory ailments or other health
problems should seek medical attention.
</P>
<P>
	   The flooding killed between 5,000 and 30,000 people, making it the worst
natural disaster in Venezuela this century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1725 </TRAILER>
