</P>
<P>
	   Wholesale Prices Up 3 Percent in '99
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prices at the wholesale level had their
biggest increase in nine years last year, rising 3 percent. But the
Labor Department said today that the rise was largely due to an
18.4 percent rebound in energy costs. Without the energy and food
sectors, wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent, well below the
1998 rise of 2.5 percent. Last month, the Producer Price Index was
up 0.3 percent, matching many analysts' expectations. Meanwhile,
the Commerce Department reported today that retail sales rose 1.2
percent last month, a stronger rise than the 0.9 percent many
analysts were expecting.
</P>
<P>
	   BP Amoco Pressures FTC on Arco
</P>
<P>
	   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- BP Amoco and Atlantic Richfield Co.
said today they were moving ahead with their merger plans, putting
pressure on the Federal Trade Commission to approve the deal or go
to court to block it. The companies said they were ready to trigger
a federal law that would force the FTC to decide within 20 days
whether the $26.8 billion deal should be allowed to proceed. At the
same time, they said they would continue their talks with the
agency. BP Amoco spokesman Thomas Koch said company officials would
meet with the agency tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
	   United Air Warns of Lower Earnings
</P>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- Shares of United Airlines' parent company fell
13.2 percent today after UAL, the world's largest airline, warned
that its earnings this year will be well below expectations because
of higher fuel and labor costs. UAL, issuing its revised outlook
before chairman and chief executive James Goodwin met with analysts
in New York, forecast earnings for the year at between $7 and $9 a
share. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had pegged
earnings for the year at $9.76 a share. UAL fell 9 7/8 to 64 7/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert To Hold Pfizer Talks
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Warner-Lambert Co. today reversed course and
said it would hold merger talks with Pfizer Inc. The decision came
two months after Warner-Lambert agreed to be acquired by American
Home Products. Either combination would create the world's largest
drugmaker. Investors had pressured Warner-Lambert executives to
re-evaluate its decision to unite with American Home Product,
especially in light of the rising value of Pfizer's offer. Pfizer's
offer is now worth about $77 billion. American Home's bid is valued
at about $57 billion. The difference between the offers widened in
recent weeks as Pfizer's stock rose and American Home's fell.
</P>
<P>
	   IBP Sued on Environmental Charges
</P>
<P>
	   OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The federal government has sued the
meatpacker IBP Inc., accusing it of polluting the air and water
surrounding its Dakota City plant. The suit, filed yesterday in
U.S. District Court on behalf of the Environmental Protection
Agency, seeks fines up to $241 million. IBP's six uncovered waste
lagoons at the site emitted largely uncontrolled amounts of
hydrogen sulfide into the air, and the company discharged ammonia
into the Missouri River in quantities toxic to aquatic life, the
Justice Department said in the complaint.
</P>
<P>
	   Fannie Mae Reports Record Profits
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fannie Mae said today that its profits rose to
a record $3.9 billion last year from $3.4 billion in 1998, boosted
by continued growth in its mortgage business and a reduction of
credit-related losses. The nation's largest mortgage-market company
said it earned $3.72 a share on a diluted basis in 1999, up 15.2
percent from $3.23 a year earlier. Chairman and CEO Franklin Raines
called 1999's financial results ``extraordinary'' and called the
outlook ``extremely bright' despite the possibility of further
interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
	   EPA Fines Pipeline Co. for Pollution
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Koch Industries was hit with $35 million in
fines and penalties by the government today as part of a settlement
over alleged contamination of lakes and streams in six states from
Missouri to Texas. The settlement with the Environmental Protection
Agency stems from allegations that the company had more than 300
oil spills from its pipelines and other oil operations and polluted
waterways in Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Alabama, Louisiana and
Missouri. The Wichita, Kan.-based company operates more than 35,000
miles of pipeline in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   Zions, First Security To Layoff 700
</P>
<P>
	   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Zions Bancorporation and First Security
Corp. plan to lay off more than 700 workers as a result of the
companies' merger. The companies want to reduce their combined
17,000-employee work force by about 10 percent and hoped to do it
primarily through attrition. A companywide hiring freeze in effect
since they announced their plans to merge in June helped reduce
employment by about 900 people, said Clark Hinckley, Zions' human
resources manager. He confirmed the number of planned layoffs
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
	   European Stock Prices Rise
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks rose today, but London shares were
slightly dampened by the Bank of England's interest rate increase,
which did nothing to alleviate global fears of inflation and
expectations for European rate rises this year. The Dow Jones Euro
Stoxx Index rose 3.61 points to 401.88. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index
of 606 shares in European companies was 1.91 points, or 0.6
percent, higher at 354.83, while the Dow Jones Stoxx 50 Index rose
30.9 points to 4494.3. In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100 Share
Index closed almost flat, down 1.3 points at 6531.5; Frankfurt's
Xetra DAX Index rose 43.17 points to 6955.98; the Paris CAC-40
Index gained 50.74 points to 5633.24; and Milan's MIBTEL Index was
208 points higher at 27,711.
</P>
