<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Versus Major Currencies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose broadly against major foreign currencies
Thursday on fresh evidence that the U.S. economy's growth is not accompanied by
a resurgence in inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   But trading was subdued in advance of a speech scheduled for Thursday night
by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
	   A one-quarter percentage point increase in British interest rates by the
Bank of England, which was widely expected, had little impact on currency
markets, said Ed Stapleton, chief foreign exchange dealer at Fortis (USA)
Financial Markets in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0254, down from $1.0311
Wednesday, and the British pound slipped to $1.6466 from $1.6477. The dollar
also was quoted at 106.13 Japanese yen, up from 105.98.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar picked up support with a Labor Department report Thursday morning
that inflation at the wholesale level was tame in December, with the exception
of the volatile food and energy components. A separate report showed continued
strength in consumer spending, the engine of the economy's long expansion.
</P>
<P>
	   It is widely expected that the Fed, which raised rates three times in 1999
to keep the economy from overheating, will increase rates again at a meeting
Feb. 1-2. But Thursday's report reduced the likelihood of an increase of more
than one-quarter percentage point, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, traders were reluctant to take major positions in advance of
Greenspan's remarks Thursday night to a meeting of economists in New York,
Stapleton said.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar also was quoted at 1.5720 Swiss francs, up from 1.5627 Wednesday,
and 1.4500 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4541.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Based on Thursday's
euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9073 German marks, up from 1.8969; 6.3968
French francs, up from 6.3614; and 1,888.21 Italian lire, up from 1,877.78.
</P>
</TEXT>
