<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crude at 2-Mo. High; Cocoa Climbs  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Crude oil futures rose to a two-month high Thursday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, extending a week-long rally that got its latest impetus
from comments by Saudi Arabia's oil minister.
</P>
<P>
	   In other markets, corn prices extended their gains to nearly 7 percent over
two days and cocoa climbed.
</P>
<P>
	   Oil prices had been sliding since hitting a nine-year high of $27.15 in
November. But a new push began this week as expectations rose of extended oil
price cuts among OPEC members.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, Ali al-Naimi, oil minister of the world's No. 1 producer, said
global inventories must be reduced still further and that the Organization of
the Petroleum Exporting Countries should extend the lowered production levels
that have chipped away at supplies. The production agreement is due to expire at
the end of March.
</P>
<P>
	   "When he starts to talk, the market really listens hard," said Tim Evans,
senior energy analyst for the Pegasus Econometrics Group in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Evans said the latest rally has served notice to anyone who doubted the
bullish market that they should "stand back and get out of the way" as prices
rise relentlessly upward.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of oil has more than doubled in the past year.
</P>
<P>
	   Crude for February delivery rose 41 cents to $26.69 a barrel. February
heating oil rose 0.81 cent to 69.28 cents a gallon; February gasoline was
unchanged at 71.27 cents a gallon; February natural gas rose 0.8 cent to $2.252
per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
	   In London, February Brent crude rose 17 cents to $24.98 a barrel on the
International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn prices powered over the $2.20-a-bushel mark on the Chicago Board of
Trade as traders shrugged off unexpectedly low weekly export sales reported by
the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
	   Other grains and soybeans also advanced sharply.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat prices reached their highest level in two months after forecasts
called for record warm temperatures this weekend in the U.S. southern and
central Plains. And soybeans also pushed to their highest price in eight weeks
on rumors, later said to be false, that Brazil had confirmed drought damage to
its crop.
</P>
<P>
	   March wheat rose 4 3/4 cents to $2.63 1/2 a bushel; March corn rose 5 1/4
cents to $2.20 3/4 a bushel; March oats rose 1 1/2 cents to $1.11 3/4 a bushel;
March soybeans rose 8 3/4 cents to $4.89 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Cocoa prices rose due in part to instability in Ivory Coast, the world's
leading producer. March cocoa settled up $17 at $871 per ton on New York's
Coffee, Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
