<HEADLINE> 'Puffy' Indicted on Weapons Charge  </HEADLINE>
    By SAMUEL MAULL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Grammy-winning rap mogul Sean "Puffy" Combs was indicted
Thursday on charges that he had two stolen guns in his sport utility vehicle as
he fled a nightclub shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   One gun was found by police in the vehicle, and the other was thrown out of
the vehicle, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   Two of Combs' associates were also named in the indictment: his rapping
protege, Jamal "Shyne" Barrow, on attempted murder charges, and bodyguard
Anthony Jones on a weapons charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs, 30, could get up to 15 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs has repeatedly proclaimed his innocence since his arrest after three
people were wounded Dec. 27 inside the crowded Club NY. He was taken into
custody, along with his girlfriend Jennifer Lopez, as they drove away from the
club after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said the vehicle carrying Combs and Ms. Lopez, the singer-actress who
starred in the films "Selena" and "Out of Sight," had run at least one red light
while fleeing the club. A driver and bodyguard were in the front; the couple
were in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs was charged with possession of a 9 mm pistol found in the front of the
car, and with possession of another stolen 9 mm that was thrown from the
vehicle, Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said.
</P>
<P>
	   Both guns had been fired, but the district attorney could not say where or
when the weapons had been fired.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs was charged with second-degree possession of a weapon, meaning he had
a loaded gun with intent to use it. He was also charged with third-degree, which
is simple possession of a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs, who earned an estimated $53 million through his rap empire in 1998,
has been free on $10,000 bail since his arrest. He is due back in court Feb. 14.
</P>
<P>
	   He scheduled a Thursday evening news conference to respond to the charges.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs' lawyer, Harvey Slovis, has said that the couple were fleeing the
nightclub in fear of their lives and that Combs did not own the weapon found in
the vehicle. Until Thursday, prosecutors had not accused Combs of having a gun
that was thrown from the car.
</P>
<P>
	   Combs was also arrested last April for allegedly beating a fellow music
executive, leaving the victim with a broken arm and jaw. Combs pleaded guilty to
harassment and was ordered to undergo counseling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
