<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First 21st Century Patent Awarded  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The first patent issued by the government in the new
century has gone to the inventor of a new type of athletic headgear, the
Commerce Department announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The department's Patent and Trademark Office awarded Patent No. 6,009,555,
the first one of the year 2000, to Leonard Siprut of San Diego, Calif., for a
combination sun visor-eye shield designed for use by ocean surfers, kayakers,
bikers and athletes in other active sports.
</P>
<P>
	   By contrast, officials said the first patent issued a century ago, in 1900,
was to Louis Allard of Utah for an early version of the washing machine.
</P>
<P>
	   Over 6 million patents have been issued since the government awarded the
first one in 1790, with 161,000 of those handed out in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
