<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DMV feverishly putting old test in, but it won't save much time  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - In an effort to attack chronically long lines,
workers this week retooled auto inspection stations across New Jersey to bring
back old auto emissions tailpipe tests.
<P>
	   But how much time will this move actually save motorists?
</P>
<P>
	   The old tests will be used when waiting times reach at least 45 minutes at
centralized inspection stations, according to an agreement reached last week by
the Whitman administration and federal environmental officials.
</P>
<P>
	   The plan began at several stations earlier this week and was expanded to all
DMV stations on Thursday. Division of Motor Vehicles spokesman Dana Sullivan
said four inspection stations switched to the old tailpipe test on Wednesday.
This option will continue through June 30.
</P>
<P>
	   But while the move was pitched last week as a big time-saver for motorists,
switching to the old test doesn't mean motorists will speed through the
inspection line.
</P>
<P>
	   That's because the new inspection tests, which were launched Dec. 13,
feature three parts: the enhanced emissions test, a brake test, and a suspension
test, which also tests for gas tank pressure. When waiting times exceed 45
minutes, the old tailpipe test will be substituted for the enhanced emissions
test. But Parsons Infrastructure and Technology, the private company that runs
the stations, will continue to administer the other two tests.
</P>
<P>
	   That means the time savings will be only about two to three minutes per car,
according to Division of Motor Vehicles estimates.
</P>
<P>
	   "Clearly, this option does not solve the line situation at any particular
station," said DMV director Richard Kamin. "It's an option that might help, but
is not going to solve the very severe problems Parsons is having with this
contract."
</P>
<P>
	   Carl Golden, spokesman for Parsons, said the modest per-car time-savings
will add up for motorists at the end of the line.
</P>
<P>
	   "The amount of time saved per car is not significant in itself, but if you
take it and multiply it across six lanes, it's going to cut down on the lines,"
Golden said.
</P>
<P>
	   Long lines for the new inspection tests have angered drivers and frustrated
the Whitman administration. The state has removed $369,000 from Parsons'
payments because of the waiting time, and the firm has promised to hire 300 more
workers to speed the process. This week, Parsons conceded computer glitches with
the brake tests have caused some cars to be flunked when their brakes were fine.
The company has vowed to clear up the problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. Christie Whitman has said she does not want to shut down any of the
safety aspects of the inspection process. Senate President Donald DiFrancesco
last week offered a bill to give Whitman several options to cut the lines,
including exempting cars five years old or newer from the emissions and safety
tests. However, Whitman may not need the Legislature to take such action.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal Environmental Protection Agency is allowing New Jersey to return
to the old tailpipe test when waiting times exceed 45 minutes as a stopgap
measure. The old test basically looks for carbon monoxide. The new test, a
treadmill-like device that attempts to simulate road conditions, also looks for
compounds that create asthma-causing smog.
</P>
<P>
	   Sullivan said four stations used the old tailpipe test on Wednesday, but he
didn't know how many switched on Thursday. He said overall, lines were shorter
on Thursday: only eight stations had waits exceeding 30 minutes at the peak
time.
</P>
<P>
	   "We won't know for sure how much an effect this will have, because we're
hoping that as operators become more and more experienced, that will save time
too," Sullivan said. "This is an emergency, interim measure. This was one of our
better days."
</P>
<P>
	   Sullivan said those at the end of long lines are still being offered the
option to return for an inspection at another time. The state offers a waiver of
up to 45 days to these motorists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1802 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latest city crackdown targets reckless drivers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Next week, police will start seizing the cars of
motorists who drive double the speed limit or commit other reckless driving
violations, Police Commissioner Howard Safir and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
announced Thursday.
<P>
	   This new crackdown on reckless driving - instituted because of an increase
in traffic-related fatalities - is similar to the NYPD's zero tolerance on
drunken driving, and has civil libertarians frustrated.
</P>
<P>
	   "You don't hang the person first and give them the trial later," said Norman
Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
	   It's also the latest in a long line of crackdowns Giuliani has enacted in
his time as mayor, and the NYPD has been christened to enforce. Several of those
initiatives, such as jaywalking and double parking, have been for the most part
ignored by New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
	   But the DWI crackdown has apparently worked, according to Safir. The goal of
this crackdown was to lower the DWI-related fatality rate. In 1999, there were
23 such fatalities in the city, compared with 31 in 1998, according to police
statistics.
</P>
<P>
	   And he thinks the same success can be achieved with the reckless driving
campaign. Including drunken driving fatalities, 416 people were killed in
traffic-related accidents in the city last year, compared with 367 in 1998,
police statistics show.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think there's a place that I've been where people are drinking
alcohol where I don't here someone mention the fact that they 'can't go drive my
car because the police are going to seize it,"' Safir said. "And that's the kind
of public awareness we want for reckless driving as well."
</P>
<P>
	   Under the new guidelines regarding reckless driving citations on city
highways, a motorist will be slapped with reckless driving, a misdemeanor
charge, when caught driving double the speed limit, Safir said. The driver will
also be charged with speeding.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, if a motorist is seen by an officer committing three hazardous driving
violations - such as following too closely, unsafe lane changing and driving in
unauthorized lanes - he or she will be slapped with reckless driving and other
traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
	   Now for the car seizure part. Just like the DWI crackdown, if you own the
car, it will be seized, and a person must be acquitted of the charges to get
their car back. However, if you were driving someone else's car, the car will be
given back to the rightful owner.
</P>
<P>
	   Siegel said it will be interesting to see if the reckless driving campaign
holds up in court. Currently, the DWI seizure program is under the scrutiny of
the New York Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think the city has the legal authority to do this," Siegel said.
"This is just another example of the increasingly authoritarian policies of
Giuliani's."
</P>
<P>
	   Siegel said in an article he wrote last year about the DWI seizure program,
he wondered how far the city would try to stretch its authority.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wondered in the article if they would start seizing cars from motorists
who were speeding," he said. "And here we are."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1802 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Air Warns of Lower Earnings  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) -- United Airlines, the world's largest airline, warned that
its earnings this year will be well below expectations because of higher fuel
and labor costs.
</P>
<P>
	   The news sent shares in UAL Corp., the carrier's parent company, plummeting
13 percent, or $9.87 1/2, to $64.87 1/2 in trading at 5:15 p.m. Thursday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   UAL, issuing its revised outlook before chairman and chief executive James
Goodwin met with analysts in New York, forecast earnings for the year at between
$7 and $9 a share. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had pegged
earnings for the year at $9.76 a share.
</P>
<P>
	   United said it anticipates a 2 percent to 4 percent increase in total
revenue, which will be outweighed by an expected 6 percent rise in costs.
</P>
<P>
	   It blamed the higher costs on fuel prices anticipated to average 25 percent
more than 1999 levels as well as contract negotiations with its pilots and
mechanics which are expected to result in higher wages
</P>
<P>
	   "If we were only dealing with the challenge of higher labor costs in 2000,
unit cost growth would actually be consistent with recent trends," Goodwin said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   United's costs this year also will be hit by investments in its Economy Plus
program, in which aircraft are being overhauled to provide more leg room for
full-fare passengers and the most frequent fliers.
</P>
<P>
	   The airline company expects the investments to ultimately pay off by drawing
more of the highest-paying passengers.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, UAL announced it is creating an e-commerce subsidiary enabling
it to better sell travel products over the Internet. The new company will be
charged with managing the company's partnerships and relationships with online
travel sites.
</P>
<P>
	   The subsidiary is to be set up in the second quarter of this year with
headquarters in the Chicago area, UAL said. It will be headed by Scott Praven,
currently United's vice president for revenue management.
</P>
<P>
	   UAL is due to report fourth-quarter 1999 earnings next Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1805 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Anti-Drug Messages Encouraged  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID BAUDER AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- The federal government used financial incentives to
get television networks to work anti-drug messages into the scripts of popular
TV shows, and would review scripts to determine whether the point was getting
across clearly.
</P>
<P>
	   The arrangement, first disclosed Wednesday by the online news service
Salon.com, raised questions about the independence of networks and their
willingness to let others influence what goes on the air.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the shows reviewed by the government were NBC's top-rated "ER," CBS's
"Chicago Hope" and "Cosby," ABC's "The Drew Carey Show" and "The Practice," and
Fox's "Beverly Hills 90210," according to Salon.com.
</P>
<P>
	   The complicated arrangement stemmed from Congress' 1997 approval of a
program to buy anti-drug ads on TV. Networks were asked to match each commercial
spot bought by the government with a free one. Since the program started,
however, commercial time has become more valuable with the rising demand for ads
by Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
	   The government has since agreed to give up some of its ad time -- as long as
the networks demonstrate that some of their programs convey anti-drug messages,
said Rich Hamilton, CEO of Zenith Media, the ad buying firm that helped develop
the idea as a go-between for the networks and the White House Office of National
Drug Control Policy.
</P>
<P>
	   This freed up advertising time that the networks could then sell to other
clients at steeper prices, Hamilton said. The White House drug office valued the
programming messages it had approved at $22 million.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm fairly amazed that there has been any concern expressed about this,"
Hamilton said. "It has been so above board and clearly voluntary on the part of
everyone involved."
</P>
<P>
	   Yet an expert on media ethics said it raises questions about the motives of
the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
	   "What it can do for the networks is make it seem that they are only going to
run those messages or shows that have prior government approval," said Aly
Colon, a professor at the Poynter Institute. "That may not be reality, but at
least it can become a perception."
</P>
<P>
	   Networks submitted scripts or tapes of completed shows for the government
drug office's review, said Alan Levitt, director of the national youth media
campaign at the White House drug office. At no time did the office suggest
changes or rewrite the scripts, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "All we said was, if you believe that a certain program that you intend to
broadcast delivers our message -- essentially that drugs can kill you -- submit
it to us for an evaluation and we may decide that we can credit you for a pro
bono match," Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
	   Salon.com, quoting an unidentified source, said that in an episode of the
WB's "Smart Guy" series, two substance-abusing teen-agers were originally
depicted as being popular, but the script was changed after government review to
show them as "losers" hidden away in a utility room taking drugs.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokesman for the WB had no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
	   In at least 24 instances over the past few years, networks or producers have
come to the federal drug office for advice in how to portray substance abuse
situations, Levitt said. This was independent of the program offering financial
credit, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   For example, producers and writers of "ER" have frequently contacted the
office. One recent storyline about a youth coming into the emergency room after
having abused alcohol was likely included after the office told producers that
alcohol is the most frequently abused drug among young people, said Donald
Vereen, deputy director of the White House drug policy office.
</P>
<P>
	   "We plead guilty to using every lawful means to saving the lives of
children," said another member of the drug office, Bob Weiner.
</P>
<P>
	   NBC has given scripts or completed shows to the drug office to review, but
has not accepted any financial credits for anti-drug messages, a network
representative said.
</P>
<P>
	   "NBC never ceded content control of any of our programs to the ONDCP or any
other department of the government," said Rosalyn Weinman, executive vice
president of broadcast content policy. "At no time did NBC turn over scripts for
approval by the ONDCP."
</P>
<P>
	   ABC spokeswoman Julie Hoover said the network submitted scripts to the drug
office, but received no financial credit because it had already used enough free
commercials. ABC does not plan to seek credit in the future, Hoover said.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked why ABC had submitted scripts, Hoover said: "Why not? We don't hate
the ONDCP. We approve of what they're doing."
</P>
<P>
	   Said Steve Dnistrian, executive vice president of the Partnership For a
Drug-Free America, which has created anti-drug commercials: "The government is
not rejecting scripts or controlling creative direction here. That's absurd. You
can't buy networks that cheap."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1806 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Leftist Promotes Economics  </HEADLINE>
   By VANIA GRANDI Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROME (AP) -- The leader of Italy's largest governing party warned Thursday
that his party would self-destruct if it failed to accept globalization and
fully embrace economic and social reforms.
</P>
<P>
	   Walter Veltroni of the Democratic Left implored some 3,000 delegates
gathered in an old Fiat car factory for a party convention to support more open
economic policies, such as privatization and flexible work contracts.
</P>
<P>
	   He also pushed for reforms in the country's pension and health care system,
which is among the most generous in Europe. The system is currently strained by
the imbalance between the growing number of retirees and shrinking number of
contributors. Italy is also plagued by an 11 percent jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
	   Veltroni's push for reforms is a clear sign of the party's transformation.
</P>
<P>
	   Once the largest Communist party in the West, the Democratic Left has shed
everything from its red hammer and sickle symbol to its Marxist policies.
</P>
<P>
	   Veltroni has tried to model the Democratic Left after the British Labor
Party, going so far as to adopt the English slogan ``I Care'' for the convention
and bringing in British rock star Sting for a live performance. The meetings,
which run through Sunday, kicked off to the beat of John Lennon's ``Imagine.''
</P>
<P>
	   The major force in Premier Massimo D'Alema's center-left coalition
government, the Democratic Left was expected to use the convention in part to
formulate government policy.
</P>
<P>
	   The gathering comes less than a month after D'Alema -- a former leader of
the Democratic Left -- briefly resigned under pressure from a disgruntled
centrist ally in his coalition. The premier came back four days later with a
reshuffled Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
	   The centrist and hardline leftist parties that the governing coalition is
courting to strengthen its position for upcoming regional elections said
Veltroni's speech did not entirely convince them. But they did not rule out a
future alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1807 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United Airline Stock Falls 13 Pct.  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVE CARPENTER AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
