<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warner-Lambert spurns American Home merger offer for Pfizer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Pfizer Inc. emerged Thursday as the likely winner in the
high stakes battle for rival drugmaker Warner-Lambert Co.
<P>
	   Two months after agreeing to merge with American Home Products Corp.,
Warner-Lambert executives bowed to investor pressure and said they would
negotiate a buyout from Pfizer instead.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer has been trying to break up the marriage of its two competitors since
the day they announced their stock swap deal on Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer's counter-offer for Warner-Lambert was higher from start and the gap
has widened because American Home's share price has steadily declined.
</P>
<P>
	   As of late Thursday, Pfizer's bid was worth $79.4 billion - about the same
as it was when the fight began - while American Home's original $70.5 billion
offer had fallen to $54.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert's decision leaves American Home Products facing its third
failed merger attempt in less than two years. American Home, maker of Robitussin
cough syrup and the best-selling estrogen replacement pill Premarin, is expected
to sweeten its takeover offer. But analysts have little doubt that a
Pfizer-Warner-Lambert marriage will be consummated.
</P>
<P>
	   Either suitor in the fight for Warner-Lambert would become the world's
largest drugmaker, and gain a significant edge in discovering new medicines and
selling existing ones. Pfizer makes the blockbuster impotence drug Viagra.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors have been urging Warner-Lambert executives to re-evaluate their
decision to unite with American Home, so Thursday's decision wasn't a big
surprise.
</P>
<P>
	   "This was inevitable," said Hemant Shah, a drug analyst in Warren, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   Wall Street applauded Warner-Lambert's move, sending its shares up $5.06 1/4
to $91.87 1/2 in late trading on the New York Stock Exchange. Pfizer rose $1.75
to $36.87 1/2 and American Home rose 43 3/4 cents to $42.62 1/2, also on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the price differential, Warner-Lambert has grown increasingly
concerned about American Home's legal liability associated with health problems
tied to the fen-phen diet drug cocktail, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
	   American Home thought it had put these concerns aside in September when it
negotiated a national legal settlement, but that deal is in danger of falling
through because many customers may reject it and file suits on their own.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement Thursday, Warner-Lambert's board said that "in light of
changing circumstances" it had concluded Pfizer's offer "is better financially
for Warner-Lambert shareholders than the proposed merger with American Home
Products."
</P>
<P>
	   Warner-Lambert, the fastest growing major drugmaker, is the world's
15th-largest prescription drug company. The Morris Plains N.J.-based company
makes the blockbuster cholesterol-lowering drug Lipitor, which it co-markets
with New York-based Pfizer, with estimated 1999 sale of $3.3 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer has been aggressively pursing a hostile takeover by seeking the
ouster of Warner-Lambert's board of directors. Pfizer also sued Warner-Lambert
for allegedly failing to properly consider its bid.
</P>
<P>
	   Up until Thursday, Warner-Lambert defended its original merger plan, saying
American Home had a superior research pipeline of new medicines.
</P>
<P>
	   As the fight has grown nastier, Warner-Lambert countersued Pfizer and has
even sought to terminate Pfizer's rights to co-market and share profits from
Lipitor. The first trial was scheduled to start Feb. 14.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sooner or later Warner had to address Pfizer's offer, and it was better to
do it across the table than in a courtroom," said Bob Kirby, an analyst with
Edward Jones.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the bickering, Kirby said Pfizer and Warner-Lambert officials should
be able to strike a deal soon. But he suspected that Warner Chairman Lodewijk
J.R. de Vink won't have a role at Pfizer.
</P>
<P>
	   Pfizer applauded Warner-Lambert's move.
</P>
<P>
	   "We look forward to an expeditious completion of the transaction combining
the two fastest-growing companies in our industry and creating the best
pharmaceutical company in the world," Pfizer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   Madison, N.J.-based American Home indicated it was not ready to give up the
fight.
</P>
<P>
	   "We continue to support the strategic merger of equals of Warner-Lambert and
American Home Products under our existing merger agreement, the terms of which
remain in full force and effect."
</P>
<P>
	   The American Home-Warner-Lambert deal requires that if either side walks
away from the deal it must pay a $1.8 billion breakup fee.
</P>
<P>
	   American Home's efforts to find a merger partner have been frustrated
repeatedly. In 1998, attempts to link with Monsanto Co. and SmithKline Beecham
PLC both failed.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said American Home has enough new drugs remain competitive in the
short term, but still needs to find a partner to keep up with the world's top
tier firms. A merger is unlikely until the company can satisfy Wall Street that
it has solved its diet drug liability problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-13-00 1807 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wholesale Level Inflation Up 3 Pct.  </HEADLINE>
    By JEANNINE AVERSA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A big jump in gasoline prices helped push inflation at
the wholesale level up 3 percent last year, the largest gain since 1990 when
Iraq invaded Kuwait and drove up energy costs.
</P>
<P>
	   Prices were tame otherwise.
</P>
<P>
	   The Labor Department's Producer Price Index, released Thursday, showed
inflation in most other areas was relatively well-behaved. A second government
report said consumer spending roared ahead, boosting retail sales 8.9 percent
last year, the fastest pace since 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   Excluding energy and food, wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent last year,
even better than a 2.5 percent increase in 1998 and evidence inflation remains
under control, economists said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We got kicked by energy prices last year but if you threw energy out it was
a good year. Inflation was contained," said Donald Ratajczak, director of
Georgia State University's economic forecasting project.
</P>
<P>
	   Energy prices, which fell steeply in 1998 as the Asian currency crisis
depressed global demand, rose 18.4 percent last year. Gasoline prices surged
76.4 percent, the biggest gain in more than 19 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Production limits by oil-producing nations and increased demand from
recovering economies in Asia accounted for the increase in energy costs last
year, economists said.
</P>
<P>
	   For December, the PPI, which measures inflation pressures before they reach
the consumer, was up 0.3 percent, reflecting sharp increases in gasoline and
other energy prices. Some economists believe energy costs will moderate this
year.
</P>
<P>
	   The 3 percent advance in last year's wholesale prices was the largest annual
gain since a 5.7 percent rise in 1990. In 1998, overall wholesale prices were
flat.
</P>
<P>
	   The government was reporting Friday on price pressures at the retail level
with the release of the Consumer Price Index. Analysts were expecting prices to
rise 0.3 percent in December and in the range of 2.8 percent for the year. In
1998, consumer prices rose 1.6 percent. But the "core" rate of inflation, which
excludes energy and food, was expected to be lower than 1998's core rate of 2.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, a burst of holiday shopping pushed retailers' sales up by a
bigger-than-expected 1.2 percent in December, capping a year where robust
consumer spending fueled economic growth.
</P>
<P>
	   "The consumer engine is still pulling the economic train and doing so very
strongly," said Tim O'Neill, chief economist for the Bank of Montreal and Harris
Bank.
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Reserve raised interest rates three times last year to slow the
economy and keep inflation from escalating. With projections for continuing
strong economic growth, most economists believe Fed policy-makers will bump up
interest rates again, probably by a quarter of a percentage point, when they
meet next on Feb. 1-2. The strong retail sales report would justify such a move,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
	   Financial markets ignored the strong retail sales report, focusing instead
on the market-friendly news of benign inflation. The Dow Jones industrial
average reached a new record, closing up 31.33 points at 11,582.43. The Nasdaq
composite index broke out of a two-day slump to finish up 107.19 at 3,957.21.
Bond prices rose as yields on the 30-year Treasury bonds dipped to 6.65 percent
from 6.71 percent late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   On the inflation front, energy prices rose 1.2 percent in December, led by a
8.5 percent jump in gasoline prices, the biggest gain since August.
</P>
<P>
	   Food costs rose 0.4 percent in December, pushing the total increase for 1999
to 0.9 percent, compared with a 0.1 percent gain for all of 1998. Sharp
increases in the prices of beef, pork, and vegetables in December offset
decreases in the prices of eggs, turkeys and fish.
</P>
<P>
	   Outside food and energy, wholesale prices rose a scant 0.1 percent in
December.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, the number of Americans filing new claims for unemployment
benefits was unchanged at 309,000 for the week that ended Saturday. But the
four-week moving average, which smoothes out week-to-week volatility, was
294,000, a level economists said indicates that employers continue to scramble
to find scarce workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1807 </TRAILER>
