<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schwab To Purchase U.S. Trust Corp.  </HEADLINE>
    By DUNSTAN PRIAL AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- While most large brokerage firms are reaching out to small,
individual investors, the Charles Schwab Corp., which has already captured that
market, reached out to wealthy investors Thursday through an agreement to buy
U.S. Trust Corp. for $2.94 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
	   In a move reminiscent of America Online's proposed acquisition earlier this
week of old line media company Time Warner, discount and online brokerage firm
Schwab -- founded just 25 years ago -- has acquired one of the nation's oldest
and most respected investment firms in U.S. Trust.
</P>
<P>
	   New York-based U.S. Trust has provided investment advice and private banking
services to some of America's wealthiest families since 1853.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors were enthusiastic about the deal, snatching up shares of U.S.
Trust and sending its stock price soaring $54.12 1/2, or by 69 percent, to $133.
Schwab shares rose $3.37 1/2, or by 9 percent, to $41 as of 5:15 p.m. EST on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   "Wealthy Americans have traditionally used a significant amount of
handholding when it came to their investments. But they, along with the rest of
the U.S. population, want to have more of a say in managing their financial
affairs. This combination allows them to do that," said Tim Butler, a research
analyst with Pacific Crest Securities in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
	   The move was designed to fill existing gaps in both Schwab's and U.S.
Trust's current array of services, company officials said during a news
conference in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwab, based in San Francisco, is the largest U.S. online brokerage and
biggest discount brokerage.
</P>
<P>
	   But it was unable to meet the needs of its wealthiest clients, said company
founder and co-chief executive Charles R. Schwab. "Our customers are saying they
need more wealth management," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Wealthy investors, meanwhile, have shown an increased desire to participate
in the online investing revolution sweeping Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies said there are more than 6 million U.S. households with a net
worth of over $1 million, and that the numbers of Americans with large
investment portfolios is expected to grow at a double-digit pace in the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
	   "The affluent market is the growth engine of investable assets in the U.S.,"
added Schwab president and co-CEO David Pottruck.
</P>
<P>
	   Millionaires currently comprise just 5 percent of Schwab's 6.4 million
customers, while U.S. Trust's core customers have more than $5 million each to
invest.
</P>
<P>
	   Pottruck said he decided to court U.S. Trust shortly after he became a U.S.
Trust customer in 1998. Noting the irony, Pottruck said Schwab "couldn't provide
my private banking services so I went to U.S. Trust."
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to such private banking services as checking accounts, credit
lines and mortgage loans, New York-based U.S. Trust also helps clients create
trust funds to assist in passing on their considerable wealth to the next
generation.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwab will now be able to offer those services through its U.S. Trust unit.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the agreement, U.S. Trust shareholders will receive 3.427 shares of
Schwab stock for each share of U.S. Trust stock, or $140.51 in stock for each
U.S. Trust share, based on Thursday's stock price.
</P>
<P>
	   Both companies will retain their separate brand identities.
</P>
<P>
	   The deal is subject to approval by the Federal Reserve Board and other
regulators and to a vote by U.S. Trust shareholders. The companies said they
expect to complete the sale by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1811 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
