<HEADLINE> GOP Leader Says New HMO Bill Coming  </HEADLINE>
   By KAREN GULLO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress will deliver a managed care bill to President
Clinton, including a limited right-to-sue option, by mid April, said Rep. Dick
Armey, R-Tex.
</P>
<P>
	   Returning to an issue that deeply divided House and Senate Republicans last
fall, Armey, House majority leader, said that he believes a patient protection
bill should allow lawsuits, but only in federal courts and only after a patient
goes through the health plan's review process.
</P>
<P>
	   That's similar to a plan that House Republican leaders rallied behind as
they tried to defeat a broader HMO bill that included an unfettered right to
sue.
</P>
<P>
	   But some House Republicans joined with Democrats to pass a stronger bill.
Senate Republicans stuck together and passed a bill without right-to-sue
provisions.
</P>
<P>
	   It's now up to a Senate-House conference committee to hammer out a
compromise bill. Speaking at a conference on uninsured Americans Thursday, Armey
said that he and House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., would urge the committee
to get to work so the bill can be sent to Clinton by Easter, which falls on
April 23.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We need to pull the conference together,'' said Armey.
</P>
<P>
	   He acknowledged that there may be a tough road ahead working out a
compromise with Senate Republicans who oppose giving patients a right to sue.
But Armey contended that greater public interest in reigning in HMOs has changed
the political landscape.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's a lot of change in public awareness,'' said Armey.
</P>
<P>
	   HMO reform is a a hot political issue and it's likely that Republicans want
to get the issue out of the way before the November election.
</P>
<P>
	   The House bill ``is a plan that we ought to be able to get to,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Texan also said that the bill Congress gives to Clinton will include
measures to make health coverage more affordable for millions of Americans,
including a new tax deduction for people who pay at least 50 percent of their
own health insurance premiums.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton administration is expected to include in its 2001 budget
proposal tax credits for people who purchase health insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
	   Armey said the White House should give people a 100 percent tax credit, not
a 25 percent subsidy, as Vice President Al Gore has proposed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What good is it to offer a subsidy on one-fourth of a person's costs, if
that person can't afford the three-fourths that isn't subsidized?'' said Armey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
