<HEADLINE> U.S. Asks for Peace Positions  </HEADLINE>
   By MARK LAVIE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The United States has asked Israel and the Palestinians to
draw up position papers explaining their stances on a peace treaty, a
Palestinian official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   A senior U.S. diplomat, Aaron Miller, met with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat in the West Bank city of Ramallah on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Palestinian official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Arafat
was asked to take the Palestinian paper with him to Washington, where he is to
meet President Clinton on Jan. 20 during U.S.-Syria negotiations.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel and the Palestinians began intensive negotiations toward a peace
treaty on Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
	   Arafat and Prime Minister Ehud Barak have set a target date of February for
reaching a framework agreement, including solutions in principle for touchy
issues such as Jewish settlements, Palestinian refugees and the future of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
	   Arafat asked the United States to play an active role in the talks, said
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
	   Adviser Tayyeb Abdel Rahim said Arafat would to go Washington ready to
explain the Palestinian positions. But, he added: ``Israel has to be equally
ready.''
</P>
<P>
	   Arafat told Miller -- a member of the State Department's Middle East
negotiating team -- that the Palestinians insist on implementation of U.N.
resolutions that call for Israel to withdraw from the West Bank and allow
refugees to return to their homes in Israel, Erekat said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Palestinian negotiator said Arafat also made clear that the Palestinians
insist on establishing a state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel hopes to keep parts of the West Bank where most Israeli settlers
live. It also opposes allowing large numbers of refugees to return, and claims
all of Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
	   No progress has been reported in the negotiations. Teams headed by Israeli
diplomat Oded Eran and Palestinian Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo have
been meeting once or twice a week to discuss the issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Both sides assume that major decisions are to be made by Barak and Arafat.
While in the United States last week for talks with Syria, Barak called Arafat
to reassure him that Israel-Syria negotiations would not overshadow talks with
the Palestinians, and that he would meet Arafat soon.
</P>
<P>
	   Arafat's spokesman, Nabil Abourdeneh, said the two leaders might meet in
Washington. Barak is to leave for the United States on Tuesday for another round
of talks with the Syrians.
</P>
<P>
	   On Jan. 20, the day Arafat is to meet Clinton, Israel is scheduled to turn
over another 6.1 percent of the West Bank to Palestinian civilian control, under
terms of an interim peace agreement signed last September in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the Palestinians complained Thursday that Israel is misrepresenting
the total size of the West Bank, allowing it to turn over less territory than it
should. In the past, Palestinian objections have delayed scheduled handovers of
territory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1828 </TRAILER>
