<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Ruling Party Wants Youth  </HEADLINE>
   By SHIHOKO GOTO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan has a long tradition of respecting the elderly, but
members of the ruling party say some of their legislators may be a tad too
senior for the country's good.
</P>
<P>
	   Liberal Democratic Party lawmakers have proposed an age limit of 80 for
representing the party in parliamentary elections, a party official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are certain experiences and wisdom that only come with age,'' said
Hiromitsu Nishiwaki, an official of the LDP's political reform committee. ``But
setting an age limit would give a clear message that the LDP is eager to
rejuvenate.''
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal supporters, who include former Foreign Minister Masahiko
Komura, hope to get it approved before the next general election, which must
take place before October.
</P>
<P>
	   But it is almost certain to face stiff opposition. Venerating the elderly is
a deeply entrenched value in Japan, and the country has a national holiday
honoring seniors.
</P>
<P>
	   Moreover, the plan would end the political careers of some of the LDP's most
prominent figures, including former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, 81, and
current Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, 80.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 500 seats in the lower house of Parliament, twelve are held by people
80 or older, and 59 are held by lawmakers over 73.
</P>
<P>
	   No date has been set for the party vote on the proposal.
</P>
<P>
	   The Japanese constitution sets a minimum age of 25 to run for parliament,
but there is no upper age limit.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In the private sector, most people have retired when they are past 70,''
said Nishiwaki. ``There is an increasing call from the public for politicians to
adhere to those standards too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1845 </TRAILER>
