<HEADLINE> Simon &AMP;Schuster Extend King Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Simon &AMP; Schuster has extended an unusual profit-sharing
deal with Stephen King, contracting for three more books from the bestselling
horror writer.
</P>
<P>
	   "This new agreement is a testimony to the strength and success of our
partnership," Simon &AMP; Schuster president and CEO Jack Romanos said Thursday. "We
look forward to being Stephen's publishing home for many years to come."
</P>
<P>
	   King left Viking/Penguin, his publisher for 20 years, in 1997. His initial
agreement with Simon &AMP; Schuster was reportedly for King and the company to
evenly split profits from his books, with the author receiving only "token"
advances and royalties.
</P>
<P>
	   In standard publishing practice, authors are paid a large advance against
sales of their book up front, and are paid royalties only when enough books have
been sold to earn back the company's advance.
</P>
<P>
	   Simon &AMP; Schuster, the publishing unit of Viacom Inc., did not disclose
financial terms of the extension. The company said it had published eight King
titles since the 1997 three-book agreement.
</P>
<P>
	   The extension covers three works of fiction, to be published in hardcover
under the Scribner imprint, by Pocket Books in paperback and by Simon &AMP; Schuster
Audio as audio books.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm delighted to know that my future with Scribner, Pocket Books and Simon
&AMP; Schuster Audio is secure," King said in the release.
</P>
<P>
	   The author of "Carrie," "The Shining," and "Misery," seriously injured when
he was struck by a van in Maine in June, has begun writing again.
</P>
<P>
	   Simon &AMP; Schuster plans to publish a non-fiction book by King, called "On
Writing," this year. The first novel scheduled to be published under the new
agreement is titled "From a Buick Eight." Simon &AMP; Schuster spokesman Adam
Rothberg said no publication date had been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
