<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends at New High of 11,582.43  </HEADLINE>
    By EILEEN GLANTON AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose Thursday after a report of relatively modest
inflation boosted the bond market and calmed jittery stock investors. Financial
shares led the Dow Jones industrials to a new closing record.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dow rose 31.33 to close at 11,582.43, just past its previous record of
11,572.20.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators also closed higher. The Nasdaq composite index
broke out of a two-day slump to finish up 107.19 at 3,957.21. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 rose 17.43 to 1,449.68.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose after the Labor Department said inflation remained largely under
control in 1999. The department's Producer Price Index, which measures inflation
pressures before they reach the consumer, shot up 3 percent in 1999, the biggest
increase in nine years.
</P>
<P>
	   But most of the increase came from the volatile energy sector. Excluding
energy, wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent last year. For December, the
index rose 0.3 percent, right on target with many analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   The reports boosted investors' confidence that inflation is not escalating
quickly enough to merit sharp interest-rate increases by the Federal Reserve.
Higher interest rates can hurt stocks by cutting into corporate profits as it
becomes more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   The Fed raised interest rates three times in 1999 in an effort to keep
inflation under control, and in recent sessions, stocks have been pressured by
fears that another series of rate hikes are ahead.
</P>
<P>
	   Thursday's report eased those fears, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Fed is not behind the curve on inflation," said David Orr, chief
economist at First Union Securities Inc. While most analysts remain convinced
that the Fed will raise rates by 25 basis points, or a quarter percentage point,
at its next meeting on Feb. 1 and 2, Thursday's report suggested the Fed won't
increase rates beyond that amount, Orr said.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond dipped to 6.65 percent from 6.71
percent late Wednesday, benefiting bank and brokerage stocks that often suffer
when rates are rising. J.P. Morgan rose 3 3/16 and Chase Manhattan rose 1 1/16
to 71 5/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Merger activity also enlivened the sector. U.S. Trust, an investment firm
that caters to wealthy clients, soared 54 1/8 to 133 after agreeing to be
acquired by online and discount broker Charles Schwab for $2.7 billion, or about
$129 per share.
</P>
<P>
	   "That deal has prompted many investors to look at this sector in a new light
and consider other possible combinations," said Ned Riley, chief investment
strategist at State Street Global Advisors in Boston.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest development in the consolidating drug industry also sparked
buying. Warner-Lambert said it would hold merger talks with hostile suitor
Pfizer, abandoning its November decision to be acquired by American Home
Products.
</P>
<P>
	   Shares of all three companies rose. Warner-Lambert gained 5 1/16 to 91 7/8,
Pfizer rose 1 11/16 to 36 13/16 and American Home Products rose 7/16 to 42 5/8.
</P>
<P>
	   Technology stocks reversed two days of steep losses. Apple Computer rose 9
9/16 to 96 3/4 after Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on the stock
to "outperform" from "neutral." Analyst Gillian Munson applauded the company's
strong product pipeline and said Apple shares should reach 120 in a year.
</P>
<P>
	   "Despite some weakness so far this year, there is still a strong conviction
that the money to be made in this market is in technology stocks," Riley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Microsoft depressed the Dow for much of the session before turning higher in
advance of a late afternoon press conference. At the conference, founder and
chairman Bill Gates announced that company president, Steve Ballmer, will take
over the chief executive officer's slot.
</P>
<P>
	   Gates, who is stepping aside as chief executive, will remain chairman and
will also take over the newly created position of "chief software architect."
</P>
<P>
	   In extended-hours trading, Microsoft shares edged down to 107 3/4 from 107
13/16 at the 4 p.m. close.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was fairly volatile in advance of Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's
evening speech on technology and the economy in a speech before the Economic
Club of New York. Greenspan has occasionally used his public speeches as an
occasion to telegraph the Fed's sentiment about the economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Traders were also awaiting the government's Friday report on price pressures
at the retail level. Analysts expect the Consumer Price Index to have risen 0.3
percent in December.
</P>
<P>
	   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 1.02 billion shares, compared with 968.78
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 11.15 to 501.19.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.8 percent, Germany's Xetra DAX
index rose 0.6 percent and France's CAC-40 was up 0.9 percent. Britain's FT-SE
100 fell 0.02 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
