<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise, Breaking 3-Day Slide  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Government bond prices rose Thursday, breaking a three-day
losing streak, as the latest economic data showed inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year bond rose 11/16 point, or $6.87 1/2 per $1,000 in
face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.65
percent from the 2 1/2-year high of 6.71 percent late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Labor Department's Producer Price Index, released Thursday, showed
inflation in most areas of the economy was tame. Excluding energy and food,
wholesale prices rose just 0.9 percent last year, even better than a 2.5 percent
increase in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   A second government report said consumer spending roared ahead, boosting
retail sales 8.9 percent last year, the fastest pace since 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   With inflation under control it is less likely the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates sharply when it meets next month. While a rate increase
still is widely expected, analysts said chances have been reduced for a big
increase at the Feb. 1-2 meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   Rising interest rates hurt bonds, which pay a fixed rate of return.
</P>
<P>
	   In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities rose 5/32
point to 7/32 point and intermediate maturities rose 5/16 point to 15/32 point,
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.39 percent as the discount fell
0.04 percentage point from Wednesday to 5.24 percent. Six-month yields were 5.67
percent, as the discount fell 0.02 percentage point from Wednesday to 5.43
percent. One-year yields were 6.07 percent as the discount fell 0.03 percentage
point to 5.73 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was
5.62 1/2 percent, up 5.50 percent late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer said the new contract for its index
of 40 actively traded municipal bonds rose 1/16 to 91 1/2. The average yield to
maturity remained unchanged at 6.29 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1851 </TRAILER>
