<HEADLINE> Bush: Use Money for Tax Cuts  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. (AP) -- Sharpening their disagreement over tax cuts, George
W. Bush suggested Thursday that John McCain's proposal would leave too much
money for Congress to spend on ``bigger government,'' and McCain countered that
the Republican presidential front-runner's plan would lead to higher payroll
taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I must confess I am skeptical of appropriators,'' Bush said, referring to
members of the House and Senate committees that write multibillion-dollar
spending bills annually.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Somehow I have trouble believing that they're going to necessarily spend
it on debt reduction,'' the Texas governor said of the surplus funds that would
be left after McCain's tax cut took effect. ``I worry they may spend it on
bigger government.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's tax cut, $483 billion over five years, would leave the Social
Security surplus alone, but spend from non-Social Security surplus funds.
McCain, in a written statement, said that wasn't enough, that a larger amount of
non-Social Security surplus funds must be set aside to make sure the retirement
program is protected.
</P>
<P>
	   By not shoring up the Social Security system now with surplus funds we are,
by fiat, agreeing to raise payroll taxes in the future,'' added McCain, whose
own plan is roughly half the size of Bush's. I have called this kind of
economics ``fiscally irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was defending his plan in a new 30-second ad beginning Thursday night
in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   The two men never crossed paths during the day as they made their campaign
rounds a little more than two weeks in advance of the nation's first
presidential primary, set for Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   But their cross-state sparring underscored the extent to which the campaign
is settling into a disagreement over tax cuts, an issue that has divided
Republicans for the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
	   Two new public opinion polls released during the day pointed to a close race
in New Hampshire between the two Sun Belt political figures, but disagreed on
which man held the lead. One survey said it was Bush, the Texas governor who is
the national front-runner by far. Then other said it was McCain, running an
insurgent's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush did not mention that Republicans hold a majority in Congress, and he
made no other comments during the day that implied criticism of the
congressional wing of his party.
</P>
<P>
	   He made his remarks midway through a full day of campaigning that took him
from a high tech factory in Laconia to a lunchtime speech in this coastal city
to a town hall meeting in Londonderry before flying off to Iowa, which holds
caucuses eight days before New Hampshire votes.
</P>
<P>
	   The weather turned wintry, the first time the Texan had witnessed it in his
New Hampshire campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our first snowstorm press conference,'' aide Karen Hughes said
enthusiastically as Bush made his rounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush is campaigning as the outsider in the race, and he told reporters
during the day one of the key issues will be ``executive experience'' versus
``Washington legislative experience,'' an obvious reference to McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the Republican establishment's embrace was evident during
the day. Judd Gregg, who sits on the Senate Appropriations Committee, and Rep.
Charles Bass spent part of the day with Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has repeatedly accused Bush of advocating a tax cut that is too large
and risks harm to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   In remarks before a Rotary Club and afterward to reporters, the front-runner
seemed eager to keep the argument alive.
</P>
<P>
	   He lumped McCain and Vice President Al Gore together as the only ``two
voices'' in the campaign to say his own tax cut was too bold.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, McCain accuses Bush of providing overly generous relief
for the wealthy, echoing criticisms that Democrats frequently level at GOP tax
plans.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor took that issue head-on at several points during the day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's fair to cut the taxes on everybody if you're going to cut taxes at
all,'' he said to the Rotarians. At a news conference afterward, he re-enforced
his plan to cut the top tax rate.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said his plan would stimulate the economy as well as return money to
the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the money lies around the halls of Washington it's going to be spent,''
he said at one point. ``Appropriators appropriate,'' he said at another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
