<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Wrong Mountain' Isn't for Broadway  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    An AP Entertainment Review
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- "Wrong Mountain"? Wrong venue is more like it.
</P>
<P>
	   Broadway would seem to be the most unlikely place for David Hirson's
ambitious and unwieldy screech of a play which opened Thursday at the Eugene
O'Neill Theater.
</P>
<P>
	   It's a shrill, rarefied piece of theater, filled with a lot of arty
references to everybody from Strindberg to Sondheim, from Auden to Olivier, that
seem designed to showcase the playwright's encyclopedic knowledge rather than
his grasp of plot or characters. Don't look for it to last long on a street
where the happily middle brow beats out the querulously quirky every time.
</P>
<P>
	   The "Mountain" story: Henry Dennett is a minor poet facing late middle age
and the prospect of a less-than-fabulous legacy. He is a scholarly curmudgeon,
jealous of his ex-wife's new boyfriend, a hit-producing Broadway playwright, no
less.
</P>
<P>
	   The man also is experiencing writer's block, a condition that is symbolized
by a 40-pound worm that has found its way into his intestinal tract. And, yes,
the worm makes an appearance. No wonder Dennett is so disagreeable.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, he is disdainful of anything that smacks of the theatrical. "A
Biblia pauperum -- a Bible in pictures for the benefit of the illiterate" is
what the poet calls theater.
</P>
<P>
	   As a lark, Dennett says he can write a play -- and does. To his horror, the
work gains him an audience his poems never did. The man sneers and screams his
way to success.
</P>
<P>
	   Ron Rifkin gets quite a workout as the dyspeptic scribe, making himself as
unpleasant as possible, not only to the other people on stage, but to the
audience as well.
</P>
<P>
	   Along the way there are moments of giggly fun, most of them provided by a
hammy director portrayed by the wonderful Daniel Davis. He has the plummiest
British accent this side of Vincent Price.
</P>
<P>
	   This director runs a playwrights festival where Dennett's play is in
competition with two other works. One is an imagined conversation between famed
soprano Nellie Melba and first lady Eleanor Roosevelt called "Nellie and Ellie";
the other -- "Cerro Torre" -- tests the boundaries between truth and illusion.
It is written by an idealistic young playwright whose combative conversations
with the cantankerous Dennett provide the play's best moments.
</P>
<P>
	   "An artist is an artist regardless of the form," says the aspiring writer,
played with earnest charm by Daniel Jenkins. "Talent doesn't just come and go
depending on circumstances."
</P>
<P>
	   One suspects the play has undergone major condensation since its debut last
October in San Francisco. Most of the large cast has little to do -- except
complain about the poet.
</P>
<P>
	   Beth Dixon, as the former spouse, and Michael Winters, her new fling, serve
mainly as targets for Dennett's sniping. So do Ilana Levine and Bruce Norris, as
the man's unpleasant children. "Casualties of a failing university system," he
calls his petulant offspring.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the loud protests of its contrary main character, the comedy, in the
end, actually celebrates the middle-class business known as Broadway. By then,
the poet is wondering if he has been climbing the wrong mountain all along,
writing verse when he should have been writing plays. He even begins to like
theater.
</P>
<P>
	   The evening moves in fits and starts. Director Richard Jones can't seem to
sustain a forward momentum. Designer Giles Cadle's fanciful settings are at
least theatrical. They range from a toy train that trundles across the stage to
a campy giant statue of Lithia the corn goddess to a backdrop of jagged peaks
that give the play its title.
</P>
<P>
	   Hirson is the author of "La Bete," one of Broadway's more famous -- and
expensive -- flop plays. Set in 17th century France and written in rhymed
couplets, the elaborate comedy dared the audience to think while they were being
entertained. "Wrong Mountain" has the same lofty ambitions, but its message is
even more muddled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 1927 </TRAILER>
