<HEADLINE> Spanish Police Arrest Oxford Rowers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Spanish police arrested 24 rowers from England's Oxford
University on Thursday following a disturbance at a restaurant where they ate
the night before.
</P>
<P>
	   The rowers -- 23 men between the ages of 19 and 27 and a 24-year-old woman
-- were arrested shortly after midnight in the town of Amposta in northeastern
Spain, police said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The group became rowdy and caused about $625 worth of damage at a pizzeria
where they were having a dinner party, police said. Out on the street, the
rowers allegedly continued to cause disturbances and damage to cars and shops.
</P>
<P>
	   After spending the night in jail and appearing before a judge Thursday they
were all released without charge. But they will have to pay for the damage at
the restaurant plus a fine, Spanish news agencies said.
</P>
<P>
	   The rowers belonged to the Oxford team and were in Amposta to train in the
nearby Ebro River. Twenty are British. The other four are from the United
States, Canada, New Zealand and India.
</P>
</TEXT>
