<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Politics 2000  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Convinced that this year's rush to earlier
presidential primaries is unhealthy, national Republicans laid out options
Thursday for averting such ``front-loading'' in 2004.
</P>
<P>
	   A preliminary report released by a Republican National Committee panel
studying the issue listed several alternatives to the current system, but issued
no recommendations.
</P>
<P>
	   As it stands now, the Democratic Party allows only Iowa and New Hampshire to
hold caucuses or primaries before March 7. The RNC does not set such limits.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the options in the report are:
</P>
<P>
	   --Rotating regional system: States would be grouped by region, with each
group taking turns holding primaries first. Iowa and New Hampshire would retain
their earliest-in-the-nation status.
</P>
<P>
	   --Population-based system: States would be split into five groups based on
size. The 10 smallest states would hold their primaries first, and the 10
biggest last.
</P>
<P>
	   --Pre-primary convention: Party leaders would select candidates eligible to
run at a gathering before any primaries or caucuses. States would be barred from
holding such votes for at least one month, then would conduct them as they do
now.
</P>
<P>
	   --One-day primary: Arrange for all states to select their delegates on the
same day.
</P>
<P>
	   --Caucuses and conventions: Require all states to hold caucuses and
conventions instead of primaries.
</P>
<P>
	   --Incentives: Increase the rewards to states that hold primaries later.
</P>
<P>
	   The RNC intends to issue a final report before its summer meeting and its
national convention so it can change the GOP's rules, if necessary, then.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- Two New Hampshire newspapers have endorsed Texas
Gov. George W. Bush in the race for the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Foster's Daily Democrat in Dover and The Citizen of Laconia, which are owned
by the same company, said Bush has the ``right leadership for a new century.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``George W. Bush has the qualities we believe the American people are
looking for in a president,'' the newspapers said. ``The ideals of the founding
fathers are what George W. Bush has brought to public service and what he offers
to restore to our public institutions.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush issued a statement saying he was honored by the endorsements.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   CINCINNATI (AP) -- E.W. Scripps Co. television stations will give airtime to
selected political candidates this year, the company announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Scripps' nine network-affiliated TV stations will provide five minutes of
free airtime to candidates nightly between 5 p.m. and 11:35 p.m. in the 30 days
preceding both primary and general elections, the Cincinnati-based company said.
</P>
<P>
	   Each station will decide which candidates and races to give the airtime,
which may be used for debates, interviews or issue statements during local
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
	   Scripps is responding to a recommendation by the President's Advisory
Committee on the Public Interest Obligations of Digital Television Broadcasters,
said Jim Hart, the company's senior vice president of broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe our stations play an important role in encouraging public
discourse, providing a framework for open discussion and affording citizens the
best opportunity to make informed choices,'' Hart said.
</P>
<P>
	   Participating will be Scripps' three NBC affiliates -- WPTV, West Palm
Beach, Fla.; KSHB, Kansas City, Mo.; and KJRH, Tulsa, Okla.; -- and its six ABC
affiliates, WXYZ, Detroit; WCPO, Cincinnati; WEWS, Cleveland; WFTS, Tampa, Fla.;
WMAR, Baltimore; and KNXV, Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Reform Party presidential candidate Pat Buchanan toured an
efficient but money-losing steel mill Thursday and warned that cheap imports
were ruining the U.S. steel industry.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This was awesome,'' Buchanan said after a 45-minute tour of LTV Steel
Cleveland Works, where 4,300 workers make flat-rolled sheets of steel for use in
cars, appliances and electrical equipment. ``It was enormously impressive.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said new equipment installed at the plant in the past 15 years had made
it one of the most efficient in the world. He asked why the parent company, LTV
Corp., had not reported a profit since 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a very simple question and a simple answer. It's because of
imports,'' Buchanan said. ``This is happening even though we've got the most
efficient steel industry in the world.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- The Iowa Democratic Party announced plans Thursday
to post minute-by-minute results from Iowa's first-in-the-nation presidential
caucuses on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   The party is teaming up with Voter.com., a Web site that provides
information on parties, issues, races, candidates, events and results, in the
first test of strength between Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
	   The site at www.voter.com/iowa will continuously update results in all 99
counties and 2,131 precincts, Iowa Democratic Party Chairman Rob Tully said.
</P>
<P>
	   On caucus night, Jan. 24, as results from each precinct are telephoned into
the Democrats' tabulation center in Des Moines, they will be posted on the
Internet, said Voter.com spokesman Douglas Herman.
</P>
<P>
	   The party also will use safeguards to ensure an accurate and fraud-free
count.
</P>
<P>
	   Caucus result forms also will be mailed separately to the state Democratic
Party, with an audit of the final results at a later date.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Associated Press writers Thomas J. Sheeran, Melanie S. Welte and Scott
Lindlaw contributed to this report.
</P>
