<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Says Budget Surpluses Growing  </HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FRAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an early estimate of how the budget picture is
continuing to improve, the chairman of the Senate Budget Committee produced
numbers Thursday showing that federal surplus projections are looking as good as
ever.
</P>
<P>
	   In a letter, Senate Budget Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said
his staff believes the fiscal 2000 surplus will be $10 billion to $20 billion.
Fiscal 2000 runs through Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
	   The 2001 surplus should reach $10 billion to $40 billion, he wrote. Both
sets of figures exclude Social Security money, which Republicans have pledged
not to touch.
</P>
<P>
	   Though the numbers are roughly what was projected last summer, the new
figures take into account billions in extra spending and tax cuts Congress and
President Clinton enacted last fall. When that additional spending was approved,
some Democrats suggested that it might prevent Republicans from meeting their
pledge of protecting Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
	   ``At this time it seems certain that Republicans made good on our commitment
to protect the Social Security surplus,'' Domenici wrote in a letter to Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
	   Domenici said his staff used ``essentially the same numbers as the
Congressional Budget Office,'' which will issue Congress' official budget
projections in two weeks. He said his figures are ``likely to be confirmed'' by
CBO.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, for the decade ending 2010, Domenici estimates the non-Social
Security surplus will total $2 trillion, about double what was projected last
year, said budget committee aides.
</P>
<P>
	   That figure, however, assumes that limits legally imposed on about one-third
of the $1.7 trillion budget will be obeyed. Those limits have been ignored the
last two years and are certain to be breached again by tens of billions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   Both sides consider the non-Social Security portion of the budget fair game
for use for tax cuts or higher spending.
</P>
<P>
	   The White House plans to update its own surplus projections on Feb. 7, when
Clinton introduces his fiscal 2001 budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
