<HEADLINE> DeLorean Ordered Off Estate by Mar.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A bankruptcy judge has awarded John DeLorean's estate
to a golf course developer and ordered the erstwhile automaker off the property
by the end of March.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Garrett Brown on Wednesday approved the sale of
DeLorean's 434-acre Bedminster, N.J., property to National Fairways Inc. for
$15.25 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The sale ended DeLorean's five-year battle to keep his property despite
financial and legal ruin. The proceeds from the sale are earmarked for
DeLorean's creditors, but the price falls about $15 million short of paying off
DeLorean's total outstanding debt.
</P>
<P>
	   DeLorean, 75, declined to comment on the decision.
</P>
<P>
	   His largest creditor, Merrill Lynch Credit Corp., won title to the Georgian
mansion and the rest of the estate in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   DeLorean had vowed to pull himself out of his financial troubles when he
filed his bankruptcy petition in September. He announced that he himself would
develop a golf resort and equestrian center on his property, which he estimated
to be worth $27 million.
</P>
<P>
	   He had even intended to build a new line of gull-winged sports cars powered
by ceramic engines, like the 8,500 stainless steel DeLorean Motor Co. cars built
in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
	   That company, based in Northern Ireland, collapsed 18 years ago amid charges
of money laundering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
