<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitive Arrested in Gotti Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- A fugitive associate of mob boss John Gotti who allegedly
paid a juror $60,000 to arrange a 1992 acquittal for the ``Teflon Don'' is in
federal custody in Florida, authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bosko Radonjich was arrested Jan. 2 at Miami International Airport.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors plan to arraign Radonjich, 56, in federal court in Brooklyn,
where he was indicted in 1992 on jury tampering charges, said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Paul Schoeman. No date for the arraignment was set.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities refused to speculate on Radonjich's whereabouts for the past
eight years.
</P>
<P>
	   He was apparently in Miami on a brief stopover for an international flight.
Because he was traveling under his own name, a background check turned up the
warrant for his arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   Gotti was known as the ``Teflon Don'' for beating conviction in three trials
as the Gambino boss. He was imprisoned for life in 1992 after being convicted in
a murder racketeering case which relied on the testimony of a mob turncoat.
</P>
</TEXT>
