<HEADLINE> Experts Discuss Salton Sea's Future  </HEADLINE>
   By DARA AKIKO WILLIAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DESERT HOT SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Federal officials warned Thursday that
the Salton Sea's rich ecosystem will die unless 9 million tons of salt is pulled
from the lake each year.
</P>
<P>
	   The process could cost up to $9.5 million annually for at least 30 years.
</P>
<P>
	   David Hayes, Interior Department deputy secretary, said reducing the
salinity is part of an overall plan to restore and develop California's biggest
lake, which sustains one of the nation's most productive fisheries and is an
important stop for migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We need to save the Salton Sea and we need to do it now,'' said Hayes, who
spoke during a Salton Sea Symposium. ``To let the sea die, in our view, is not
an option.''
</P>
<P>
	   A draft environmental impact report outlining the best methods of restoring
the sea's health was discussed by politicians, environmentalists and scientists.
The document will be used by Hayes and others when seeking restoration funds
from Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Salton Sea formed in 1905 after the Colorado River burst through a canal
and flooded an area 120 miles northeast of San Diego. The lake, below sea level,
sucked salt out of the desert over the years, making it 25 percent saltier than
the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
	   The Interior Department, the Bureau of Reclamation and the Salton Sea
Authority spent 18 months preparing the draft as other experts developed
scientific studies. The results of those studies will be presented Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The draft offers five alternatives, including damming sections of the lake
to create evaporation ponds, building evaporation towers that would pull water
from the sea and spray mist into collection basins, or a combination of ponds
and towers.
</P>
<P>
	   The annual costs range from $1.6 million for the ponds to $9.5 million for
the towers. A combination of both would cost $7.1 million.
</P>
<P>
	   The goal is to reduce the sea's salinity to the same level as the Pacific
Ocean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
