<HEADLINE> Dad Sentenced in Starvation Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A father convicted of starving to death his 2-year-old son
because ``God doesn't like babies who are fat'' was sentenced Thursday to 25
years to life in prison, the maximum sentence.
</P>
<P>
	   David Mayer, 32, was convicted in December of first-degree murder. Jurors
could not reach a unanimous decision on a special circumstance charge of
torture, which would have qualified Mayer for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   The boy, Zechariah, weighed only 19 pounds when he died in January 1998 in a
home where the refrigerator was full of food, prosecutors said. He was a month
shy of this third birthday.
</P>
<P>
	   Superior Court Judge Laura Hammes said Mayer drank alcohol, smoked
marijuana, watched his big screen television and left the house when he wanted
while his son starved to death.
</P>
<P>
	   Mayer ``related everything back to God,'' Hammes said. ``God conveniently
gave him an excuse to provide for himself and his selfish wants while permitting
him to kill the child intentionally.''
</P>
<P>
	   Defense attorney Jesse Gilbert argued that Mayer was delusional, believed
that God controlled his life and that God would take care of everything.
</P>
<P>
	   A social worker told authorities that prior to Zachariah's death, Mayer said
that ``God doesn't like babies who are fat.''
</P>
<P>
	   The boy's mother, Jennifer Mayer, 23, was convicted in October of
second-degree murder. Her sentencing is set for Jan. 27. She faces 15 years to
life in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
