<HEADLINE> France Restores Power After Storms  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France's national electric company has restored power to all
the homes that lost it during violent storms that swept through France at
Christmastime, the EDF power company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   At the worst point of the electricity crisis, about 3.4 million homes -- 10
percent of EDF's clients -- had no power, company chairman Francois Roussely
said.
</P>
<P>
	   But telephone lines were still a problem. About 5,000 subscribers were still
without telephone connections, though national company France Telecom said the
problem should be resolved by the middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
	   After the two violent windstorms whipped through France, the total cost of
repairs to the electricity network alone came to $2.7 billion, with about a
third of that going towards emergency repairs, the government has said.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wednesday, French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin unveiled an aid package
worth $630 million aimed at helping France get back on its feet after the
devastating weather.
</P>
<P>
	   Ninety people died in storm-related accidents. Many people are still carting
away uprooted trees and repairing battered roofs.
</P>
</TEXT>
