<DOCNO> APW20000113.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't. Unveils Debt Buyback Plan  </HEADLINE>
   By MARTIN CRUTSINGER AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, seeking to operate in the new
world of budget surpluses, adopted rules Thursday that will allow the government
to buy back up to $30 billion of the national debt this year, something that
hasn't happened for at least a century.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're going to get this country out of debt,'' President Clinton told a
Democratic fund-raising audience in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, in making the announcement, called the
debt buyback program ``an important new tool'' for the government to use in
managing the $5.76 trillion national debt.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Reducing the supply of Treasury debt held by the public brings enormous
benefits to our economy,'' Summers said. ``It means that there will be less
pressure on interest rates than there would otherwise have been and therefore
lower borrowing costs for businesses and lower interest payments for American
families.''
</P>
<P>
	   The administration, which first proposed the idea of debt buybacks last
August, has sought to portray its proposal as the responsible way to utilize the
government's burgeoning surpluses, the product of the current economic boom, in
contrast to Republican calls for large tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton said the debt buyback plan was a ``dramatic reminder'' of
how much the government's economic fortunes have improved after decades of
rising budget deficits and would allow the government to ``refinance old debt
and pay it down on the best terms possible.''
</P>
<P>
	   Under the rules the government adopted, Treasury will conduct what is known
as a ``reverse auction,'' in which the government will offer cash to bond
holders who indicate their willingness to sell government bonds back to the
government.
</P>
<P>
	   The price will be set in a bidding process designed to make sure the
government pays prevailing market rates for the bonds it buys.
</P>
<P>
	   Treasury Under Secretary Gary Gensler, who oversees the debt operations,
said Treasury records show it has been at least a century since the federal
government has offered cash to buy securities that have not yet matured.
</P>
<P>
	   Gensler said the Treasury conducted limited swap operations in the 1960s and
as late as 1972, swapping new bonds for older bonds held by the public in an
effort to reorganize the types of bonds outstanding.
</P>
<P>
	   Summers said the debt buyback program would be launched in the coming weeks
with several operations conducted in the next 12 months, totaling up to $30
billion. Officials said the exact timing of the program and the size of each
buyback program had yet to be determined.
</P>
<P>
	   The national debt now stands at $5.76 trillion, with the amount of that debt
held by the public totaling $3.6 trillion. The rest of the debt, some $2
trillion, is held by the government's large trust funds, primarily the Social
Security trust fund.
</P>
<P>
	   Summers noted that under current surplus forecasts, the entire $3.6 trillion
in debt held by the public could be eliminated over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
	   However, private economists caution that those long-range projections are
based on assumptions that the current good economic times, which have triggered
the swelling revenues, continue and that Democrats and Republicans resist the
urge to spend the surplus on new government programs or in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
	   Elimination of the $3.6 trillion of publicly-held debt would mark the first
time that the debt held by the public has been eliminated since President Andrew
Jackson accomplished the feat in 1835.
</P>
<P>
	   However, even if that goal is accomplished, it would still leave the sizable
$2 trillion in debt the government owes to the Social Security trust fund, money
that will be needed to finance the Baby Boomers' retirement.
</P>
<P>
	   Participants in financial markets offered general support for the debt
buyback approach.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The $30 billion was on the high side of market expectations and the
initial market reaction has been positive,'' said David Jones, chief economist
at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co., a government securities dealer in New York.
</P>
<P>
	   The amount of the national debt held by the public has been reduced over the
past two years by $140 billion, reflecting the fact that the government has
posted back-to-back surpluses over the last two years for the first time since
Dwight Eisenhower was president.
</P>
<P>
	   The extra cash allowed the Treasury to reduce outstanding debt simply by
selling fewer new bonds at its regularly scheduled auctions than the amount of
old bonds coming due.
</P>
<P>
	   That procedure will be employed again this year. But officials said the new
buyback procedure will allow them to better control the government's interest
costs by buying back longer maturities and substituting shorter-term maturities
with lower interest payments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 2206 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush: Use Money for Tax Cuts  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID ESPO AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. (AP) -- Sharpening their disagreement over tax cuts, George
W. Bush suggested Thursday that John McCain's proposal would leave too much
money for Congress to spend on ``bigger government,'' and McCain countered that
the Republican presidential front-runner's plan could lead to higher payroll
taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I must confess I am skeptical of appropriators,'' Bush said, referring to
members of the House and Senate committees that write multibillion-dollar
spending bills annually.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Somehow I have trouble believing that they're going to necessarily spend
it on debt reduction,'' the Texas governor said of the surplus funds that would
be left after McCain's tax cut took effect. ``I worry they may spend it on
bigger government.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's tax cut, $483 billion over five years, would leave the Social
Security surplus alone, but spend from non-Social Security surplus funds.
McCain, in a written statement, said that wasn't enough, that a larger amount of
non-Social Security surplus funds must be set aside to make sure the retirement
program is protected.
</P>
<P>
	   ``By not shoring up the Social Security system now with surplus funds we
are, by fiat, agreeing to raise payroll taxes in the future,'' added McCain,
whose own plan is roughly half the size of Bush's. I have called this kind of
economics ``fiscally irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was defending his plan in a new 30-second ad beginning Thursday night
in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   And in comments later to reporters, McCain said that his was a conservative
approach. ``I think it's conservative to pay down the debt and save Social
Security'' and shore up Medicare, as well as cutting taxes, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The two men never crossed paths during the day as they made their campaign
rounds a little more than two weeks in advance of the nation's first
presidential primary, set for Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   But their cross-state sparring underscored the extent to which the campaign
is settling into a disagreement over tax cuts, an issue that has divided
Republicans for the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
	   Two new public opinion polls released during the day pointed to a close race
in New Hampshire between the two Sun Belt political figures, but disagreed on
which man held the lead. One survey said it was Bush, the Texas governor who is
the national front-runner by far. The other said it was McCain, running an
insurgent's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush did not mention that Republicans hold a majority in Congress, and he
made no other comments during the day that implied criticism of the
congressional wing of his party.
</P>
<P>
	   He made his remarks midway through a full day of campaigning that took him
from a high tech factory in Laconia to a lunchtime speech in this coastal city
to a town hall meeting in Londonderry before flying off to Iowa, which holds
caucuses eight days before New Hampshire votes.
</P>
<P>
	   During the town hall meeting, Bush bristled at the suggestion from someone
in the crowd that he had a ``drug past.'' The Texas governor has refused to
directly answer questions about whether he has used illegal drugs, except to say
he has not since 1974.
</P>
<P>
	   A man who said he was Sanho Tree of the Institute for Policy Studies, a
Washington think tank, asked the governor for his perspective on the war on
drugs ``from your own drug past.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Sir, sit down please,'' Bush said. ``You're making an assumption about me
that you have -- you really don't know what you're talking about. I don't accept
that assumption.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush told the man that ``what you need to know about is, should I swear in,
I'm going to bring honor and dignity to the office.'' He added, ``You shouldn't
fall prey to rumors and gossip.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush is campaigning as the outsider in the race, and he told reporters
during the day one of the key issues will be ``executive experience'' versus
``Washington legislative experience,'' an obvious reference to McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the Republican establishment's embrace was evident during
the day. Judd Gregg, who sits on the Senate Appropriations Committee, and Rep.
Charles Bass spent part of the day with Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has repeatedly accused Bush of advocating a tax cut that is too large
and risks harm to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
	   In remarks before a Rotary Club and afterward to reporters, the front-runner
seemed eager to keep the argument alive.
</P>
<P>
	   He lumped McCain and Vice President Al Gore together as the only ``two
voices'' in the campaign to say his own tax cut was too bold.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, McCain accuses Bush of providing overly generous relief
for the wealthy, echoing criticisms that Democrats frequently level at GOP tax
plans.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor took that issue head-on at several points during the day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's fair to cut the taxes on everybody if you're going to cut taxes at
all,'' he said to the Rotarians. At a news conference afterward, he re-enforced
his plan to cut the top tax rate.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said his plan would stimulate the economy as well as return money to
the taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the money lies around the halls of Washington it's going to be spent,''
he said at one point. ``Appropriators appropriate,'' he said at another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
