<HEADLINE> Samoa Death Sentence Commuted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- The death sentence of a man who pleaded
guilty to the assassination of a Samoan Cabinet minister has been commuted to
life in prison, sources close to the head of state said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Samoan head of state, Malietoa Tanumafili II, commuted 34-year-old
Alatise Vitale Leafa's death sentence, sources told The Associated Press on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
	   Alatise Vitale will be a state prosecution witness next week when his
father, former Cabinet minister Leafa Vitale, and another former Cabinet
minister, Toi Aukusa, go to trial for the same murder -- of Public Works
Minister Luagalau Levaula Kamu. He was shot to death last July.
</P>
<P>
	   Alatise Vitale later pleaded guilty to the murder and was sentenced to death
by hanging.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Samoa retains the death penalty, it has not been enforced since the
modern Samoan state was founded in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
	   Samoa is 2,300 miles southwest of Hawaii.
</P>
</TEXT>
