<HEADLINE> Jordan King Appoints New Top Aide  </HEADLINE>
   By JAMAL HALABY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Jordan's King Abdullah II on Thursday appointed as his
top aide a confidant of his late father and a proponent of Jordan's 1994 peace
treaty with Israel, the state-run Jordan Television reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Fayez Tarawneh, 52, replaces Abdul-Karim Kabariti, who resigned last month
amid speculation of a deep rift between him and Prime Minister Abdur-Ra'uf S.
Rawabdeh.
</P>
<P>
	   The television said Abdullah, 37, issued a royal decree appointing Tarawneh
as the chief of the Royal Court, a post that has often been a stepping stone to
the prime ministership.
</P>
<P>
	   Tarawneh had earlier served as prime minister under Abdullah's father, the
late King Hussein, who died of cancer on Feb. 7. When Abdullah succeeded
Hussein, he removed Tarawneh. The move was largely seen as an attempt by
Abdullah to assert his independence rather than a reflection on Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
	   Tarawneh, who led Jordan's negotiating team in peace talks with Israel for
two years ending in 1994, also served as a royal court chief under Hussein for
six months. Known for his liberal views, Tarawneh was Jordan's ambassador to the
United States in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, the official Petra news agency said Prime Minister Rawabdeh would
shuffle his Cabinet on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Petra said Rawabdeh has instructed all his 23 ministers to submit their
resignations in line with a formality that allows the king, the ultimate
authority in the kingdom, to approve a new Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
	   But government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said key
portfolios like foreign affairs, information, finance and planning are unlikely
to be changed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
