<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose at midday Friday after a robust earnings
report from Intel boosted technology share prices. The U.S. dollar rose against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 29.76 points, or 0.16
percent, to 18,863.05 at the end of the morning trading session. On Thursday,
the average closed up 155.87 points, or 0.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. dollar was trading at 106.19 yen on the Tokyo foreign exchange
market, up from 105.66 yen late Thursday and above its late New York level of
106.13.
</P>
<P>
	   In stock trading, U.S. computer chip maker Intel said fourth quarter
earnings rose 17 percent from the same period last year to $2.4 billion, sending
Sony and other Japanese technology stocks higher.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it will be a fairly positive day," said Robert Sasaki, head of
quantitative strategy group at Jardine Fleming Securities. "I think Intel will
kick up more focus on high-tech issues, or the so-called 'new Japan' stocks."
</P>
<P>
	   Tokyo stocks had risen as much as 192 points in the morning session, but
pared some of the gains after Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan expressed
concerns that growing imbalances between consumer demand and the supply of
available workers could derail the U.S. economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
	   On Wall Street, before Greenspan's speech, the Dow Jones industrial average
rose 31.33 points on Thursday to a record 11,582.43 after a report of relatively
modest inflation calmed jittery stock investors.
</P>
<P>
	   The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index broke out of a two-day slump to
finish up 107.19 at 3,957.21.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section rose 0.55 points, or 0.03 percent, to 1,658.52. On Thursday, the TOPIX
rose 1.05 points, or 0.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency trading, the dollar rose after U.S. sales and price data showed
that the U.S. economy is growing at a steady pace with no danger of a sharp rise
in inflation, traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar earlier rose as high as 106.28, but fell back somewhat after
Greenspan said that the U.S. central bank can't afford to wait for signs of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
	   That raised concerns that the U.S. Federal Open Market Committee will
increase interest rates to slow the economy at its meeting in early February,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 108.82 yen, down from 108.84 yen
late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.8000
percent from 1.7950 percent on Thursday. The bond's price fell 0.04 point to
100.84.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
