<HEADLINE> Ala. KKK Probed for Web Site Threat  </HEADLINE>
   By RON HARRIST Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Mississippi Attorney General Mike Moore said his
office is contacting state authorities after discovering an Alabama Klan group's
Web site declared Moore had ``earned a death sentence.''
</P>
<P>
	   Moore, perhaps best known for his role in suing the tobacco industry, has
recently helped to bring to trial several murder cases dating back to the
state's civil rights struggle.
</P>
<P>
	   A group calling itself the Alabama White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan railed
against Moore in an article on its Web site glorifying onetime Mississippi Klan
chieftain Sam Bowers. Bowers is serving a life prison term for the 1966 murder
of Vernon Dahmer, an NAACP leader and black voting rights advocate.
</P>
<P>
	   The article calls Moore ``the cynical and politically ambitious Mississippi
Attorney General'' for his prosecution of Bowers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is our opinion it is Moore who has earned the death sentence for
treason against the white race,'' the article said.
</P>
<P>
	   Moore said his office is contacting Alabama authorities and may work with
federal authorities on the matter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have to take these things seriously but, honestly, I'm not afraid of
cowards who dress up in robes,'' Moore said Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
