<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thursday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Note: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Heart Institute Rejects Keon Resignation Over Hooker Incident
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- The University of Ottawa Heart Institute wants renowned
surgeon Wilbert Keon to stay on as director and chief operating officer despite
an embarrassing arrest during a police prostitution sweep.
</P>
<P>
	   The institute's board of directors voted unanimously Thursday to reject the
resignation tendered last month by Keon and ask him to resume his duties, said
chairman Gordon Ritchie.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Support for Dr. Keon was total,'' Ritchie told a news conference, saying
none of the 15 members spoke against him at a two-hour, closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately clear whether Keon, who did not attend the meeting,
would heed the board's advice and withdraw his resignation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He has asked for a few days to reflect and decide on his future,'' said
Ritchie.
</P>
<P>
	   Keon was not at his medical office Thursday and could not be reached at
home. Hospital officials said they do not expect a decision from him until next
week.
</P>
<P>
	   The famed surgeon, who also serves as a Conservative senator, resigned
shortly before Christmas after he was caught in a ``compromising situation''
with an undercover police officer posing as a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
	   Doer, Ventura To Meet on Water Diversion Plans
</P>
<P>
	   WINNIPEG (AP) -- Manitoba Premier Gary Doer is teaming up with Minnesota
Governor Jesse Ventura to battle two water diversion projects planned by North
Dakota.
</P>
<P>
	   Doer called Ventura a powerful partner in the drive to protect Canadian
waters from possible contamination by the projects, and the two planned to meet
in St. Paul, Minn., Friday to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
	   The Minnesota governor has been an outspoken opponent of the projects on
environmental grounds.
</P>
<P>
	   North Dakota wants two controversial water diversion projects built.
</P>
<P>
	   One is a modified form of the Garrison diversion project, defeated once by
Canada more than 10 years ago, which would channel water from the Missouri and
Mississippi rivers north.
</P>
<P>
	   The other is a new plan to divert water out of Devils Lake to ease flooding.
</P>
<P>
	   Manitoba is concerned about the foreign fish species and other organisms
that might be transferred into its waterways and also about the quality of the
water that will find its way north.
</P>
<P>
	   Court Says Francophones Entitled to French School
</P>
<P>
	   OTTAWA (AP) -- Children of a small Francophone community in P.E.I. have won
the right to be educated in French in a decision that supports French and
English minority rights enshrined in the charter.
</P>
<P>
	   An unanimous Supreme Court of Canada decision Thursday sided with
Francophone parents in Summerside who want the province to pay for French
elementary education in the community.
</P>
<P>
	   The court reaffirmed the purpose of Section 23 of the Charter of Rights and
Freedoms, which says children of English- or French-language minority
communities have the right to have publicly funded education in their language
where the numbers warrant.
</P>
<P>
	   The law, said the court, ``mandates that provincial governments do whatever
is practically possible to preserve and promote minority language
education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 2233 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
