<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Morocco Ministers Meet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RABAT, Morocco (AP) -- Morocco wants to raise the level of its relations with
Israel, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said Thursday after meeting his
Moroccan counterpart during a four-day visit.
</P>
<P>
	   Both countries share a ``mutual desire'' to build upon their current
low-level diplomatic relations, said Levy, adding that he doesn't know when
Morocco might be prepared to do so.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It could be soon. I can't say how much time or how many days,'' he told
Israeli Army Radio. ``But it is certainly a mutual desire, not only ours, and it
will all be done in time and out of a determination to do it.''
</P>
<P>
	   Levy met Thursday with Mohamed Benaissa, part of a visit that suggests that
Morocco is not about to forgo its discreet but important role in the Middle East
peace process -- despite the death of King Hassan II in July. The late monarch
broke Arab world taboos to hold secret talks with Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
	   The trip is the first official Israeli visit to Morocco since Mohammed VI,
Hassan's son, came to power in July.
</P>
<P>
	   It is also a sort of emotional homecoming for Levy, who was born in Morocco.
Meeting with Andre Azoulay, an adviser to the king, he discussed the Jewish
community of Morocco, the state news agency MAP reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel's Channel Two TV reported that Mohammed VI invited Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak to visit Morocco during Wednesday's meeting. It said Levy
also extended an invitation to the king to visit Israel.
</P>
<P>
	   Levy was scheduled Friday to meet in Rabat with other members of the Jewish
community and in the evening attend Sabbath services in the central synagogue.
</P>
</TEXT>
