<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Excerpts from Gonzalez Interview  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Excerpts from Chris Wallace's interview with Juan Miguel Gonzalez, father of
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, on ABC News' ``Nightline,'' as transcribed by the
network:
</P>
<P>
	   Q. Mr. Gonzalez, there is a story in the Miami Herald that says that you
don't work anymore, that you don't live in your own home and it even says that
you are under psychiatric treatment. How much of that is true, sir?
</P>
<P>
	   A. ... I will just say that all of that is a lie. I am still working. I
continue living in my home and I am under no type of psychiatric treatment.
Perhaps I might be a little bit crazy because I would feel like breaking the
neck of all those SOBs ... starting with all of those politicians in Miami and
those who, you know, have behaved in a manner that is contrary to what our
relatives should have done, they do not take into account that this is only a
6-year-old child. The problem is suffering that both the child as well as all of
his relatives here are going through simply because of political reasons and
also because of money.
</P>
<P>
	   Q. The implication of this is that you are under the control of the Cuban
government and therefore not free to speak you own mind.
</P>
<P>
	   A. ... I have been under absolutely no pressure from anybody here. I have
always said with everybody I have had interviews with, the INS, journalists,
etc., with total freedom, I have been the one who has been exerting pressure on
the government to get a response, ... and they have not sent my child back to
me.
</P>
<P>
	   Q. It has been suggested ... that the reason you do not come to Miami is
because the Cuban government is afraid once you get to Miami, you will defect.
</P>
<P>
	   A. Who said that? ... People think, or some people think, that I am under
pressure here. I have always said I haven't lost anything in Miami, and
sometimes what I would like to do is go down there with a rifle -- I don't know
-- to get rid of how many people. ... And what about -- isn't it inflammatory
what they are doing with my son? ... I think the main thing is to send my child
back to me as soon as possible ... It's almost -- been almost two months that I
haven't seen my son, that he's away from me, and this has been always my main
interest.
</P>
<P>
	   A. Do you see the pictures of him from Miami, for instance waving the
congressional subpoena and giving the ``V'' for victory sign?
</P>
<P>
	   A. ... This is child abuse. He is being made to do things against his will
because if he were able to say or to defend Fidel (Castro), he would do it. ...
He told me over the phone that he is dreaming about coming back to me to be with
him, to be with me, and they are manipulating what he is saying and saying
things that are untrue. ... I would like to express my gratitude to Janet Reno,
the attorney general, and I would like to ask her please to do whatever is
possible for them to send my son back to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
