<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Avoids Possible Walkout  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SEATTLE (AP) -- The Boeing Co. and the union representing its engineers and
technical workers reached a tentative contract agreement Thursday, narrowly
avoiding a proposed walkout that had been set for Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   After both sides met for nearly seven hours, the union won concessions on
four of five major issues, said Charles Bofferding, executive director of the
Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
	   "The membership solidarity and dedication prompted The Boeing Co. to make
significant changes in the contract," Bofferding said in a release. An earlier
offer contact offer was rejected Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   "We held the line on benefits, we protected the weekends and we reduced the
length of the contract from four to three years."
</P>
<P>
	   The revised offer still needs to be approved by the SPEEA membership. Voting
could begin as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Boeing hailed the offer as one worthy of SPEEA members' full consideration.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is one of the fairest packages offered to any bargaining unit in the
country," Geoff Stamper, Boeing's director of union relations and chief
negotiator in the talks, said in a release.
</P>
<P>
	   The offer did not include a guaranteed general wage increase for the
engineers, but the union did win total increases of 8 percent the first year,
4.5 percent the second year, and 4.5 percent the final year to the pools of
money available for engineer wage increases, SPEEA said.
</P>
<P>
	   The pools of money available for technical employees wage increases are 5.5
percent, 4.5 percent and 4.5 percent, with 3 percent guaranteed in the first
year and 2 percent guaranteed in the final year.
</P>
<P>
	   The new offer also includes a reduction in the contract length from four to
three years.
</P>
<P>
	   SPEEA represents nearly 23,000 scientists, engineers, computer programmers,
manual writers and other technical workers in the Puget Sound region, Spokane
and Portland, Ore. Included are more than 13,000 dues-paying union members.
</P>
<P>
	   The 50-year-old union, the second largest at Boeing behind the machinists,
has never had a full-scale strike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
