<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Animation Pioneer Davis Dies  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GERMAIN AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GLENDALE, Calif. (AP) -- Cartoonist Marc Davis, one of the ``nine old men''
who made up the core of Walt Disney's crack animation staff and the lead
designer of Tinker Bell, Bambi and Cruella De Vil, has died. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis died Wednesday at Glendale Memorial Hospital in suburban Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
	   He had been one of four surviving members of the key animators Walt Disney
assembled to work on his studio's cartoon features beginning with ``Snow White
and the Seven Dwarfs'' in 1937.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis and his colleagues were dubbed the ``nine old men'' by Disney, who
compared them to Franklin Roosevelt's Supreme Court appointees, said Ollie
Johnston, another of the nine.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Walt said, 'Hey, I've got my nine guys, and they're all over the hill,
too,' even though we were only in our 30s and 40s,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis was the best artist of the bunch, Johnston said. ``The others were
excellent draftsmen, but Marc had the ability to take things and make them into
fine art,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis attended art schools in Kansas City, San Francisco and Los Angeles
before becoming an apprentice animator for Disney in 1935. He was an assistant
animator on ``Snow White,'' then took the lead on developing the animals for
``Bambi,'' including the title character and Thumper.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis became something of a specialist on designing female characters,
including Alice for ``Alice in Wonderland,'' Tinker Bell for ``Peter Pan,''
Briar Rose, the princess from ``Sleeping Beauty,'' and two classic villainesses,
Maleficent from ``Sleeping Beauty'' and Cruella from ''101 Dalmatians.''
</P>
<P>
	   Later, he designed concepts and characters for such Disney theme-park
attractions as ``Pirates of the Caribbean,'' ``It's a Small World'' and ``Jungle
Cruise.''
</P>
<P>
	   He retired in 1978 but remained a design consultant for Disney theme parks.
</P>
<P>
	   Davis is survived by his wife, Alice. No funeral service was planned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 2301 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000113.0382 </DOCNO>
