<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Rebels Renew Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Rebels on Thursday renewed a three-month humanitarian
cease-fire in war-torn areas of southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
	   The new cease-fire will take effect Saturday when the current one expires,
the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
	   The SPLA was renewing the cease-fire due to the ``prevailing hunger induced
by the combination of war and natural causes such as alternating drought and
floods,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   The cease-fire covers western Bahr el Ghazal, where fighting has been halted
for more than a year on humanitarian grounds, and also in the Western Upper Nile
and Central Upper Nile regions of southern Sudan, where government troops have
been fighting rebel forces, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
	   Rebels in the predominantly Christian and animist south want increased
autonomy and development in their region, which has been traditionally neglected
under the government in the Muslim and Arab north.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly 2 million people have been killed since the civil war began in 1983.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-13-00 2301 </TRAILER>
