<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Campaigning for Bush  </HEADLINE>
   By WALTER R. MEARS AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTIC, Iowa (AP) -- Former President Bush campaigned for his son the
front-runner on Thursday, telling Iowa Republicans that George W. learned at his
side and would ``be excellent at doing what I tried to do'' to unite Americans
at home and allies abroad.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the former president's first vote-hunting mission of the 2000
presidential campaign, in territory where he both won and lost as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   Father, like son, talked about Barbara Bush, and joked that he was tired of
always being asked where she was. ``I used to be president, you know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``She's working her heart out for our son,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   While helping the son, Bush said, ``I will have nothing bad to say against
any of the people that he is campaigning against right now.''
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, he said that when he left the White House he vowed not even to
criticize President Clinton, the man who beat him in 1992. He said it would have
been ``sort of sour grapes, bad loser.''
</P>
<P>
	   Still, he did slip in a taunting reminder of the sex scandal that led to
Clinton's impeachment, saying that the Jenny Craig diet people had called to ask
him whether he wanted to lose 30 pounds. Monica Lewinsky said she did, and has
signed on as a representative of the organization.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's speech to an overflow crowd of more than 500 people at the Atlantic
High School auditorium was generally low key. He said he spoke on the basis of
his experience as a president and as a father.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, in Des Moines, Bush addressed nearly 1,400 people at an annual
Chamber of Commerce dinner, ``a nonpolitical event at a highly politicized time
of the year in Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said he'd respect the bipartisan ground rules. ``Though I might be
tempted to utter a few words of encouragement to anyone who is considering
supporting my boy,'' he said, ``I will heed the immortal words of Dana Carvey.
'Not gonna do it. Wouldn't be prudent.'''
</P>
<P>
	   Carvey is the comic who used those lines in Bush parodies. ``A lot of guys
don't miss me in Washington, but there's one guy who does,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   Texas Gov. Bush leads the public opinion polls in Iowa by margins of 25
points and more over Steve Forbes in preferences for the Jan. 24 caucuses that
will begin the 2000 voting. Sen. John McCain, Bush's closest challenger
nationally, is not competing in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I can tell you in Iowa organization counts,''' the former president told
reporters. ``I came in here as asterisk ... but I won.'' That was in 1980, when
he upset Ronald Reagan in Iowa. Then Bush said, ``I got dusted by Reagan in New
Hampshire.'' Nominated, Reagan made Bush his vice president.
</P>
<P>
	   Eight years later, Bush was the upset victim, running third in Iowa but
winning the White House anyhow.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said George W. was with him in four national campaigns, learning in the
process. ``You know presidential politics is not very pleasant, it's not very
civil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He knows it's tough,'' Bush said. ``He's seasoned enough to take criticism
and seasoned enough not to make mistakes when somebody writes something personal
about you.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think the American people are tired of divisiveness,'' Bush said. ``I
think George has demonstrated an ability to bring people together.'' He said his
son had done that better than other Republicans, including ``certainly, his
Dad.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush recalled the fall of the Berlin Wall, the disintegration of the old
Soviet Union, the Persian Gulf War, all during his one term as president.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All around that four-year period George was at my side during a lot of
this,'' he said. ``I think he'd be excellent at doing what I tried to do as
president in building coalitions.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``You can't do it alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We'd better get somebody who's knowledgeable enough and concerned enough
to get good people around him to be able to cope with problems and work with
others, build coalitions. ...''
</P>
<P>
	   So, he said, ``without criticizing anybody else ... I would simply suggest
that if you take a look at Texas, our candidate did what he said he would do ...
kept his word.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said he hopes uncommitted Iowa Republicans will recognize that when
they vote in the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
	   Then he reminisced, wryly, about his own defeat in 1992. He said Clinton
made the economy a winning issue, even though the Republican administration
``handed him an economy that was doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``But I wasn't clear about that,'' he said. ``People wanted change, change,
change, and people want change today.
</P>
<P>
	   ``And I think that my son has the opportunity to represent change.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bush has appeared at private fund-raising receptions for George W., but the
Iowa outing, in Atlantic and later at a Des Moines dinner, was his first
outright campaigning. ``He'll be on the road more for his son,'' said Karl Rove,
political director of the Bush campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
