<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-13 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Surplus Lower in 1999  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China's trade surplus shrank by a third from the previous
year to $29.1 billion in 1999, according to revised customs figures reported
Friday by state-run media.
</P>
<P>
	   The total is slightly less than the $30 billion estimate given by the
National Bureau of Statistics late last year, and a 33.3 percent decline from
the $43.6 billion surplus recorded in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Exports rose 6.1 percent last year to $194.9 billion, while imports soared
18.2 percent to $165.8 billion, the official China Daily newspaper reported the
revised statistics as showing.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Bureau of Statistics had reported 1999 imports at $165 billion
and exports at $195 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   More than three quarters of last year's total trade surplus came from a
$22.5 billion trade gap with the United States, according to a separate report
in the International Business Daily, which is published by China's foreign trade
ministry.
</P>
<P>
	   That figure is 7.1 percent higher than the $21 billion trade surplus with
the United States that China reported for 1998, which means growth in the gap
has tapered off from the 28 percent jump in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Exports to the United States totaled $42.0 billion in 1999, the paper
reported, up 10.6 percent from the $37.98 billion in U.S. exports China recorded
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Imports from the United States reached $19.5 billion in 1999, 15.0 percent
higher than in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
